const HEXAGRAMAS_EN = [
  [1,"The Creative",["creation", "force", "heaven", "origin", "pure yang"],"The Creative works sublime success, furthering through perseverance. The creative principle. Sublime success. Continuing is favorable. HEAVEN. Let a GREATER SACRIFICE be performed. A FAVORABLE ORACLE. According to the original meaning, the attributes (sublimity, potential for success, power to further, and perseverance) are grouped in pairs. When a person obtains this oracle, it means that success will be given from the most basic depths of the universe and that everything depends on how one seeks happiness — one's own and that of others. This search for happiness can only be accomplished by persevering in what is right. The specific meanings of the four attributes were debated from the very origin. The Chinese word used here for 'sublime' literally means 'head,' 'origin,' or 'great.' Therefore, Confucius says in explaining this sign: 'Great indeed is the generative power of the creative; all beings owe their beginning to this power. This power is present throughout all heaven.' This is so because this principle contains the other three as well. The beginning of all things lies still in the beyond, as an idea that has yet to become reality. However, the creative is capable of giving form to these archetypes of ideas. This is indicated by the word 'success' and by the fact that the process is represented by an image of nature. 'The clouds pass and the rain does its work and all individual beings flow into their forms.' Applied to the world of human relationships, these attributes show the superior person the path to achieving remarkable success: Since the superior person sees causes and effects with great clarity, they complete the six steps at the appropriate time and ascend toward heaven at the optimal moment, as if they were six dragons. The six steps are the six distinct positions in the hexagram, which are later represented by the symbol of the dragon. Here it is demonstrated that the path to success lies in assimilating and enacting the walk of the universe, the Tao, which — as a law running from beginning to end — makes all phenomena occur at the proper time. Thus each step taken forward is a preparation for the next. Time is no longer an obstacle but the means by which what is a possibility becomes reality. To the act of creation, expressed in the attributes of sublimity and success, is added the work of conservation, which presents itself as a constant updating and differentiation of form. This is expressed in two terms: 'favorable' — that is, the condition that makes a thing or person favorable or inclined to do something — and 'persevering' — that is, firm in doing what is right. 'The course of the creative alters and shapes beings until each one attains its true and specific nature, then it maintains them in conformity with the Great Harmony. In this way it shows itself as favorable through perseverance, as favorable thanks to perseverance.' Regarding the sphere of human activity, it demonstrates how the superior person brings peace and security to the world through their creative activity of ordering: 'The superior person stands far above the multitude of beings, and all lands are united in peace.' Another line of reflection goes further by separating the words 'sublime,' 'success,' 'favorable,' and 'perseverance' and establishing parallels between those attributes and the four cardinal virtues of humanity. The sublime, which as a fundamental principle encompasses all other attributes, is linked with love. Success is linked with customs and morality, which regulate and organize the expressions of love and, consequently, make them successful. The favorable is related to justice, which creates the conditions for each to receive what corresponds to their being, what should be given, and what constitutes their happiness. The attribute of perseverance is correlated with wisdom, which discerns the immutable laws by which all things pass and can, consequently, generate lasting conditions. This line of thought, already present in the commentary called Wen Yan, later formed the bridge that connected the philosophy of the 'five stages (elements) of change,' as set forth in the Book of History (Shu Ching), with the philosophy of the Book of Changes (I Ching), based exclusively on the polarity between the positive and negative principles. In the course of time, this combination of two systems of thought opened the way to an increasingly intricate numerical symbolism.","The movement of Heaven is full of power. Thus the superior person makes themselves strong and untiring. Since there is only one heaven, the duplication of the trigram Ch'ien, of which heaven is the image, indicates the movement of heaven. A complete revolution of heaven makes one day, and the repetition of the trigram means that each day is followed by another. This creates the idea of time. Since it is the same heaven with untiring movement, the idea of duration is also established, both in time and beyond time — a movement that never stops nor delays, just as one day follows the next in an endless becoming. This duration in time is the image of the power inherent in the creative. With this image as model, the sage is able to define the best path for developing themselves so that their influence endures. The superior person must strengthen themselves in every way, achieving this by banishing all that is inferior and degrading. Thus the superior person attains the condition of untiringness that depends on consciously limiting the fields of their activity. 1. The creative dragon. Design and create your own life. What are your goals? How can you reach them? The wise dragon says 'yes' to life. Be a winner! Walk untiringly on the path of all-embracing love. Supreme success."],
  [2,"The Receptive",["earth", "receptivity", "nourishment", "pure yin", "support"],"The Receptive brings sublime success, furthering through the perseverance of a mare. If the superior person undertakes something and tries to lead, they go astray; but if they follow, they find guidance. It is favorable to find friends in the west and south, and to set aside friends in the east and north. Quiet perseverance brings good fortune. The receptive element brings sublime success. The symbol of a mare. At first, one leads and loses; afterward, one follows and receives support. Friends in the west and south, not in the east and north. A peaceful continuation is beneficial. EARTH. Let a GREATER SACRIFICE be performed. The ORACLE of a MARE is FAVORABLE. The NOBLE PERSON PROCEEDS WITH a PURPOSE. You might, at FIRST, LOSE your WAY; But AFTERWARD, you WILL GAIN a MASTER. FAVORABLE. You WILL GAIN a FRIEND in the SOUTHWEST, you WILL LOSE a FRIEND in the NORTHEAST. The ORACLE of PEACE is AUSPICIOUS. The four fundamental aspects of the creative — 'sublime success, favorable through perseverance' — also belong to the receptive. In this case, however, perseverance is defined more precisely: it is the perseverance of a mare. The receptive denotes a spatial reality in contrast to the spiritual potentiality of the creative. Potential becomes reality and the spiritual acquires spatial dimensions through a specific qualifying definition. Thus, the qualification 'of a mare' is added to the idea of perseverance. The horse belongs to the earth as the dragon belongs to heaven. Its tireless coming and going across the plains is a symbol of the vastness of the earth. This symbol is chosen because the mare combines the strength and speed of a horse with the gentleness and devotion of a cow. Only because nature, in its millions of forms, corresponds to the millions of impulses of the creative can it make these impulses real. The richness of nature lies in its power to nourish all living beings; its greatness lies in its power to give them beauty and splendor. Thus all that lives prospers. It is the creative that creates things, but the receptive brings them to life. Applied to human affairs, what the hexagram indicates is action in conformity with the situation. The person in question is not in an independent position. They act as an assistant. This means that the person must accomplish something. It is not their task to try to lead. That would only make them lose their way. What they must do is let themselves be guided. The person does not advance blindly but learns from the situation what is expected of them and then follows this indication of destiny. Since there is something to be done, we need friends and helpers at the time of work and effort, once ideas have been clearly defined. The time of work and effort is indicated by the west and south, for west and south represent the place where the receptive works for the creative, as nature does in summer and autumn. If in that situation one does not mobilize all one's powers, the work to be done will not be accomplished. Hence, to find friends, one must find guidance and direction. In addition to this time of work and effort, it is also necessary to plan, and therefore solitude is needed. The east symbolizes the place where a person receives orders from their superior, and the north the place where they report what they have done. In that time, the person must be alone and remain objective. In this sacred hour they must live without companions, so that the purity of the moment is not ruined by fictitious hatreds or preferences.","The condition of Earth is Giving while receiving. Thus the superior person, the one who possesses greatness of character, sustains the outer world. Just as there is only one heaven, so there is only one earth. In the hexagram Heaven, the duplication of the trigram implies duration in time, but in the hexagram Earth, the duplication implies solidity and extension in space, for the earth sustains and preserves all things that live and move upon it. The earth, in its devotion — that is, in its surrender, in its giving of itself — sustains all things, good and bad, without exception. Just as the superior person enlarges their character, purifies themselves, and gains power to sustain themselves, they are also able to sustain and support people and things. 8. The field. The sage concentrates on their goals and finds their way to those goals by being flexible, by flowing like water in a field, which is what allows them to overcome obstacles. The sage does what is possible and triumphs through perseverance. What are your goals? What is your path to victory? Forward. Great success. THE DIFFERENT LINES At the beginning a six means: When there is frost underfoot, solid ice is not far off. Frost underfoot, solid ice then arrives. You WALK upon FROST. SOLID ICE ARRIVES. Just as the life-giving power represents life, the dark power, the gloomy, represents death. When the first frost falls in autumn, the power of darkness and cold is nascent. After this first warning, signs of death will gradually multiply, until, according to immutable laws, the raw winter with its ice arrives. In life the same thing happens. After a few barely perceptible signs of decay appear, the process continues until final dissolution occurs. But in life it is possible to take precautions to control the first signs of decay and address them in time. 9. Difficulties. The frost in the field indicates that ice is near. The sage walks a difficult path. You triumph through perseverance and wisdom. Six in the second place means: Straight, square, great. Without purpose, and yet nothing remains unbenefited. Straight, broad, great. Without purpose and yet achieves — STRAIGHT, SQUARE and GREAT: Even WITHOUT REVIEW, NOTHING that does NOT end FAVORABLY. The symbol of Heaven is the circle and that of Earth is the square. Thus squareness is a primary quality of the earth. On the other hand, movement in a straight line, also as a magnitude, is a primary quality of the creative. But all square things have their origin in a straight line, and from that straight line they form solid bodies; rectangular planes, for example, are the result of straight lines, and cubic magnitudes are the product of rectangular planes. The receptive accommodates itself to the qualities of the creative and makes them its own. Thus a square develops from a straight line and a cube from a square. This results from the fulfillment of the laws of the creative. Nothing is subtracted, nothing enlarged. Therefore the receptive has no need for any special purpose or effort, and yet everything develops as it should be. Nature creates all beings without error; therein lies its condition of squareness. It tolerates all creatures equally. That is its condition of greatness. Consequently, it achieves what is right for all without artifice or special intentions. The person reaches the pinnacle of wisdom when everything they do is as self-evident and effortless as what nature does. 10. Change. Great transformation. Find your way by being flexible. Things will improve without enormous effort. Be receptive; it will guide you to success. Six in the third place means: Hidden lines. One can remain persevering. If perhaps you are in the service of a king, do not seek tasks; complete them. Concealing one's possibilities is correct. Outer activities will eventually prosper. PRESERVE your INTEGRITY and you MAY practice DIVINATION. PERHAPS you WILL ENTER the service of the KING. THE LACK of ACHIEVEMENT will COME to an END. If a person is free of vanity, they are able to conceal their abilities and avoid attracting attention too soon. Thus they can mature without disturbance. If conditions demand it, that person can enter public life, but even then they will do so with certain limitations. The sage gladly leaves fame to others. That person does not seek credit for things that have been done but wishes to liberate active forces — that is, they complete their tasks in a way that bears fruit in the future. 11. The hidden master. One must remain in the background. Speak little and act wisely. Do not display your special abilities. Act modestly and be a mother or father to all: 'I send light to… May all be happy! May the world be happy!' Success. Six in the fourth place means: A tied-up bag. No blame, no praise. A tied-up bag. No praise, no blame. The BAG has been TIED TIGHT. There is NO HARM NOR PRAISE. The dark element opens when it moves and closes when it rests. The strictest reserve is indicated here. The time is dangerous, for any kind of notoriety leads either to enmity with adversaries who cannot be fought if one challenges them, or to false recognition if one overcomes. Therefore the person must maintain reserve, whether in solitude or in the whirl of the world, for there too it is possible to hide well so that no one knows them. 12. Excessive control. You don't risk enough, so you receive no criticism, but neither praise. You could risk more; act with more courage. A mother is willing to fight like a lioness for the happiness of her children. Advance with courage. Six in the fifth place means: Yellow undergarment brings supreme good fortune. A yellow undergarment. The greatest fortune. A YELLOW GARMENT. An IMPORTANT and AUSPICIOUS ORACLE. Yellow is the color of the earth and of the middle. It is the symbol of what is reliable and genuine. The undergarment is modestly decorated and is the symbol of the reserve that nobles should keep in their performance. When someone is called to work in a preeminent position that is not independent of others, true success depends on the greatest discretion. The genuine condition of a person and the refinement that distinguishes them must not reveal themselves directly; they should express themselves only indirectly, as an effect of what is within. 13. The master's attire. You will receive as a prize the attire of the sovereign. You are a champion. You do your work well. Remain. Great praise! At the top a six means: Dragons fight in the meadow. Their blood is black and yellow. Dragons fly in open country. Their blood is black and yellow. DRAGONS BATTLE in the FIELD. Their BLOOD flows BLACK and YELLOW. At the top, the dark element must yield its position to the light. If it tries to maintain a position that does not belong to it and wishes to rule instead of serve, it attracts upon itself the fury of the powerful. A struggle thus occurs in which it is deposed, with damage, however, to both sides. The dragon, symbol of Heaven, comes to fight the false dragon that symbolizes the inflation of the earth principle. Deep blue is the color of Heaven; yellow is the color of the earth. Thus the flowing of black and yellow blood is a sign of an unnatural struggle in which both primary powers suffer harm. 14. Yin and Yang. Advance with the two powers Yin (serenity) and Yang (strength). You triumph by applying your feminine (water) and masculine (dragon) energies at the optimal moment. The supreme art of life can be expressed in the idea of living the optimal balance between activity and rest. Whoever works relaxed, happy in themselves, to achieve a happy world is strengthened more deeply in love and light. When all lines are six it means: Lasting perseverance is favorable. The ORACLE of ETERNITY is FAVORABLE. When the number six appears in all lines, the hexagram the receptive mutates into the hexagram the creative. By remaining loyal to what is right, it gains the power of permanence. There is in fact no advance, but neither does a retreat occur."],
  [3,"Difficulty at the Beginning",["beginning", "chaos", "germination", "perseverance", "difficulty"],"Difficulty at the Beginning works supreme success, furthering through perseverance. Nothing should be undertaken. It is favorable to appoint helpers. Difficulty is followed by great success. Difficulty followed by great success. Continuing on the path is rewarded. Remaining in what exists, not seeking what is new. Appointing princes offers advantage. DIFFICULTIES. Let a GREATER SACRIFICE be performed. A FAVORABLE ORACLE. DO NOT PROCEED WITH a PURPOSE. It is FAVORABLE to APPOINT feudal PRINCES. Times of growth are marked by difficulties. They are similar to the birth of a firstborn. But these difficulties are the result of the very profusion of what struggles to take form. Everything is in motion; consequently, if one perseveres there are prospects of great success, despite the existing risk. When it is a person's destiny to undertake these new beginnings, everything still lacks form, everything is in darkness. Hence one must be very careful, for any premature movement could bring disaster. Likewise, it is very important not to be alone; to overcome chaos one needs helpers. This does not mean, however, that one should look at everything passively. One must act and participate with inspiration and guidance.","Clouds and thunder: The image of Difficulty at the Beginning. Thus the superior person creates order out of confusion. Clouds and thunder are represented by defined decorative lines; this means that in the chaos of difficulty at the beginning, order is already implicit. Likewise the superior person must arrange and organize the nascent profusion of the beginning times, just as one untangles a skein of silk filaments and gives them form by working the threads. In order that one may find one's place in the infinitude of being, one must be able to separate and unite. 15. The beginning. There are difficulties at the start, but you can overcome them. The wise dragon advises you to be patient and persistent. Do not give up. Success comes to those who persevere. ○ Initial nine: Hesitation and hindrance. It is favorable to remain persevering. It is favorable to appoint helpers. Hesitation and hindrance. It is FAVORABLE to REMAIN PERSEVERING. It is FAVORABLE to APPOINT HELPERS. At the beginning of time, when the creative principle first manifests, everything is still in chaos. The creative force wants to push forward but encounters danger. Therefore there is hesitation and hindrance. But since the creative force is strong enough, it overcomes the hindrance through perseverance. However, since the danger is real, one should not rush forward alone. One needs helpers and assistants to overcome the obstacles. This is why it is favorable to appoint helpers. 16. The wise dragon at the beginning. You face difficulties at the start of a great project. Do not be discouraged. Seek help and persevere. Success is certain. Six in the second place means: Difficulties pile up. Horse and wagon part. He is not a robber; he wants to woo at the right time. The maiden is chaste, she does not pledge herself. Ten years — then she pledges herself. Difficulties pile up. HORSE and WAGON PART. He is NOT A ROBBER; he WANTS to WOO at the RIGHT TIME. The MAIDEN is CHASTE, she does NOT PLEDGE herself. TEN YEARS — then she PLEDGES herself. The creative force is still in the lower position and must push through obstacles. But it finds resonance in the ruling place. The obstacle is so strong that it seems to separate the creative force from its goal, as a wagon is separated from its horse. However, this is not a hostile robbery but a delay caused by the difficulty of the time. The creative force knows how to wait. It does not force things but waits for the right moment. The maiden remains faithful to her beloved and does not pledge herself to another. After ten years — when the cycle is complete — the union takes place. In times of difficulty at the beginning, one must wait patiently for the right moment. Force leads to failure. The right moment will come of itself. 17. Waiting for the right moment. The wise dragon advises patience. The obstacle will be overcome in due time. Do not force things. Six in the third place means: Whoever hunts deer without the forester only loses his way in the forest. The superior person understands the signs of the time and prefers to desist from pursuing the quarry. To continue brings humiliation. Whoever HUNTS DEER without the FORESTER only LOSES his WAY in the FOREST. The SUPERIOR PERSON understands the SIGNS of the TIME and PREFERS to DESIST from PURSUING the QUARRY. To CONTINUE brings HUMILIATION. The creative force is in a dangerous position. It wants to push forward but lacks the knowledge of the terrain. The forester is the one who knows the forest — that is, the one who knows the conditions of the time. Without this knowledge, one only loses one's way. The superior person understands this and prefers to wait rather than to act without guidance. In times of difficulty at the beginning, one should not act alone but seek the guidance of someone who knows the conditions. 18. Lost in the forest. You are in a difficult situation. Do not try to force your way through. Seek the guidance of someone more experienced. The wise dragon advises humility and patience. Six in the fourth place means: Horse and wagon part. Strive for union. To go brings good fortune. Everything acts favorably. HORSE and WAGON PART. STRIVE for UNION. To GO brings GOOD FORTUNE. Everything acts FAVORABLY. The creative force is separated from its goal, but the time of separation is coming to an end. The obstacle begins to yield. Now it is the moment to strive for union with the goal. Going brings good fortune because the creative force is strong enough to overcome the remaining obstacles. Everything acts favorably because the time of difficulty is passing. In times of difficulty at the beginning, there comes a moment when one must act decisively. The time of waiting is over. Now one must push forward with determination. 19. The union. The wise dragon advises you to strive for your goal. The time of difficulty is passing. Act with determination and success will come. Nine in the fifth place means: Difficulties in blessing. A little perseverance brings good fortune. Great perseverance brings misfortune. Difficulties in BLESSING. A little PERSEVERANCE brings GOOD FORTUNE. Great PERSEVERANCE brings MISFORTUNE. The creative force is in the position of honor. It has the power to overcome the difficulties. But the difficulties are still too great to be overcome completely by force. A little perseverance — that is, gentle and flexible persistence — brings good fortune because it allows one to work with the conditions of the time. Great perseverance — that is, rigid and forceful persistence — brings misfortune because it goes against the conditions of the time. In times of difficulty at the beginning, even when one is in a strong position, one must act with flexibility and gentleness. Force will only create more resistance. 20. Gentle persistence. The wise dragon advises flexibility. Do not try to overcome obstacles by force. Work with the conditions of the time. At the top a six means: Horse and wagon part. Bloody tears flow. HORSE and WAGON PART. BLOODY TEARS FLOW. The creative force is at the top of the hexagram. The time of difficulty at the beginning has reached its extreme. The creative force has no way to push forward and no way to retreat. It is in a position of extreme helplessness. The separation from the goal is complete. There is nothing to do but weep bloody tears. But even in this extreme situation, the creative force remains true to itself. It does not give up. It waits for the time to change. In times of difficulty at the beginning, there may be moments of extreme helplessness. But even in these moments, one must remain true to oneself and wait for the time to change. The creative force will find its way. 21. Bloody tears. The wise dragon advises you not to give up, even in the most difficult moments. The time will change. Remain true to yourself and wait for the right moment."],
  [4,"Youthful Folly",["youth", "learning", "teaching", "clarity", "seeking"],"Youthful folly has success. I do not seek the young fool; the young fool seeks me. At the first oracle I give an answer. If one asks two, three times, it is importunity. When one is importunate, I do not inform. Perseverance is favorable. Juvenile, immature, growth. Good fortune. I do not seek immature people, but if they come to me, I answer them. If they continue with immature questions, I remain silent. IGNORANCE. Let a SACRIFICE be performed. I did NOT SEEK the IGNORANT INFANT. The IGNORANT INFANT was the one who SOUGHT ME. When the FIRST DIVINATION, I SPOKE. To ask TWO or THREE times is to LACK RESPECT. When one LACKS RESPECT, I do NOT REVEAL a FAVORABLE ORACLE. In youth, being foolish is not bad. Despite everything, one can triumph. But one must find an expert teacher and treat them correctly. For this, first of all, one must accept one's inexperience and seek a teacher. Only modesty and diligence certify the willingness to learn, which results in a devout recognition of the teacher. The teacher must wait calmly until being sought. They should not offer themselves spontaneously. Only thus will teaching occur at the right time and correctly. The teacher's answer to the student's question must be clear and concrete, like the answer that a querent wishes to obtain from the oracle. Being so, one must accept the answer as the solution of the doubt, as a decision. Distrustful or thoughtless questions only bother the teacher, and the best they can do is to dismiss them, as the oracle, which only offers one answer and refuses itself before questions that denote doubt or try to test it. If perseverance is added, which does not cease until one punctually appropriates knowledge, a beautiful success is assured. The sign offers, then, useful counsel to both teacher and student.","At the foot of the mountain a spring rises: the image of Youth. Thus the superior person, through scrupulous action, sustains their character. The spring manages to flow and overcome obstacles by not hesitating to fill up the empty places before it and thus advance. In the same way, the sage acts with determination to cultivate their character. Everything that is human is originally good but tends to stray from its original nature and fall into error. The cause of this is contact with the outer world, which acts upon it with seductions and temptations. From this contact arise desires and passions that cloud the original clarity of the soul. The sage knows that character must be cultivated through constant care and attention. Like the spring that rises at the foot of the mountain and gradually fills the hollows before flowing onward, the sage fills the gaps in their character through study and reflection. 22. The spring at the foot of the mountain. The wise dragon advises you to cultivate your character with determination. Fill the gaps in your knowledge and do not hesitate to advance. Success comes to those who persevere. ○ Initial six: To make the foolish person develop, it is favorable to apply discipline. The fetters are placed to remove the disgraceful. To make the foolish person DEVELOP, it is FAVORABLE to APPLY DISCIPLINE. The FETTERS are placed to REMOVE the DISGRACEFUL. At the beginning of education, discipline is necessary. The foolish person is like a child who does not yet know the difference between right and wrong. Discipline provides the structure that allows learning to take place. The fetters are not meant to punish but to remove what is disgraceful — that is, to remove the bad habits that prevent learning. Discipline should be applied with firmness but also with love. Its purpose is not to crush the spirit but to guide it toward the right path. 23. Discipline. The wise dragon advises you to apply discipline in your life. Remove bad habits and cultivate good ones. Success comes to those who are disciplined. Nine in the second place means: To bear with fools in their stupidity. Taking a maiden and a son brings good fortune. The son is capable of managing the household. To BEAR with FOOLS in their STUPIDITY. Taking a MAIDEN and a SON brings GOOD FORTUNE. The SON is CAPABLE of MANAGING the HOUSEHOLD. The teacher is in a position of strength. They have the power to bear with the foolishness of the student. This is like a man who takes a maiden as his wife and accepts her shortcomings. The maiden, in turn, bears a son who is capable of managing the household. The teacher bears with the student's foolishness because they know that, in time, the student will develop into a capable person. The teacher's patience and tolerance are the key to successful education. 24. Patience with the foolish. The wise dragon advises patience and tolerance. Do not be discouraged by the foolishness of others. Bear with them and guide them gently. Six in the third place means: One should not take a maiden who, when she sees a man of bronze, does not possess herself. Nothing that would be favorable. One should NOT take a MAIDEN who, when she sees a MAN of BRONZE, does NOT POSSESS herself. Nothing FAVORABLE. The foolish person is in a dangerous position. They are attracted to the first person who comes along, like a maiden who loses herself when she sees a strong man. This is not a favorable situation. The foolish person must learn to distinguish between true teachers and false ones. They must not be swayed by appearances but must seek the one who truly has wisdom. 25. False attraction. The wise dragon advises you to be discerning. Do not be attracted by appearances. Seek the one who truly has wisdom. Six in the fourth place means: Entangled folly brings humiliation. ENTANGLED FOLLY brings HUMILIATION. The foolish person is trapped in their own foolishness. They are so far from the truth that they cannot even recognize their own condition. This is the most dangerous form of folly — the folly that does not know itself to be folly. The person in this situation is entangled in illusions and delusions. They cannot see the truth because they are surrounded by their own preconceptions and desires. The only way out is to recognize one's own foolishness and to seek help from a teacher. 26. Entangled in folly. The wise dragon advises you to recognize your own limitations. If you are trapped in illusions, seek the help of a teacher. Only by recognizing your foolishness can you begin to overcome it. Six in the fifth place means: Childlike folly brings good fortune. CHILDLIKE FOLLY brings GOOD FORTUNE. The foolish person in the position of honor is like a child who is willing to learn. This is the best form of folly, for it is close to wisdom. The child does not pretend to know what they do not know. They are open and receptive, willing to learn from everyone. This attitude brings good fortune because it allows the person to grow and develop. In times of youthful folly, the best attitude is that of the child — open, receptive, and willing to learn. 27. Childlike openness. The wise dragon advises you to approach learning with the openness of a child. Be willing to learn from everyone. Do not pretend to know what you do not know. At the top a nine means: In punishing folly it does not further one to commit transgressions. The only thing that furthers is to ward off transgressors. In PUNISHING FOLLY it does NOT further one to COMMIT TRANSGRESSIONS. The only thing that FURTHERS is to WARD OFF TRANSGRESSORS. The teacher is at the top of the hexagram. They have the power to punish the foolish. But punishment should not be excessive. The teacher should not commit transgressions in the name of discipline. The only thing that furthers is to ward off transgressors — that is, to protect the student from the consequences of their own foolishness. Punishment should be firm but fair. Its purpose is not to harm but to protect and guide. 28. Fair discipline. The wise dragon advises you to be firm but fair in your discipline. Do not commit transgressions in the name of order. Protect and guide, do not punish and harm."],
  [5,"Waiting",["patience", "waiting", "nourishment", "calm", "certainty"],"Waiting. If you are sincere, you have light and success. Perseverance brings good fortune. It is favorable to cross the great waters. Intentional inaction. Waiting with confidence yields results. It is beneficial to persevere. Crossing the great waters is to progress. WAITING. CONFIDENCE and GLORY. Let a SACRIFICE be performed. The ORACLE is AUSPICIOUS. It is FAVORABLE to CROSS the GREAT RIVER. Waiting does not imply empty hope. It has the inner certainty of reaching its goal. Such certainty alone gives the light that leads to success. This leads to perseverance, which in turn brings good fortune and gives the power to cross the great waters. One is confronted with a danger that must be overcome. Weakness and impatience achieve nothing. Only the strong person can thus face their destiny, for inner security allows them to endure to the end. This strength shows itself as loyalty to oneself through every test. Only when one has the courage to face things exactly as they are, without any deception or illusion, will a light develop as a result of the events, which will allow us to recognize the path to success. This recognition must be accompanied by decisive and persevering action. Only the person who faces their destiny decisively will be capable of taking the necessary decision and of defeating the danger.","The clouds rise to heaven: The image of Waiting. Thus the superior person eats and drinks, is joyful and of good humor. When clouds rise in the sky it is a sign that it will rain. There is nothing to be done. One can only wait until the rain falls. The same happens in life when destiny acts. We should not worry and try to shape the future through interventions before the appointed time arrives. What should be done is to quietly fortify the body with food and drink and the mind with joy and good humor. Destiny will arrive when it must, and then we will be ready. 29. Trust in God. Wait, trust in your life and receive the guidance of God (of the light or of your inner wisdom). Those who come into contact every day with God, with the Tao, with heaven or with inner wisdom, will be led to the light. Those who act thus will grow on their path to illumination, holiness, or inner healing. Supreme success through the daily practice of the oracle, prayer, or spiritual reading. THE DIFFERENT LINES At the beginning a nine means: Waiting in the open. It is favorable to hold to the eternal. Without blame. You wait at the outer boundaries. Being constant prevents errors. You WAIT in the FIELD. It is FAVORABLE to ACT with CONSTANCY. WITHOUT HARM. The danger is not yet near. One still waits on the open plain. Conditions are still simple. Despite this, there is a feeling that something will happen very soon. One must try to carry on one's common life as much as possible. Only in this way can one safeguard against a premature expenditure of energy; one must remain free of reproach and errors that could be a source of weakness later. 30. Autonomy. Conserve your inner energy. Separate yourself from the world and your fellow beings. How much autonomy do you need to grow with your spiritual practice? Much rest and sufficient spiritual practice are the most direct paths to illumination. Give yourself what you need. Nine in the second place means: Waiting on the sand. There are rumors. The end brings good fortune. You wait on the sandy shore. There are whispers but, eventually, good fortune. You WAIT on the SAND. A SMALL DISPUTE. The END will be AUSPICIOUS. The danger gradually approaches. The sands are found near the rivers and water implies danger. Disagreements accumulate. General uneasiness can easily occur in these times and there are mutual recriminations. The one who remains calm will succeed in making things right in the end. Insults will be silenced if we do not honor them with answers that show the insult has caused offense. 31. Inaction. Wu Wei is the Chinese concept of illuminated existence (Sat-Chit-Ananda). Free yourself from all your external objectives (desires) on a deeper plane. You must participate on the outer plane as little as necessary so that you conserve all your vital energy and your tension dissolves by itself. People might think you are lazy, but you will become a god or goddess of light. Live calmly and peacefully enough, hold to your spiritual practice and awaken your inner joy. Nine in the third place means: Waiting in the mud announces the arrival of the enemy. Waiting in the mud invites evil. You WAIT in the MUD. This MAKES the ENEMIES ARRIVE. The mud is not the right place to wait, for it has already been washed by the river water. Instead of having saved energy to cross the river on the first attempt, one has started prematurely, which has not allowed one to get beyond the muddy bank. Such an unfavorable position invites the enemies to naturally take advantage of the situation of weakness in which one finds themselves. Concern and a sense of the gravity of conditions are all that can prevent harm. 32. Action. One can also abuse inaction. God is with those who work hard. Solve your problems. Direct yourself to the light with your spiritual practice. Be careful. Proceed with strength. Triumph. Six in the fourth place means: Waiting in blood. Leap from the hole. Waiting in the midst of blood. Exiting the hole. You WAIT in the presence of BLOOD. you LEAVE the CAVE. The situation is extremely dangerous. It is of the greatest gravity now. It is already a matter of life or death. Bloodshed seems imminent. It is not possible to advance or retreat; we are trapped, as if we were in a hole. Now we can only endure firmly and let destiny take its course. This composure, which prevents us from aggravating the problems by something we might do, is the only way out of the dangerous hole. 33. The sacrifice. Without external sacrifice there can be no inner happiness. What do you need to renounce on the external plane so that you can grow with happiness on the internal plane? What is your sacrifice for successful advance on the spiritual path? Free yourself from your ego, walk with strength on the route of truth. Do your spiritual practice and arrive at the land of light. Success. Nine in the fifth place means: Waiting with food and drink. Perseverance brings good fortune. Waiting while eating and drinking. Continuing on the path brings good fortune. You WAIT in the presence of FOOD and WINE. The ORACLE is AUSPICIOUS. Even in the midst of danger there are periods of peace in which things go relatively well. If one possesses sufficient inner strength, these intervals will be used to fortify ourselves for the renewed struggle. We must know how to enjoy the moments we have without being distracted from the goal, for perseverance is required to achieve victory. This is also true in public life; it is not possible to achieve everything at once. The pinnacle of wisdom is reached when one is capable of allowing people to have enough rest to make their work pleasant until the task is completed. Therein lies the entire secret of this hexagram. This hexagram differs from Chien, Obstruction, in the fact that in this case, while we wait we are sure of our cause and therefore do not lose the serenity of our inner joy. 34. Joy. Proceed on the middle path. Do not demand too much or too little of yourself on the spiritual path. Live joyfully. Make your path, your course of action, something beautiful. What will you do today to have joy? At the top a six means: One falls into the hole. Three unexpected guests arrive. Honor them and, in the end, good fortune will come. You enter the hole. Three unexpected guests arrive, honor them and good fortune will come. UPON ENTERING the CAVE, THREE UNINVITED GUESTS ARRIVE. RESPECT THEM and the END will be AUSPICIOUS. The wait is over. The danger can no longer be avoided. One falls into the hole and must yield to the inevitable. Everything seems to have been in vain. But precisely in this extreme situation, things take an unexpected turn. Without one moving, there is an external intervention. At first it is not possible to know what it is: Is it a rescue or destruction? A person in this situation must keep their mind alert and not shut themselves in with a stubborn attitude of rejection. One must welcome the new situation with respect. Thus, finally, the danger is avoided and everything goes well. Even fortunate twists sometimes arrive in forms that may seem strange to us. 35. Conflict. Before one can dissolve internal blockages, one must overcome obstacles. Feelings of doubt appear. Hold your course. Live as a spiritual winner. A great reward awaits you. Proceed with strength and persevere on the path of wisdom and light."],
  [6,"Conflict",["conflict", "honesty", "retreat", "mediation", "caution"],"<strong><em>Conflict. You are sincere and face obstruction. A cautious halt halfway brings fortune. Proceeding to the end brings misfortune. It is favorable to see the great person. It is not favorable to cross the great waters.<br><br>Conflict. The certainty of being right encounters obstacles. With care, there is progress in the middle, but it is disastrous at the end. It is beneficial to see the great person, but it is not beneficial to cross the great water.<br><br>A DISPUTE. There is CONFIDENCE, yet there are OBSTACLES. Be VIGILANT. HALFWAY, everything is AUSPICIOUS. But the END will bring MISFORTUNE. It is FAVORABLE to SEE the GREAT PERSON. It is UNFAVORABLE to CROSS the GREAT RIVER.</em></strong><br><br>Conflict develops when one feels in the right position and encounters opposition. If one is not convinced of being right, opposition leads to acting cunningly or to displays of violence, but not to open conflict. If a person is involved in a conflict, their only salvation lies in meeting the opponent halfway. Carrying the conflict to the bitter end has negative effects even if one is right, for the enmity is perpetuated.<br><br>It is important to consult the great person, who is impartial and whose authority is great enough to end the conflict in a friendly way or to ensure a just decision. In times of struggle, one should avoid crossing the great waters. That is, dangerous enterprises should be avoided, for successful completion requires a concerted unity of focus. Inner conflict weakens the capacity to conquer outer danger.","<strong><em>Heaven and water move in opposite directions; The image of Conflict. Thus, in all their affairs, the superior person carefully considers the beginning.</em></strong><br><br>The image indicates that the causes of conflict lie latent in the opposing tendencies of the two trigrams. Once these tendencies appear, conflict is inevitable. To avoid it, therefore, everything must be carefully considered at the very beginning. If rights and duties are carefully defined, or if, within a group, the spiritual tendencies of individuals are harmonized, the cause of conflict is removed in advance."],
  [7,"The Army",["discipline", "authority", "organization", "leadership", "service"],"The Receptive brings sublime success, furthering through the perseverance of a mare. If the superior person undertakes something and tries to lead, they go astray; but if they follow, they find guidance. It is favorable to find friends in the west and south, and to set aside friends in the east and north. Quiet perseverance brings good fortune. The receptive element brings sublime success. The symbol of a mare. At first, one leads and loses; afterward, one follows and receives support. Friends in the west and south, not in the east and north. A peaceful continuation is beneficial. EARTH. Let a GREATER SACRIFICE be performed. The ORACLE of a MARE is FAVORABLE. The NOBLE PERSON PROCEEDS WITH a PURPOSE. You might, at FIRST, LOSE your WAY; But AFTERWARD, you WILL GAIN a MASTER. FAVORABLE. You WILL GAIN a FRIEND in the SOUTHWEST, you WILL LOSE a FRIEND in the NORTHEAST. The ORACLE of PEACE is AUSPICIOUS. The four fundamental aspects of the creative — 'sublime success, favorable through perseverance' — also belong to the receptive. In this case, however, perseverance is defined more precisely: it is the perseverance of a mare. The receptive denotes a spatial reality in contrast to the spiritual potentiality of the creative. Potential becomes reality and the spiritual acquires spatial dimensions through a specific qualifying definition. Thus, the qualification 'of a mare' is added to the idea of perseverance. The horse belongs to the earth as the dragon belongs to heaven. Its tireless coming and going across the plains is a symbol of the vastness of the earth. This symbol is chosen because the mare combines the strength and speed of a horse with the gentleness and devotion of a cow. Only because nature, in its millions of forms, corresponds to the millions of impulses of the creative can it make these impulses real. The richness of nature lies in its power to nourish all living beings; its greatness lies in its power to give them beauty and splendor. Thus all that lives prospers. It is the creative that creates things, but the receptive brings them to life. Applied to human affairs, what the hexagram indicates is action in conformity with the situation. The person in question is not in an independent position. They act as an assistant. This means that the person must accomplish something. It is not their task to try to lead. That would only make them lose their way. What they must do is let themselves be guided.","The condition of Earth is Giving while receiving. Thus the superior person, the one who possesses greatness of character, sustains the outer world. Just as there is only one heaven, so there is only one earth. In the hexagram Heaven, the duplication of the trigram implies duration in time, but in the hexagram Earth, the duplication implies solidity and extension in space, for the earth sustains and preserves all things that live and move upon it. The earth, in its devotion — that is, in its surrender, in its giving of itself — sustains all things, good and bad, without exception. Just as the superior person enlarges their character, purifies themselves, and gains power to sustain themselves, they are also able to sustain and support people and things."],
  [8,"Holding Together",["union", "alliance", "solidarity", "community", "mutual support"],"Holding together brings good fortune. You inquire of the oracle anew: Is your spirit great, constant, and persevering? Then there will be no blame. The insecure approach gradually. Whoever arrives late meets misfortune. Unity, integrating into a whole. Good fortune. You inquire once more for signs. Without error. The afflicted gather. Those who arrive late will have misfortune. HOLDING TOGETHER. AUSPICIOUS. The PRIMEVAL AUGURY: The FUNDAMENTAL and ETERNAL ORACLE. WITHOUT HARM. Upon ARRIVAL from the PLACE of CONFLICT, whoever is LATE will find MISFORTUNE. What is required is that we unite with others so that all may complement and help each other through solidarity. However, that holding together, that solidarity, requires a central figure around which others can unite. Becoming the center of influence that keeps others united is a delicate task charged with great responsibility. It requires greatness of spirit, consistency, and strength. Therefore, whoever wishes to gather others around them must ask whether they are equal to the task, for whoever attempts it without a true calling will only provoke a confusion worse than what would have existed without the union. But when there is cause for true union, those who at first doubted will gradually arrive of their own will. Those who delay in approaching will suffer the consequences, for to create union and solidarity, it is also necessary that it be done in due time. Relationships form and establish firmly according to clearly established laws. Shared experiences strengthen these bonds, and whoever arrives late will find the door closed. If a person has recognized the need to unite with others but does not believe themselves strong enough to be the center, they must become a member of another type of community.","On the earth there is water: The image of Holding Together. Thus the kings of ancient times granted the various kingdoms as fiefs and cultivated friendly relations with the feudal lords. Water fills all the empty spaces on earth and quickly adheres to the ground. The social organization of ancient China was based on this principle of maintaining unity between dependents and rulers. Water flows to join with water, for all its parts are governed by the same laws. Just as water fills the empty places and flows onward, so the ancient kings granted territories to those who depended on them, establishing a network of mutual support and loyalty. The principle is simple: those who are united by common interests and shared values form a natural community. But this community requires a center — a leader who embodies the common purpose and around whom all can gather. 36. Unity. The wise dragon advises you to seek union with others. Together you are stronger. Find your community and contribute to the common good. Success comes through solidarity. ○ Initial six: Hold to the truth with loyalty. There is no blame. If your truth is like a full earthen bowl, in the end good fortune comes from other sources. Hold to TRUTH with LOYALTY. There is NO BLAME. If your TRUTH is like a FULL BOWL, in the END GOOD FORTUNE comes from OTHER SOURCES. At the beginning of the time of holding together, the emphasis is on loyalty and truth. One must be sincere and honest in one's relationships. Like a bowl full of rice offered as a gift, sincerity is more important than wealth. If one holds to the truth with loyalty, good fortune will come even from unexpected sources. 37. Sincere unity. The wise dragon advises you to be sincere in your relationships. True union is based on mutual trust and loyalty. Six in the second place means: Hold to the truth within. Perseverance brings good fortune. Hold to TRUTH WITHIN. PERSEVERANCE brings GOOD FORTUNE. The foundation of holding together is inner truth. One must be true to oneself before one can be true to others. Inner truth creates a magnetic force that attracts others naturally. When one perseveres in inner truth, good fortune follows as a matter of course. 38. Inner truth. The wise dragon advises you to cultivate inner truth. Be authentic in your relationships. Truth attracts others naturally. Six in the third place means: You hold together with people who are not the right ones. You hold together with those who are NOT RIGHT. If one associates with the wrong people, the union will not last. One must be discerning in choosing one's companions. Not everyone who wishes to join is suitable. One must evaluate whether the potential companions share the same values and purpose. A union based on wrong foundations will eventually dissolve. 39. Discernment in union. The wise dragon advises you to be discerning in your associations. Choose companions who share your values and purpose. Six in the fourth place means: Hold to the truth outwardly. Perseverance brings good fortune. Hold to TRUTH OUTWARDLY. PERSEVERANCE brings GOOD FORTUNE. In the position of the minister, one must hold to the truth in one's external relations. This means being honest and upright in one's dealings with others. The minister serves the ruler with loyalty and truth. This outward truth strengthens the bond between ruler and minister and ensures the stability of the state. 40. Outward truth. The wise dragon advises you to be truthful in your external relations. Honesty and uprightness strengthen all relationships. Nine in the fifth place means: Manifestation of holding together. In the king's approach he has servants. Good fortune. MANIFESTATION of HOLDING TOGETHER. In the KING's APPROACH he has SERVANTS. GOOD FORTUNE. The king is the center of the union. He attracts others through his virtue and authority. His servants are those who have gathered around him out of genuine loyalty and trust. This is the ideal form of holding together — a strong and virtuous center that naturally attracts and unites others. The king does not force unity but inspires it through his example. 41. The manifest union. The wise dragon advises you to be a center of unity through your virtue and example. Do not force others to follow; inspire them through your integrity. At the top a six means: Holding together without a head. Misfortune. HOLDING TOGETHER without a HEAD. MISFORTUNE. A union without a head — without a leader or center — is doomed to fail. Without direction and purpose, the group will dissolve into chaos. This is the consequence of arriving late — of missing the opportunity to join when the union was being formed. Those who hesitate too long find themselves excluded. The door is closed. In the time of holding together, one must decide early and commit fully. Hesitation and delay lead to isolation and misfortune. 42. The headless union. The wise dragon advises you not to hesitate. If you see the opportunity for union, seize it. Do not wait until it is too late. Commitment and timely action are the keys to successful holding together."],
  [9,"The Taming Power of the Small",["pause", "moderation", "cultivation", "gentle wind", "accumulation"],"The taming power of the small has success. Dense clouds, but no rain from our western region. Nourishment of the small. Success. Dense clouds but no rain from the west. A SMALL offering of LIVESTOCK. Let a SACRIFICE be performed. DENSE CLOUDS WITHOUT RAIN approach from MY WESTERN FIELDS. The image refers to the state of affairs in China at the time of King Wên, who originally came from the west and was in the east at the court of the reigning tyrant Chou Hsin. The moment for acting on a large scale had not yet arrived. King Wên could only keep the tyrant under control through friendly persuasions. Hence the image of many clouds that promised moisture and blessings to the earth, even though the rain had not yet come. The situation is not unfavorable. There is a prospect of final success, but there are still obstacles on the way, and we can only take preparatory measures. Only through the small means of friendly persuasion can we exercise influence. The time has not yet come for taking definitive measures. However, we could, with restrictions, act as an influence that limits and tames. To realize our purpose we need firm determination within and gentleness and adaptability in external relations.","The wind runs across the sky: The image of the taming power of the small. Thus the superior person refines the outer aspect of their nature. The wind can indeed group the clouds in the sky. However, being only air without any solid body, it does not produce great or lasting effects. Likewise, an individual in times when they cannot produce great effects in the outer world can only refine through small adjustments the expression of their nature. 57. The gentle wind. The wise dragon advises you to work through small, gentle adjustments. Do not try to force great changes. Small consistent efforts will lead to success. ○ Initial nine: Return to the way. How could there be blame in this? Good fortune. RETURN to the WAY. How could there be BLAME in this? GOOD FORTUNE. At the beginning of the time of taming the small, one returns to one's own way. This is the right thing to do and brings good fortune. One does not try to change others but focuses on one's own path. 58. Return to the way. The wise dragon advises you to focus on your own path. Do not try to change others. Self-improvement is the key to success. Six in the second place means: One allows oneself to be drawn into returning. Good fortune. One allows oneself to be DRAWN into RETURNING. GOOD FORTUNE. One is not strong enough to return to the way on one's own. But one has the good fortune to be associated with someone who provides guidance. By allowing oneself to be drawn along, one returns to the right path. This is a form of success that comes through association with the right people. 59. Being drawn back. The wise dragon advises you to seek the company of those who can guide you back to the right path. Humility and openness bring good fortune. Nine in the third place means: The spokes burst out of the wagon. Man and wife stare at each other. The SPOKES BURST OUT of the WAGON. MAN and WIFE stare at EACH OTHER. The taming power of the small is not sufficient to hold back the creative force. The creative force pushes forward with such strength that the bonds that try to restrain it break. This is like a wagon whose spokes burst out — the vehicle cannot move forward. In human relationships, this is like a marriage in which the partners stare at each other without being able to move forward. The time of taming the small has reached its limit. A different approach is needed. 60. Broken bonds. The wise dragon advises you to recognize when gentle persuasion is no longer sufficient. Sometimes stronger measures are needed. Six in the fourth place means: If you are sincere, blood vanishes and fear falls away. Without blame. If you are SINCERE, BLOOD VANISHES and FEAR falls away. WITHOUT BLAME. The situation is dangerous. There is a threat of bloodshed. But sincerity is powerful enough to overcome the danger. When one is truly sincere, even the most violent opposition softens. Blood vanishes and fear falls away. The danger passes without harm. Sincerity is the most powerful weapon in times of conflict. 61. The power of sincerity. The wise dragon advises you to be sincere even in the most dangerous situations. Sincerity can overcome any obstacle. Nine in the fifth place means: If you are sincere and walk in the middle path, you are rich through your neighbor. If you are SINCERE and walk in the MIDDLE PATH, you are RICH through your NEIGHBOR. The ruler is in the position of honor. They are sincere and walk the middle path. Their influence is so strong that even their neighbors benefit from their wealth. This is the highest form of taming the small — when the gentle influence of a sincere leader enriches everyone around them. 62. Enriching influence. The wise dragon advises you to walk the middle path with sincerity. Your gentle influence will enrich those around you. At the top a nine means: The rain comes, there is rest. This is due to the lasting effect. Perseverance brings the woman into danger. Even the moon is nearly full. If the superior person persists, misfortune comes. The RAIN comes, there is REST. This is due to the LASTING EFFECT. PERSEVERANCE brings the WOMAN into DANGER. Even the MOON is nearly FULL. If the SUPERIOR PERSON persists, MISFORTUNE comes. The taming has been successful — the rain has come. But now there is a new danger. If one continues to push, even what was successful becomes a source of misfortune. This is like the moon that is nearly full — the next step is the waning. One must know when to stop. 63. Knowing when to stop. The wise dragon advises you to recognize when you have achieved your goal. Do not push beyond what is necessary. Rest and consolidate what has been gained."],
  [10,"Treading",["conduct", "careful advance", "respect", "ritual", "danger overcome"],"Treading. Stepping on the tiger's tail. The tiger does not bite the person. Success. Stepping on the tiger's tail. It does not bite the person. Success. You WALK upon the TIGER's TAIL. The tiger does NOT BITE. Let a SACRIFICE be performed. The situation is truly difficult. The strongest and the weakest are together. The weak follows the strong and provokes it. The strong, however, accepts and does not harm the weak, for it is a contact of good humor that causes no harm. In terms of a human situation, one deals with wild, intractable people. In such a case, one achieves one's goals if one behaves with decorum. Kindness triumphs even when approaching irritable people.","Heaven above, the lake below: The image of Treading. Thus the superior person discriminates between high and low, and in that way strengthens the thinking of the people. Heaven and the lake have different heights; that is something in their nature. Hence there is no envy between them. Among humanity too there are — of necessity — differences of elevation. Universal equality is impossible. However, it is important that differences in social rank not be arbitrary or unjust. If they are, envy and class struggle are inevitable consequences. If, on the other hand, external differences in rank correspond to differences in each person's intrinsic worth, and if inner value gives shape to outer rank, people are docile and order reigns in society. 64. The clever master. Although the person steps on the tiger's tail, they suffer no harm. The person risks achieving the impossible and succeeds. They risk much and everything turns out well. THE DIFFERENT LINES At the beginning a nine means: Simple conduct. Progress without blame. Simple energy. To advance free of all guilt. To ADVANCE, WALK with SIMPLICITY. WITHOUT HARM. One who begins the time of treading does so with simple conduct. There is no affectation or pretension. One walks the path with sincerity and directness. This simplicity ensures that one advances without blame. 65. Simple conduct. The wise dragon advises you to walk your path with simplicity and sincerity. Do not complicate things. Directness brings success. Nine in the second place means: Treading a smooth, level course. The perseverance of a dark person brings good fortune. Treading a SMOOTH, LEVEL COURSE. The PERSEVERANCE of a DARK PERSON brings GOOD FORTUNE. One is in a position of ease. The path is smooth and level. But one must not become complacent. Even in easy times, perseverance is necessary. The dark person — one who is not in a position of leadership — can still achieve good fortune through perseverance. By remaining steady and true, one navigates the easy times successfully. 66. The smooth path. The wise dragon advises you to remain persevering even when the path is easy. Do not become complacent. Steadiness brings good fortune. Six in the third place means: A one-eyed person is able to see, a lame person is able to tread. They tread on the tiger's tail. The tiger bites the person. Misfortune. The warrior thus works for the great prince. A ONE-EYED person is able to SEE, a LAME person is able to TREAD. They tread on the TIGER's TAIL. The tiger BITES the PERSON. MISFORTUNE. The WARRIOR thus works for the GREAT PRINCE. One has insufficient ability for the task at hand. Like a one-eyed person who can see but not clearly, or a lame person who can walk but not well, one is not equipped for the challenge. If one nevertheless takes on the task — if one treads on the tiger's tail — the result is misfortune. The warrior who works for the great prince takes on a task beyond their capacity. In times of treading, one must honestly assess one's abilities before taking action. 67. Overestimating oneself. The wise dragon advises you to honestly assess your abilities. Do not take on tasks beyond your capacity. Overconfidence leads to misfortune. Nine in the fourth place means: They tread on the tiger's tail. Cautiousness and circumspection lead to good fortune. They tread on the TIGER's TAIL. CAUTIOUSNESS and CIRCUMSPECTION lead to GOOD FORTUNE. One is in a dangerous position. Like treading on a tiger's tail, the situation requires the greatest care. But if one approaches the danger with caution and circumspection, good fortune is the result. The danger is real, but it can be navigated successfully through careful and respectful behavior. 68. Careful treading. The wise dragon advises you to approach danger with caution and respect. Careful behavior in difficult situations leads to good fortune. Nine in the fifth place means: Resolute conduct. Perseverance brings danger. RESOLUTE conduct. PERSEVERANCE brings DANGER. One is in a position of authority. One has the power to act resolutely. But resolute action in a position of power can be dangerous. If one is too forceful, one may provoke resistance. The time of treading requires tact and consideration, not brute force. Even when one has the authority to act decisively, one must be mindful of the effects of one's actions. 69. The danger of force. The wise dragon advises you to use tact and consideration even when you have the power to act forcefully. Brute force provokes resistance. At the top a nine means: Look to your conduct and attend to your blessing. Everything acts to further. LOOK to your CONDUCT and attend to your BLESSING. Everything acts to FURTHER. The time of treading is complete. One looks back on one's conduct and assesses the blessing that has come from it. If one has walked the path with care and propriety, everything has been to the good. The conduct has been correct and the blessing follows naturally. This is the successful completion of the time of treading. 70. Completed conduct. The wise dragon advises you to review your conduct and celebrate the blessings that have come from careful and proper behavior. Success is the reward of correct conduct."],
  [11,"Peace",["harmony", "prosperity", "exchange", "balance", "fullness"],"Peace. The small departs. The great approaches. Good fortune. Success. Peace. The narrow departs. The great arrives. Good fortune and success. PEACE. The SMALL things DEPART, GREAT things ARRIVE. AUSPICIOUS. Let a SACRIFICE be performed. This hexagram denotes a time in nature in which heaven seems to be on earth. Heaven has placed itself below the earth, so that its powers unite in profound harmony. Thus peace and blessing descend upon all living things. In the world of humans it is a time of social harmony; those in elevated positions show themselves favorable to those in lower positions, and the low and inferior put an end to their disputes. Regarding the positions of the signs, it is important to observe that in the center — the most important position — is found the illuminating principle; the principle of darkness is outside. Thus the light has powerful influence while the dark is submissive. In this way each receives what corresponds to them. When the good elements of society occupy a central position and are in control, the evil elements submit to their influence and take the place that belongs to them. The individual lines enter the hexagram from below and leave it again at the top. Here the small, weak, and evil elements are about to depart, while the great, strong, and good elements move upward. This brings good fortune and success.","Heaven and earth unite: The image of Peace. Thus the ruler divides and completes the course of heaven and earth, and in that way aids the people. Heaven and earth are in contact and combine their influences. This produces a time of universal flowering and prosperity. This current of energy must be regulated by the ruler of the people. This is done by dividing and completing the course of heaven and earth. The ruler establishes the measures of time — the seasons, the calendar — and ensures that the natural rhythms are respected. By aligning human activity with the rhythms of nature, the ruler aids the people and ensures prosperity. 71. The time of peace. The wise dragon advises you to align your activities with the natural rhythms. When heaven and earth are in harmony, everything flourishes. Take advantage of this time of peace and prosperity. ○ Initial nine: When ribbon grass is pulled up, it brings its roots with it. Each according to its kind. Perseverance brings good fortune. When RIBBON GRASS is PULLED UP, it brings its ROOTS with it. Each according to its KIND. PERSEVERANCE brings GOOD FORTUNE. In times of peace, advancement is easy. Like ribbon grass that, when pulled, brings its roots along, one's advance brings others along. Each person advances according to their kind. This is the natural way of progress in times of peace. Perseverance ensures that the advance continues without obstruction. 72. Natural advance. The wise dragon advises you to advance naturally in times of peace. Your progress will bring others along. Perseverance ensures continued success. Nine in the second place means: Bearing with the uncouth in firmness, fording the river with resolution. Not neglecting what is distant. Not regarding one's party. The way of the middle is honored. Bearing with the UNCOUTH in FIRMNESS, fording the RIVER with RESOLUTION. Not NEGLECTING what is DISTANT. Not REGARDING one's PARTY. The WAY of the MIDDLE is HONORED. In times of peace, one must be broad-minded and inclusive. One bears with the uncouth, fords the river with resolution, does not neglect what is distant, and does not favor one's own party. This is the way of the middle — the path of balance and fairness that honors all. 73. Broad-mindedness. The wise dragon advises you to be inclusive and fair-minded in times of peace. Do not favor your own group. The middle path honors all. Nine in the third place means: No plain not followed by a slope. No going not followed by a return. He who perseveres when there are no difficulties remains without blame. Do not mourn over this truth. Enjoy the good fortune that you still possess. No PLAIN not followed by a SLOPE. No GOING not followed by a RETURN. He who PERSEVERES when there are NO DIFFICULTIES remains WITHOUT BLAME. Do not MOURN over this TRUTH. Enjoy the GOOD FORTUNE that you still POSSESS. Even in times of peace, change is constant. Every plain is followed by a slope; every going is followed by a return. This is the law of nature. One must not become complacent in times of peace but must persevere as if difficulties were present. By doing so, one remains without blame and can enjoy the good fortune that is still present. 74. Impermanence of peace. The wise dragon advises you not to become complacent in times of peace. Change is constant. Persevere and enjoy the present good fortune. Six in the fourth place means: He flutters down, not boasting of wealth, together with his neighbor, guileless and sincere. He FLUTTERS DOWN, not BOASTING of WEALTH, together with his NEIGHBOR, GUILELESS and SINCERE. In times of peace, those in high positions should not boast of their wealth but should associate with their neighbors in guileless sincerity. Like a bird that flutters down to join its companion, the person in power descends to the level of others with genuine warmth and honesty. This creates the bonds of trust that sustain peace. 75. Guileless sincerity. The wise dragon advises you to be sincere and unpretentious in times of peace. Do not boast of your wealth or position. Genuine warmth creates lasting bonds. Six in the fifth place means: The sovereign I gives his daughter in marriage. This brings blessing and supreme good fortune. The SOVEREIGN I gives his DAUGHTER in MARRIAGE. This brings BLESSING and SUPREME GOOD FORTUNE. The sovereign, in the position of honor, gives his daughter in marriage to someone of lower rank. This is a sign of humility and openness that brings great blessing. The union of high and low, of heaven and earth, is the essence of peace. When those in power are willing to lower themselves and unite with those below, supreme good fortune follows. 76. The blessing of humility. The wise dragon advises you to be humble even in positions of power. The willingness to unite with those below brings supreme good fortune. At the top a six means: The wall falls back into the moat. Do not use the army now. Issue commands from your own town. Perseverance brings humiliation. The WALL falls back into the MOAT. Do NOT use the ARMY now. Issue COMMANDS from your own TOWN. PERSEVERANCE brings HUMILIATION. The time of peace has come to its end. The wall that protected the city falls back into the moat — the defenses crumble from within. This is not a time for military action but for issuing commands from one's own domain. If one tries to persevere as if peace still reigned, the result is humiliation. One must recognize the change in the times and adapt accordingly. 77. The end of peace. The wise dragon advises you to recognize when the time of peace is ending. Do not try to maintain what has already crumbled. Adapt to the new reality."],
  [12,"Standstill",["stagnation", "blockage", "retreat", "perseverance", "patience"],"Standstill. It is not favorable for the superior person to persevere. The one who relates to bad people. The great departs; the small approaches. Standstill. Evil obstructs the superior person. The broad departs. The narrow arrives. The person needs to persevere. Those who OBSTRUCT the PERSON are BANDITS. The ORACLE of the NOBLE PERSON is NOT FAVORABLE. GREAT things DEPART, SMALL things ARRIVE. Heaven and earth are not in communion and all things are in a state of shock. What is below has no relation to what is above. And upon the earth confusion and disorder prevail. The power of darkness has settled within; the power of light is outside. Weakness dominates within, hardness outside. Within is the inferior and outside the superior. The way of bad people is on the rise; the way of superior people is in decline. But superior people do not allow themselves to be turned away from their principles. If it is not possible for superior people to exercise influence, they nevertheless remain faithful to their principles and withdraw into hiding.","Heaven and earth do not unite: The image of Standstill. Thus the superior person takes refuge in their inner worth in order to evade the difficulties. The superior person does not allow themselves to be honored with emoluments. When, due to the influence of inferior people, mutual distrust prevails in public life, fruitful activity is considered impossible, for the foundations of public life are out of place. Consequently, the superior person knows what to do in such circumstances. They do not admit being tempted by attractive offers to participate in public activities. This would expose them to danger, for they could not accept the evil of others. The superior person, therefore, withdraws into their inner worth and endures the difficulties in silence. 78. Withdrawal. The wise dragon advises you to withdraw into your inner worth when the time is not favorable. Do not accept offers that would compromise your principles. Silence and patience are your allies. ○ Initial six: When ribbon grass is pulled up, it brings its roots with it. Each according to its kind. Perseverance brings good fortune. When RIBBON GRASS is PULLED UP, it brings its ROOTS with it. Each according to its KIND. PERSEVERANCE brings GOOD FORTUNE. In times of standstill, inferior people advance together, pulling each other along. But superior people can also use this principle to remain united with those of like mind. By holding together with those who share their values, they preserve their integrity. 79. Unity in adversity. The wise dragon advises you to hold together with those who share your values in times of adversity. Mutual support preserves integrity. Six in the second place means: Bearing with the uncouth in firmness, fording the river with resolution. Not neglecting what is distant. Not regarding one's party. The way of the middle is honored. Bearing with the UNCOUTH in FIRMNESS, fording the RIVER with RESOLUTION. Not NEGLECTING what is DISTANT. Not REGARDING one's PARTY. The WAY of the MIDDLE is HONORED. Even in times of standstill, one must maintain breadth of vision and fairness. One bears with the uncouth, fords difficulties with resolution, and does not favor one's own party. The middle way remains the standard. 80. The middle way in adversity. The wise dragon advises you to maintain fairness and breadth of vision even in difficult times. The middle way remains the standard. Six in the third place means: They have shame. They have SHAME. Those who are responsible for the standstill begin to feel shame for their actions. This is the first sign that the situation may improve. When those in power recognize their errors, the path opens for change. Shame is the beginning of reform. 81. The beginning of reform. The wise dragon advises you that even in times of standstill, change is possible. When those responsible recognize their errors, the path to improvement opens. Nine in the fourth place means: He who acts at the command of the highest remains without blame. Those of like mind partake in the blessing. He who acts at the COMMAND of the HIGHEST remains WITHOUT BLAME. Those of LIKE MIND partake in the BLESSING. In times of standstill, one must act only at the command of the highest principle. If one's actions are guided by the highest truth, one remains without blame and those who share the same purpose partake in the blessing. 82. Acting from the highest. The wise dragon advises you to act only from the highest principles in times of adversity. Your integrity will inspire others and bring blessing. Nine in the fifth place means: Standstill is giving way. Good fortune for the great person. 'It perishes, it perishes!' Thus one ties it to a cluster of mulberry shoots. STANDSTILL is GIVING WAY. GOOD FORTUNE for the GREAT PERSON. 'It PERISHES, it PERISHES!' Thus one TIES it to a CLUSTER of MULBERRY SHOOTS. The time of standstill begins to give way. The great person who has remained faithful to their principles now sees the fruits of their perseverance. But even in this moment of transition, one must remain vigilant — constantly reminding oneself 'it perishes, it perishes!' — and tie one's fate to something strong and enduring, like a cluster of mulberry shoots. 83. The end of standstill. The wise dragon advises you to remain vigilant even when the time begins to change. Tie your fate to what is enduring. At the top a nine means: The standstill comes to an end. First standstill, then good fortune. The STANDSTILL comes to an END. First STANDSTILL, then GOOD FORTUNE. The time of standstill reaches its end. The transition is not immediate — there is first a final moment of standstill before good fortune arrives. One must endure this last moment with patience and faith. The change is inevitable; it only requires one more push. 84. Final endurance. The wise dragon advises you to endure the last moment of difficulty with patience. Good fortune is just beyond the threshold."],
  [13,"Fellowship with Men",["fraternity", "community", "shared purpose", "openness", "unity"],"<strong><em>Fellowship with people in the open country. Success. It is favorable to cross the great waters. The perseverance of the superior person is favorable.<br><br>Fellowship in the open. Success. It is beneficial to cross the great water. The superior person benefits through perseverance.<br><br>PEOPLE GATHER in the OPEN FIELD. Let a SACRIFICE be performed. It is FAVORABLE to CROSS the GREAT RIVER. The ORACLE of the NOBLE PERSON is FAVORABLE.</em></strong><br><br>True community among people must be based on a universal concern. It is not the private interests of individuals that create lasting community bonds among people, but the objectives of humanity.<br><br>That is why it is said that fellowship with people in the open country brings success. If this unity prevails, even difficult and dangerous tasks, like crossing the great waters, can be accomplished. However, to make this type of community possible, it is necessary to have an illuminated and persevering leader, a person with clear, convincing, and inspiring objectives who is endowed with the necessary strength to make them real. The inner trigram means clarity. The outer trigram means strength.","<strong><em>Heaven together with fire: The image of Fellowship with people. Thus the superior person organizes the clans and establishes differences between things.</em></strong><br><br>Heaven has the same direction of movement as fire, despite being distinct from fire. Just as the luminaries of heaven serve to achieve a systematic division of time and to organize time, so too human society and all things that truly belong together must be organized in an organic way. Community cannot be a mere mixture of interests. It must be based on an inner organizing principle. The superior person classifies beings and distinguishes things, establishing the organic order that allows true community to flourish. 85. True community. The wise dragon advises you to build community on universal principles, not private interests. True fellowship requires a shared purpose that transcends individual concerns."],
  [14,"Possession in Great Measure",["abundance", "light", "generosity", "virtue", "wealth"],"Difficulty at the Beginning works supreme success, furthering through perseverance. Nothing should be undertaken. It is favorable to appoint helpers. Difficulty is followed by great success. Difficulty followed by great success. Continuing on the path is rewarded. Remaining in what exists, not seeking what is new. Appointing princes offers advantage. DIFFICULTIES. Let a GREATER SACRIFICE be performed. A FAVORABLE ORACLE. DO NOT PROCEED WITH a PURPOSE. It is FAVORABLE to APPOINT feudal PRINCES. Times of growth are marked by difficulties. They are similar to the birth of a firstborn. But these difficulties are the result of the very profusion of what struggles to take form. Everything is in motion; consequently, if one perseveres there are prospects of great success, despite the existing risk. When it is a person's destiny to undertake these new beginnings, everything still lacks form, everything is in darkness. Hence one must be very careful, for any premature movement could bring disaster. Likewise, it is very important not to be alone; to overcome chaos one needs helpers. This does not mean, however, that one should look at everything passively. One must act and participate with inspiration and guidance. 17","Clouds and thunder: The image of Difficulty at the Beginning. Thus the superior person creates order out of confusion. Clouds and thunder are represented by defined decorative lines; this means that in the chaos of difficulty at the beginning, order is already implicit. Likewise the superior person must arrange and organize the nascent profusion of the beginning times, just as one untangles a skein of silk filaments and gives them form by working the threads. In order that one may find one's place in the infinitude of being, one must be able to separate and unite."],
  [15,"Modesty",["humility", "balance", "equanimity", "moderation", "silent virtue"],"Youthful folly has success. I do not seek the young fool; the young fool seeks me. At the first oracle I give an answer. If one asks two, three times, it is importunity. When one is importunate, I do not inform. Perseverance is favorable. Juvenile, immature, growth. Good fortune. I do not seek immature people, but if they come to me, I answer them. If they continue with immature questions, I remain silent. IGNORANCE. Let a SACRIFICE be performed. I did NOT SEEK the IGNORANT INFANT. The IGNORANT INFANT was the one who SOUGHT ME. When the FIRST DIVINATION, I SPOKE. To ask TWO or THREE times is to LACK RESPECT. When one LACKS RESPECT, I do NOT REVEAL a FAVORABLE ORACLE. In youth, being foolish is not bad. Despite everything, one can triumph. But one must find an expert teacher and treat them correctly. For this, first of all, one must accept one's inexperience and seek a teacher. Only modesty and diligence certify the willingness to learn, which results in a devout recognition of the teacher. The teacher must wait calmly until being sought. They should not offer themselves spontaneously. Only thus will teaching occur at the right time and correctly. The teacher's answer to the student's question must be clear and concrete, like the answer that a querent wishes to obtain from the oracle. Being so, one must accept the answer as the solution of the doubt, as a decision. Distrustful or thoughtless questions only bother the teacher, and the best they can do is to dismiss them, as the oracle, which only offers one answer and refuses itself before questions that denote doubt or try to test it. If perseverance is added, which does not cease until one punctually appropriates knowledge, a beautiful success is assured. The sign offers, then, useful counsel to both teacher and student. 22","At the foot of the mountain a spring rises: the image of Youth. Thus the superior person, through scrupulous action, sustains their character. The spring manages to flow and overcome obstacles by not hesitating to fill up the empty places before it and thus advance. In the same way, the sage acts with determination to cultivate their character. Everything that is human is originally good but tends to stray from its original nature and fall into error. The cause of this is contact with the outer world, which acts upon it with seductions and temptations. From this contact arise desires and passions that cloud the original clarity of the soul. The sage knows that character must be cultivated through constant care and attention. Like the spring that rises at the foot of the mountain and gradually fills the hollows before flowing onward, the sage fills the gaps in their character through study and reflection."],
  [16,"Enthusiasm",["enthusiasm", "joy", "preparation", "movement", "music"],"Enthusiasm. It is favorable to appoint helpers and to make armies march. A calm attention benefits the preparation and the march of the armies. FELICITY. It is FAVORABLE to APPOINT feudal PRINCES and send the ARMY. The time of enthusiasm is founded on the presence of an important person who is in empathy with the soul of the people and acts in accordance with it. For this reason, voluntary and general obedience is given to them. In order to awaken enthusiasm, it is therefore necessary that in their dispositions they adhere to the nature of those they lead. In this rule of movement that follows the line of least resistance, the inviolability of natural laws is founded. These do not constitute something external to things but the harmony of the movement immanent in things. For this cause, the celestial bodies do not deviate from their orbits and all natural occurrence takes place with firm regularity. In a similar way, things present themselves in human society. Within it too, only those laws can be imposed that are rooted in the feeling of the people, for laws that contradict that feeling only arouse resentment. Enthusiasm also makes it possible to appoint helpers for the execution of tasks without the need to anticipate secret reactions. On the other hand, enthusiasm is capable of unifying mass movements, as in the case of war, to the point of obtaining victory.","Thunder issues rumbling from the earth: The image of Enthusiasm. Thus the ancient kings made music to honor merit, and offered it with splendor to the supreme God, and invited their ancestors to be present. When, at the beginning of summer, the electrical energy of thunder returns hastening from the earth, and the first storm refreshes nature, the ancient kings understood this as a sign to create music. Music was not merely entertainment but a sacred act that harmonized the human world with the cosmic order. The thunder that issues from the earth represents the awakening of creative energy from below. The ancient kings responded to this energy with music that honored virtue and connected heaven and earth. Through music, the merits of heroes and ancestors were celebrated, and the connection between the human and the divine was renewed. 86. The power of music. The wise dragon advises you to respond to the awakening of creative energy with joy and celebration. Music, art, and celebration harmonize the human spirit with the cosmic order. ○ Initial six: Enthusiasm that expresses itself brings misfortune. Enthusiasm that EXPRESSES itself brings MISFORTUNE. At the beginning of the time of enthusiasm, one must not express enthusiasm too loudly or too soon. Premature expression of enthusiasm can lead to disappointment and misfortune. One must first feel the enthusiasm deeply before expressing it outwardly. 87. Reserved enthusiasm. The wise dragon advises you to feel enthusiasm deeply before expressing it outwardly. Premature expression can lead to disappointment. Six in the second place means: Persistence like a rock. Not a whole day. Perseverance brings good fortune. Persistence like a ROCK. Not a whole DAY. PERSEVERANCE brings GOOD FORTUNE. One is firm as a rock in one's convictions. One does not waste a whole day in hesitation. The moment one recognizes the truth, one acts immediately. This firmness and swiftness bring good fortune. True enthusiasm is not mere excitement but a deep conviction that leads to immediate and decisive action. 88. Firm as a rock. The wise dragon advises you to be firm in your convictions. When you recognize the truth, act immediately. Do not waste time in hesitation. Six in the third place means: Enthusiasm looks upward. Remorse. Hesitation brings remorse. Enthusiasm LOOKS UPWARD. REMORSE. HESITATION brings REMORSE. One looks upward to those in authority for signs of enthusiasm. But if one hesitates too long, the moment passes and remorse follows. One must not wait for others to show the way but must generate one's own enthusiasm from within. 89. Self-generated enthusiasm. The wise dragon advises you to generate your own enthusiasm from within. Do not wait for others to lead the way. Hesitation brings remorse. Nine in the fourth place means: The source of enthusiasm. Attain great things. Have no doubts. Friends gather around you as a hairpin gathers the hair. The SOURCE of ENTHUSIASM. Attain GREAT THINGS. Have NO DOUBTS. Friends GATHER around you as a HAIRPIN gathers the HAIR. One is the source of enthusiasm for others. Like a hairpin that gathers the hair, one's enthusiasm draws friends and collaborators together. When one is the source rather than a reflector of enthusiasm, great things can be attained. 90. The source of enthusiasm. The wise dragon advises you to be the source of enthusiasm for others. Your genuine passion will attract collaborators and achieve great things. Nine in the fifth place means: Persistently ill. But does not die. PERSISTENTLY ILL. But does NOT DIE. One is in a position of authority but is surrounded by inferior people who try to suppress one's enthusiasm. This is like a persistent illness that does not kill. Despite the pressure, one's inner enthusiasm remains alive. One does not die to one's vision. The illness is persistent but not fatal. 91. Enduring enthusiasm. The wise dragon advises you to keep your inner enthusiasm alive even when surrounded by those who try to suppress it. Your vision will survive. At the top a six means: Deluded enthusiasm. But if, after completion, one changes, there is no blame. DELUDED enthusiasm. But if, after COMPLETION, one CHANGES, there is NO BLAME. One has been deluded by false enthusiasm — enthusiasm that was based on illusion rather than reality. But if, after the completion of the action, one recognizes the error and changes, there is no blame. The capacity to recognize one's mistakes and change course is the mark of wisdom. 92. Correcting false enthusiasm. The wise dragon advises you to distinguish between genuine enthusiasm and delusion. If you have been misled, recognize the error and change course. There is no blame in correction."],
  [17,"Following",["adaptation", "following", "renewal", "flexibility", "movement"],"Following brings supreme success. Perseverance is favorable. Without blame. Following. Supreme success. One must continue on the path. Without error. FOLLOWING. Let a GREATER SACRIFICE be performed. A FAVORABLE ORACLE. WITHOUT BLAME. The time of following is based on the relationship between the strong and the weak, between the one who leads and the one who follows. If the strong places itself below the weak, the weak follows with joy. This is the principle of following. To be followed, one must know how to follow. The one who leads must adapt to the conditions of the time and to the nature of those who follow. Only thus can following bring supreme success. If one forces others to follow, the result is resistance and blame. But if one leads with gentleness and perseverance, others follow freely and success is assured.","Thunder in the midst of the lake: The image of Following. Thus the superior person at evening enters and rests. When thunder appears in the lake, it indicates a time of rest and renewal. The superior person follows the rhythm of the day: working during the daylight hours and resting when evening comes. This is the natural way of following the order of things. By adapting to the natural rhythms, one achieves harmony and success. 93. Natural following. The wise dragon advises you to follow the natural rhythms of life. Rest when it is time to rest, work when it is time to work. Harmony comes from adaptation. ○ Initial nine: The standard is changing. Perseverance brings good fortune. Going out of the door one meets merit. The STANDARD is CHANGING. PERSEVERANCE brings GOOD FORTUNE. Going out of the DOOR one meets MERIT. At the beginning of the time of following, the standards are changing. One must adapt to the new conditions with perseverance. By going out and meeting others with merit, one establishes the bonds of following. 94. Changing standards. The wise dragon advises you to adapt to changing conditions with perseverance. Go out and meet others with merit. Six in the second place means: If one clings to the little boy, one loses the strong man. If one CLINGS to the LITTLE BOY, one LOSES the STRONG MAN. One must choose whom to follow. If one clings to the inferior, one loses the superior. One must follow those who are worthy and strong, not those who are merely close or comfortable. 95. Choosing whom to follow. The wise dragon advises you to choose your leaders wisely. Follow those who are strong and worthy, not those who are merely comfortable. Six in the third place means: If one clings to the strong man, one loses the little boy. Through following one finds what one seeks. It is favorable to remain persevering. If one CLINGS to the STRONG MAN, one LOSES the LITTLE BOY. Through FOLLOWING one finds what one seeks. It is FAVORABLE to REMAIN PERSEVERING. When one follows the strong, one may lose the comfortable, but one gains what one truly seeks. Perseverance in following the right path brings its reward. 96. Following the strong. The wise dragon advises you to follow those who are strong and worthy. You may lose comfort but gain what you truly seek. Nine in the fourth place means: Following brings supreme success. If one is sincere, one is without blame. FOLLOWING brings SUPREME SUCCESS. If one is SINCERE, one is WITHOUT BLAME. One is in a position of leadership. Others follow because of one's sincerity and strength. This is the highest form of following — when the leader is sincere and the followers are genuine. Supreme success is assured. 97. Sincere following. The wise dragon advises you to lead with sincerity. When followers are genuine, supreme success follows. Nine in the fifth place means: Sincere in the good. Good fortune. SINCERE in the GOOD. GOOD FORTUNE. One is in the position of honor. One is sincere in pursuing the good. This sincerity attracts others and brings good fortune. The leader who is genuinely committed to the good creates a community of following that is both natural and beneficial. 98. Sincere goodness. The wise dragon advises you to be sincere in your pursuit of the good. Genuine commitment attracts others naturally. At the top a six means: They meet with loyalty and are bound even more. The king introduces them to the western mountain. They meet with LOYALTY and are BOUND even more. The KING introduces them to the WESTERN MOUNTAIN. The time of following reaches its culmination. Those who have followed with loyalty are bound even more closely to the leader. The king, representing the highest authority, introduces them to the sacred mountain — the place where heaven and earth meet. This is the ultimate reward for faithful following. 99. The reward of loyalty. The wise dragon advises you that faithful following brings the highest rewards. Loyalty is recognized and celebrated."],
  [18,"Work on What Has Been Spoiled",["renewal", "correction", "work", "repair", "inheritance"],"Work on what has been spoiled brings supreme success. It is favorable to cross the great waters. Before the starting point, three days. After the starting point, three days. Decay. Supreme success. It is beneficial to cross the great water. Three days before the critical point, three days after. CORRUPTION. Let a GREATER SACRIFICE be performed. It is FAVORABLE to CROSS the GREAT RIVER. Use ARMOR THREE DAYS BEFORE, Use ARMOR THREE DAYS AFTER. What has been spoiled through the fault of humans can be made good again through the work of humans. It is not an immutable destiny, as in the time of Standstill (hexagram 12), that has caused the corruption, but rather the abuse of human freedom. Working to improve the situation is promising, since it is in concordance with the possibilities of the time. We must not shrink from the work and the danger symbolized by crossing the great waters but rather devote ourselves to it with energy. Success depends, however, on proper deliberation. This is expressed in the lines 'before the starting point, three days. After the starting point, three days.' One must first know the causes of corruption before eradicating them; therefore one must be careful during the time before the beginning. Then it will be possible to verify that the new ways function securely. The capacity for decision and energy must replace the inertia and indifference that led to decadence, so that a new beginning may follow.","The wind blows at the lower parts of the mountain; The image of Decay. Thus the superior person mobilizes their fellow beings and strengthens their spirit. When the wind blows slowly on the mountain, it encounters resistance and in doing so generates whirlwinds that ruin the vegetation. This presents a challenge for the superior person, who must mobilize others and strengthen their spirit to overcome the damage caused by decadence. Like the wind that must overcome the mountain's resistance, the superior person must work to restore what has been spoiled. 100. Overcoming decay. The wise dragon advises you to confront decay with energy and determination. Mobilize others and strengthen their spirit. Restoration is possible. ○ Initial six: Setting right what has been spoiled by the father. If there is a son, the blame rests on the deceased. Danger. In the end, good fortune. Setting RIGHT what has been SPOILED by the FATHER. If there is a SON, the BLAME rests on the DECEASED. DANGER. In the END, GOOD FORTUNE. One takes on the task of correcting what the previous generation has spoiled. This is a dangerous task, for it involves confronting the legacy of the past. But if one approaches it with the respect of a son for the father, the danger is overcome and good fortune follows. 101. Correcting the past. The wise dragon advises you to correct past errors with respect and determination. Confronting the legacy of the past is dangerous but necessary. Nine in the second place means: Setting right what has been spoiled by the mother. One must not be too persevering. Setting RIGHT what has been SPOILED by the MOTHER. One must NOT be too PERSEVERING. When correcting what has been spoiled by the feminine principle — by excessive gentleness or indulgence — one must not be too forceful. Excessive severity in correction creates new problems. A balanced approach is needed. 102. Balanced correction. The wise dragon advises you to be balanced in your corrections. Do not be too forceful when addressing the consequences of excessive gentleness. Nine in the third place means: Setting right what has been spoiled by the father. There will be little remorse. Setting RIGHT what has been SPOILED by the FATHER. There will be LITTLE REMORSE. One confronts the errors of the previous generation with determination. There may be some remorse for the harshness of the correction, but it is minimal because the work is necessary and just. 103. Necessary correction. The wise dragon advises you to confront past errors with determination. Some remorse is natural but the work is necessary. Six in the fourth place means: Tolerating what has been spoiled by the father. In continuing, one sees humiliation. TOLERATING what has been SPOILED by the FATHER. In CONTINUING, one sees HUMILIATION. If one tolerates the corruption inherited from the past and does nothing to correct it, humiliation follows. Inaction in the face of decay is itself a form of complicity. 104. The danger of tolerance. The wise dragon advises you not to tolerate corruption inherited from the past. Inaction leads to humiliation. Six in the fifth place means: Setting right what has been spoiled by the father. One meets with praise. Setting RIGHT what has been SPOILED by the FATHER. One meets with PRAISE. One successfully corrects the errors of the previous generation. This achievement is recognized and praised. The work of restoration brings honor. 105. Praised restoration. The wise dragon advises you that successful restoration of past errors brings honor and praise. At the top a nine means: One does not serve kings and princes. One sets oneself higher goals. One does NOT serve KINGS and PRINCES. One sets oneself HIGHER GOALS. The time of working on decay has reached its culmination. One is no longer content with serving the established order but sets oneself higher goals. The work of correction has freed one from the limitations of the past, and now one can aim at something greater. 106. Higher goals. The wise dragon advises you to set yourself higher goals once the work of correction is complete. Freedom from the past opens the way to greater achievements."],
  [19,"Approach",["influence", "drawing near", "leadership", "growth", "supervision"],"Approach brings supreme success. Perseverance is favorable. When the eighth month arrives, there will be misfortune. Approach. Supreme success. Correct persistence is rewarded. In the eighth month there will be evil. APPROACH. Let a GREATER SACRIFICE be performed. A FAVORABLE ORACLE. The ARRIVAL of the EIGHTH MONTH brings MISFORTUNE. The hexagram as a whole refers to a time of joyful and hopeful progress. Joy and good will cause those in high and low positions to draw near together. Success is certain. But it is necessary to work with determination and perseverance to make the most of the propitious times. And something more: spring is not forever. In the eighth month, the aspects are reversed. Then only two strong and illuminated lines remain; these do not advance but retreat (see the following hexagram). We must be conscious of this change in the good times. If we confront evil before it becomes a reality, before it even manifests, it is possible to overcome it.","The earth above the lake: The image of Approach. Thus the superior person is inexhaustible in their disposition to teach, and knows no bounds in their tolerance and disposition to protect the people. The earth borders the lake from above. This symbolizes approach and condescension, in the sense of the good will of the superior person toward those below. The two elements of the image indicate what their attitude toward those people will be. Insofar as the lake is inexhaustible in its depth, the sage is inexhaustible in their disposition to teach humanity. Insofar as the earth is broad and without borders, allowing it to sustain and provide for all creatures, the sage is broad and without borders in their tolerance and protection of the people. 107. Inexhaustible teaching. The wise dragon advises you to be inexhaustible in your willingness to teach and protect. Like the earth above the lake, be broad and deep in your care for others. ○ Initial nine: Joint approach. Perseverance brings good fortune. JOINT approach. PERSEVERANCE brings GOOD FORTUNE. At the beginning of the time of approach, one advances together with others. This joint approach, sustained by perseverance, brings good fortune. One does not advance alone but as part of a community. 108. Joint approach. The wise dragon advises you to advance together with others. Community effort brings good fortune. Nine in the second place means: Joint approach. Good fortune. Everything is favorable. JOINT approach. GOOD FORTUNE. Everything is FAVORABLE. The approach continues with the support of others. Everything is favorable because the advance is made with the right attitude and in the right direction. 109. Favorable advance. The wise dragon advises you that when the approach is made with the right attitude, everything is favorable. Six in the third place means: Comfortable approach. Nothing that would further. If one is induced to grieve over it, one is free of blame. COMFORTABLE approach. Nothing that would FURTHER. If one is INDUCED to GRIEVE over it, one is FREE of BLAME. One approaches with too much comfort and complacency. This is not favorable. But if one recognizes the error and feels concern, one is free of blame. Self-reflection prevents the error from becoming permanent. 110. The danger of complacency. The wise dragon advises you not to approach with complacency. Recognize your errors and correct them. Six in the fourth place means: Complete approach. No blame. COMPLETE approach. NO BLAME. One approaches with complete sincerity and devotion. There is no reservation or holding back. This complete approach is without blame because it is genuine and wholehearted. 111. Complete approach. The wise dragon advises you to approach with complete sincerity. Wholehearted engagement is without blame. Six in the fifth place means: Wise approach. This is right for the great prince. Good fortune. WISE approach. This is RIGHT for the GREAT PRINCE. GOOD FORTUNE. The ruler approaches with wisdom. This is the right way for a leader — to approach those below with wisdom and understanding. Such an approach brings good fortune because it is based on genuine knowledge and care. 112. Wise leadership. The wise dragon advises you to approach others with wisdom and understanding. Wise leadership brings good fortune. At the top a six means: Magnanimous approach. Good fortune. No blame. MAGNANIMOUS approach. GOOD FORTUNE. NO BLAME. The approach reaches its culmination in magnanimity. One approaches with generosity and greatness of spirit. This brings good fortune and is without blame. Magnanimity is the highest form of approach. 113. Magnanimous approach. The wise dragon advises you to approach with magnanimity. Generosity and greatness of spirit bring the highest good fortune."],
  [20,"Contemplation",["observation", "vision", "silent influence", "presence", "model"],"Contemplation. The ablution has occurred, but the offerings have not yet been presented. Full of confidence they raise their gaze to them. Contemplation. The ablution has been performed, but the sacrifice still occurs. Authenticity gains respect. CONTEMPLATION. The ABLUTIONS have been made. But there is no WORSHIP. MAINTAINING CONFIDENCE is something NOBLE. The ritual of sacrifices in China began with an ablution and a libation in which God was invoked; then the sacrifice was made. The brief interval between these two ceremonies is the most sacred of all, the moment of deepest concentration. If piety is sincere and expresses a true faith, the contemplation of this fact has a transforming effect, provoking awe in those who observe it. Thus, too, in nature a sacred seriousness is observed in the fact that natural occurrences are uniformly subject to law. The contemplation of the divine meaning underlying the operation of the universe offers the means to produce similar effects in the person called upon to influence others. This requires the power of inner concentration that religious contemplation develops in great people, strong in their faith. This allows them to understand the mysterious and divine laws of life and, through the deepest inner concentration, to express these laws in their persons. Thus a hidden spiritual power emanates from them, which influences and dominates others without their being aware of how this occurs.","The wind blows over the earth; The image of Contemplation. Thus the kings of ancient times visited the regions of the world, contemplated the people, and taught them. When the wind blows over the earth it travels far and in many directions, and the grass must yield to its power. These two facts are confirmed in the hexagram. The two images complete each other. The wind that travels over the earth represents the king who travels through the world to contemplate the state of the people and to impart teaching. Like the wind that bends the grass, the king's influence reaches everywhere and all submit to it. But this influence is not based on force but on the power of contemplation and example. The king first contemplates the people — understands their needs and conditions — and then teaches them. Teaching that is based on genuine understanding has the power of the wind that bends all grass before it. 114. The power of example. The wise dragon advises you to contemplate before you teach. Understanding the needs of others gives your teaching the power of the wind. ○ Initial six: Childlike contemplation. For an inferior person, no blame. For a superior person, humiliation. CHILDLIKE contemplation. For an INFERIOR PERSON, NO BLAME. For a SUPERIOR PERSON, HUMILIATION. At the beginning of the time of contemplation, one's view is limited and childlike. For an ordinary person, this is not blameworthy. But for someone in a position of responsibility, a limited view is humiliating. One must strive to see beyond the surface. 115. Limited view. The wise dragon advises you to expand your view. Do not remain satisfied with a childlike understanding. Seek deeper contemplation. Six in the second place means: Contemplation through the crack of the door. It is favorable for the perseverance of a sage. CONTEMPLATION through the CRACK of the DOOR. It is FAVORABLE for the PERSEVERANCE of a SAGE. One contemplates from a limited vantage point — through the crack of a door. The view is partial but not entirely wrong. For a sage who perseveres in contemplation, even this limited view can be a starting point for deeper understanding. 116. Partial view. The wise dragon advises you that even a partial view can be a starting point for deeper contemplation. Persevere in your search for understanding. Six in the third place means: Contemplation of my life decides the choice between advance and retreat. CONTEMPLATION of my LIFE decides the choice between ADVANCE and RETREAT. One contemplates one's own life and the effects of one's actions. This self-contemplation determines whether one should advance or retreat. One must be honest in assessing one's own condition and the impact one has on others. 117. Self-contemplation. The wise dragon advises you to contemplate your own life honestly. Self-knowledge determines the right course of action. Nine in the fourth place means: Contemplation of the light of the kingdom. It is favorable to be the guest of the king. CONTEMPLATION of the LIGHT of the KINGDOM. It is FAVORABLE to be the GUEST of the KING. One contemplates the light of the kingdom — the overall state of affairs. This broad view allows one to understand the forces at work and to position oneself favorably. Being the guest of the king means being recognized for one's wisdom and invited to participate in the governance of the realm. 118. The broad view. The wise dragon advises you to contemplate the broad picture. Understanding the overall state of affairs allows you to position yourself favorably. Nine in the fifth place means: Contemplation of my life. The superior person is without blame. CONTEMPLATION of my LIFE. The SUPERIOR PERSON is WITHOUT BLAME. One in the position of honor contemplates their own life and the effects of their actions on the people. This self-contemplation ensures that the leader remains aware of their impact and acts accordingly. The superior person who contemplates their life is without blame because they are constantly correcting their course. 119. The leader's contemplation. The wise dragon advises you to constantly contemplate the effects of your actions on others. Self-correction keeps you without blame. At the top a nine means: Contemplation of their life. The superior person is without blame. CONTEMPLATION of their LIFE. The SUPERIOR PERSON is WITHOUT BLAME. At the top of the hexagram, the contemplation reaches its highest point. One contemplates not only one's own life but the life of the entire community. This universal contemplation is the mark of the sage who has transcended the personal and sees from the perspective of the whole. 120. Universal contemplation. The wise dragon advises you to transcend the personal and contemplate from the perspective of the whole. Universal vision is the mark of the sage."],
  [21,"Biting Through",["justice", "clarity", "overcoming obstacles", "decision", "law"],"Biting through brings success. It is favorable to administer justice. Bite through decisively. Success. It is time to observe the law. BITE and TEAR AWAY. Let a GREATER SACRIFICE be performed. It is FAVORABLE to INVOKE the LAW. When an obstacle to union appears, a decisive bite brings success. This is true in all situations. Whenever unity cannot be achieved, the obstruction is due to a slanderer and traitor who interferes and blocks the way. To prevent permanent damage, vigorous measures must be taken as quickly as possible. The deliberate obstruction of this type disappears by itself. Judgment and punishment are required to eliminate it or to circumvent it. However, it is necessary to proceed correctly. The hexagram combines Li, the Clarity, and Chên, the Arousing. Li yields and Chên is firm. Unqualified hardness and emotion could be too severe in fixing punishments. Unqualified clarity and gentleness would be too weak. Both create the just measure. It is crucial that the person making the decisions, represented by the fifth line, be gentle by nature but also inspire respect through their conduct in their position.","Thunder and lightning: The image of Biting Through. Thus the ancient kings made the laws firm through clearly established penalties. Penalties are the specific applications of the law. The law specifies punishments. Clarity prevails when severe punishments are differentiated from lesser ones according to the nature of the crimes. This is represented by the clarity of lightning. The law is strengthened through the just application of laws. This is represented by the terror of thunder. This clarity and severity has the effect of inspiring respect. It is not that the punishments are cruel, but that they are clear and just. When the law is applied with both clarity and firmness, it removes obstacles to justice just as biting through removes obstacles to chewing. 121. Clear justice. The wise dragon advises you to apply justice with both clarity and firmness. Clear and just laws remove obstacles to harmony. ○ Initial nine: One's feet are fastened in the stocks, so that the toes disappear. Without blame. One's FEET are FASTENED in the STOCKS, so that the TOES DISAPPEAR. WITHOUT BLAME. At the beginning, the punishment is mild — the feet are merely fastened in stocks. This is appropriate for a first offense. The punishment is designed to prevent further wrongdoing, not to inflict unnecessary suffering. There is no blame in this mild correction. 122. Mild correction. The wise dragon advises you to begin with mild correction. Punishment should prevent wrongdoing, not inflict suffering. Six in the second place means: Biting through tender meat, so that the nose disappears. Without blame. Biting through TENDER MEAT, so that the NOSE DISAPPEARS. WITHOUT BLAME. The punishment is slightly more severe — biting through tender meat. The nose disappears, meaning the punishment is noticeable but not disfiguring. This is appropriate for a second offense. 123. Noticeable correction. The wise dragon advises you to increase the severity of correction gradually. The punishment should fit the offense. Six in the third place means: Biting through old dried meat and strikes upon something poisonous. Slight humiliation. Without blame. Biting through OLD DRIED MEAT and strikes upon something POISONOUS. Slight HUMILIATION. WITHOUT BLAME. The punishment encounters resistance — like biting through old dried meat that also contains something poisonous. This represents a difficult case where the offender is hardened. The punishment may cause slight humiliation, but it is necessary and without blame. 124. Difficult justice. The wise dragon advises you to persist in justice even when encountering resistance. Hardened offenders require firm correction. Nine in the fourth place means: Biting through dried gristle. Gets golden arrows. It is favorable to think of the difficulties and be steadfast. Biting through DRIED CARTILAGE. Gets GOLDEN ARROWS. It is FAVORABLE to think of the DIFFICULTIES and be STEADFAST. The case is difficult — like biting through dried cartilage. But one has the golden arrows — the straight and unbending quality of justice. By thinking of the difficulties and remaining steadfast, one overcomes the obstacle. 125. Steadfast justice. The wise dragon advises you to remain steadfast in justice even when the case is difficult. The golden arrows of justice will overcome any obstacle. Six in the fifth place means: Biting through dried lean meat. Gets yellow gold. Perseveringly aware of danger. Without blame. Biting through DRIED LEAN MEAT. Gets YELLOW GOLD. PERSEVERINGLY aware of DANGER. WITHOUT BLAME. One is in the position of the judge. The case is difficult but one handles it with care. The yellow gold represents the middle way — justice that is neither too severe nor too lenient. By remaining aware of the danger of injustice, one acts without blame. 126. The middle way of justice. The wise dragon advises you to apply justice with the middle way — neither too severe nor too lenient. Awareness of danger prevents error. At the top a nine means: One's neck is fastened in the wooden cang, so that the ears disappear. Misfortune. One's NECK is FASTENED in the WOODEN CANG, so that the EARS DISAPPEAR. MISFORTUNE. The punishment is extreme — the neck is fastened in a heavy wooden frame, and the ears disappear. This represents a case where the offender has gone too far and the punishment must be severe. But this is also a warning: if one does not heed earlier corrections, the consequences become ever more severe. 127. The final warning. The wise dragon advises you to heed corrections before they become severe. Persistent wrongdoing leads to ever harsher consequences."],
  [22,"Grace",["adornment", "beauty", "form", "clarity", "art"],"Grace brings success. In small things it is favorable to undertake something. Grace, adornment or elegance. Success. One loses the advantage if one takes the lead. ADORNMENT. Let a SACRIFICE be performed. IN SMALL THINGS it is FAVORABLE to PROCEED WITH a PURPOSE. Grace is not a serious matter. It is a question of secondary importance. It concerns the form rather than the substance. Grace brings success in small things because it makes life pleasant and agreeable. But it should not be confused with what is essential. The person who is content with grace and does not strive for what is substantive will lose their way. Grace is like the light of the moon that illuminates the landscape but does not warm it. It is beautiful but not vital. In important matters, one must rely on substance, not form.","Fire at the base of the mountain: The image of Grace. Thus the superior person, when clarifying current affairs, does not dare to decide important cases on this basis. Fire at the base of the mountain illuminates the forms of things with its light. Everything appears beautiful and clear. But this illumination is only about the surface — the form, not the substance. The superior person, when clarifying current affairs, uses this illuminating quality to bring clarity to everyday matters. But when it comes to important cases — matters of life and death, of justice and injustice — the superior person does not dare to decide on the basis of appearance alone. Form must yield to substance in matters of consequence. 128. Form and substance. The wise dragon advises you to distinguish between form and substance. Grace illuminates the surface, but important matters require deeper judgment. ○ Initial nine: They give grace to the toes, leave the wagon, and walk. They give GRACE to the TOES, leave the WAGON, and WALK. At the beginning of the time of grace, one chooses to walk rather than ride. This is a sign of humility — one does not use the wagon of status but walks with one's own feet. The grace is in the simplicity of the gesture. 129. Simple grace. The wise dragon advises you that true grace lies in simplicity. Do not use status symbols when simplicity is more appropriate. Nine in the second place means: Giving grace to the beard on the chin. Giving GRACE to the BEARD on the CHIN. The beard follows the movement of the chin. This represents grace that is purely ornamental — it follows the movement of what is substantial but has no independent movement of its own. Ornament should always be subordinate to substance. 130. Ornamental grace. The wise dragon advises you to keep ornament subordinate to substance. Grace should enhance, not replace, what is essential. Nine in the third place means: Graceful and radiant. Eternal perseverance brings good fortune. GRACEFUL and RADIANT. ETERNAL PERSEVERANCE brings GOOD FORTUNE. One is in a position where grace and radiance are in harmony. The external beauty reflects inner quality. When this harmony is maintained through eternal perseverance, good fortune follows. 131. Harmonious grace. The wise dragon advises you to cultivate harmony between inner quality and outer grace. When they reflect each other, good fortune follows. Six in the fourth place means: Grace or simplicity? A white horse comes as if on wings. One is not a robber but will wed at the right time. GRACE or SIMPLICITY? A WHITE HORSE comes as if on WINGS. One is NOT A ROBBER but will WED at the RIGHT TIME. One faces a choice between grace and simplicity. The white horse that comes as if on wings represents the suitor who approaches with pure intentions. This is not a robber but a genuine partner. The right choice is simplicity — the pure white horse that comes without adornment. 132. The choice of simplicity. The wise dragon advises you to choose simplicity over mere ornament. Pure intentions are more valuable than beautiful appearances. Six in the fifth place means: Grace in hills and gardens. The roll of silk is meager and small. Humiliation, but in the end good fortune. GRACE in HILLS and GARDENS. The ROLL of SILK is MEAGER and SMALL. HUMILIATION, but in the END GOOD FORTUNE. One seeks grace in elevated places — hills and gardens. But the offering is meager. This may seem humiliating, but sincerity in small things eventually brings good fortune. The quality of the offering matters more than its size. 133. Sincere offering. The wise dragon advises you that sincerity in small things is more valuable than grand gestures. A meager but sincere offering brings good fortune. At the top a nine means: Simple grace. Without blame. SIMPLE GRACE. WITHOUT BLAME. At the culmination of the time of grace, one returns to simplicity. Simple grace — grace without adornment — is the highest form. It is without blame because it is genuine and unpretentious. 134. Simple grace. The wise dragon advises you that the highest form of grace is simplicity. Unadorned genuineness is the most beautiful ornament."],
  [23,"Splitting Apart",["dissolution", "patience", "stillness", "adaptation", "decay"],"Splitting apart. It is not favorable to undertake anything. Splitting apart. There is no favorable objective. SPLITTING APART. It is NOT FAVORABLE to PROCEED WITH a PURPOSE. This symbol represents a time in which inferior people are on the rise and the superior person must yield. The five yin lines push upward, threatening to expel the last yang line. This is a time of disintegration, in which what is dark and weak increases while what is light and strong is pushed out. It is not a time for action but for patient endurance. The superior person understands the conditions of the time and does not resist the inevitable but waits for the cycle to turn. Like the mountain that rests on the earth, the superior person remains stable while the world around them crumbles.","The mountain rests on the earth: The image of Splitting Apart. Thus those in superior positions can only strengthen their position by giving to those below. The mountain rests on the earth. Its greatness is based on its foundation. If the foundation crumbles, the mountain falls. Thus those in superior positions can only strengthen their position by giving to those below. If the superior person recognizes that their position depends on the support of others, they will be generous and give freely. This generosity strengthens the foundation and ensures stability. But in the time of splitting apart, even generosity may not be enough. The disintegration must run its course before renewal can begin. 135. The foundation. The wise dragon advises you to strengthen your foundation by giving to those below. Your position depends on the support of others. ○ Initial six: The leg of the bed is split. Those who destroy perseverance. Misfortune. The LEG of the BED is SPLIT. Those who DESTROY PERSEVERANCE. MISFORTUNE. The splitting apart begins at the base — the leg of the bed. This represents the destruction of the foundation. Those who undermine perseverance cause misfortune. When the foundation is attacked, the entire structure is threatened. 136. The crumbling foundation. The wise dragon advises you to recognize when the foundation is being undermined. Attack on the base threatens the entire structure. Six in the second place means: The bed is split at the edge. Those who destroy perseverance. Misfortune. The BED is SPLIT at the EDGE. Those who DESTROY PERSEVERANCE. MISFORTUNE. The splitting spreads upward from the base to the edge of the bed. The destruction is advancing. Those who undermine perseverance continue their destructive work. The situation worsens. 137. Advancing destruction. The wise dragon advises you to recognize the advance of destruction. When the splitting spreads, the situation becomes more dangerous. Six in the third place means: He splits with them. No blame. He SPLITS with them. NO BLAME. One separates from those who are causing the destruction. This is not betrayal but self-preservation. By splitting with the destructive forces, one preserves one's integrity. There is no blame in refusing to participate in destruction. 138. Separation from destruction. The wise dragon advises you to separate yourself from destructive forces. Refusing to participate in destruction preserves your integrity. Six in the fourth place means: The bed is split down to the skin. Misfortune. The BED is SPLIT down to the SKIN. MISFORTUNE. The splitting has reached the surface — the skin. The destruction is now visible and immediate. There is no longer any room for compromise. The situation has become critical. 139. Critical situation. The wise dragon advises you to recognize when a situation has become critical. When destruction reaches the surface, decisive action is needed. Six in the fifth place means: A school of fishes. Everything favors the one in the middle. A SCHOOL of FISHES. Everything FAVORS the one in the MIDDLE. Like a school of fishes that follows the lead fish, the people look to the one in the middle for guidance. In times of splitting apart, the leader who remains centered and true can still guide others through the crisis. 140. Centered leadership. The wise dragon advises you to remain centered in times of crisis. Others look to you for guidance. Your stability is their anchor. At the top a nine means: There is a large fruit still uneaten. The superior person receives a wagon. The small person's hut is stripped. There is a large FRUIT still UNEATEN. The SUPERIOR PERSON receives a WAGON. The SMALL PERSON's HUT is STRIPPED. The time of splitting apart reaches its end. The large fruit that remains uneaten represents the seed of renewal — the yang line that survives the onslaught of yin. The superior person, who has endured the splitting apart, receives the wagon of recognition. But the small person, who caused the destruction, loses everything. 141. The seed of renewal. The wise dragon advises you that even in the darkest time of splitting apart, the seed of renewal survives. Endure and the cycle will turn."],
  [24,"Return",["renewal", "return", "hope", "cycles", "rebirth"],"Return. Success. Going out and coming in without error. Friends arrive without blame. Going and returning along the path, on the seventh day comes the return. It is favorable to have somewhere to go. Return. Success. Going out and returning without error. FRIENDS arrive WITHOUT BLAME. Going and RETURNING along the PATH. On the SEVENTH DAY comes the RETURN. It is FAVORABLE to HAVE somewhere to GO. The return of the light after darkness. The turning point after the splitting apart. The yang line returns to the bottom position, beginning a new cycle of growth. This is the solstice — the moment when the longest night gives way to the return of light. Friends arrive without blame because they come at the right time, in response to the natural turning of the cycle. The path of return is the path of nature itself. On the seventh day, the return comes — the cycle completes and begins anew. It is favorable to have somewhere to go because the energy of return supports all forward movement.","Thunder within the earth: The image of the Return. Thus the kings of old, at the time of the winter solstice, closed the passes. The thunder that was within the earth retreats to its place. The winter solstice marks the moment of return — the return of light after the longest night. The ancient kings understood that this was a time for rest, not for action. They closed the passes so that no one would travel, allowing the earth to rest and the new light to establish itself. This is the way of heaven — a time for return, for stillness, for the gathering of strength before the new cycle begins. 142. The time of return. The wise dragon advises you to honor the time of return. Rest and gather your strength. The new cycle is beginning. ○ Initial nine: Return from a short distance. No need for remorse. Great good fortune. RETURN from a SHORT DISTANCE. No need for REMORSE. Great GOOD FORTUNE. One has gone only a short distance before returning. The error was small and the return was quick. There is no need for remorse because the mistake was recognized and corrected immediately. This brings great good fortune. 143. Quick return. The wise dragon advises you to return quickly when you recognize an error. Swift correction brings great good fortune. Six in the second place means: Quiet return. Good fortune. QUIET RETURN. GOOD FORTUNE. One returns quietly, without fanfare or drama. This quiet return is the most natural and therefore the most fortunate. One does not make a spectacle of one's correction but simply returns to the right path. 144. Quiet return. The wise dragon advises you to return to the right path quietly and naturally. No drama is needed. Simple correction is the best. Six in the third place means: Repeated return. Danger. No blame. REPEATED RETURN. DANGER. NO BLAME. One returns again and again, each time straying a bit further before coming back. This is dangerous because the pattern may become entrenched. But as long as one continues to return, there is no blame. The important thing is to keep returning. 145. Repeated return. The wise dragon advises you to keep returning to the right path, even if you stray repeatedly. As long as you return, there is no blame. Six in the fourth place means: Walking in the midst of others, one returns to one's own self. Walking in the MIDST of OTHERS, one RETURNS to one's own SELF. One is surrounded by others but manages to return to one's own nature. This is the return of someone who has been distracted by the world but remembers their true self. It is a return from the outer to the inner. 146. Return to self. The wise dragon advises you to return to your true self, even when surrounded by distractions. Inner return is the most important return. Six in the fifth place means: Noblehearted return. No remorse. NOBLEHEARTED RETURN. NO REMORSE. One returns with a noble heart. The return is motivated by genuine self-knowledge and the desire to align with the way. There is no remorse because the return is wholehearted and sincere. 147. Noble return. The wise dragon advises you to return with a noble heart. Sincere return aligned with the way brings no remorse. At the top a six means: Missing the return. Misfortune. Misfortune from within and without. If one sets armies marching, one will in the end suffer a great defeat. Missing the RETURN. MISFORTUNE. MISFORTUNE from WITHIN and WITHOUT. If one sets ARMIES marching, one will in the END suffer a GREAT DEFEAT. One has missed the time for return. The cycle has passed and one has not turned back. This brings misfortune from both within and without — inner confusion and outer failure. If one tries to compensate by force — by setting armies marching — the result is only greater defeat. The time for return has been lost. 148. The missed return. The wise dragon advises you not to miss the time for return. When the moment to turn back arrives, act immediately. Hesitation leads to compounding misfortune."],
  [25,"Innocence",["spontaneity", "authenticity", "rectitude", "sincerity", "nature"],"Innocence. Supreme success. Perseverance is favorable. If someone is not as they should be, they have misfortune, and it is not favorable to undertake anything. INNOCENCE. Supreme success. PERSEVERANCE is FAVORABLE. If a person is NOT as they SHOULD BE, they have MISFORTUNE. And it is NOT FAVORABLE to undertake anything. The unexpected. Something that happens without one's having planned it. This is innocence in its original sense — the state of being in accordance with the original will of heaven. It is the state of natural purity, before the mind has been clouded by calculation or selfishness. When one acts from innocence, one is in harmony with the laws of the universe and success is assured. But if one departs from innocence — if one acts from calculation, selfishness, or dishonesty — misfortune follows inevitably. The person who is innocent does not know why they are successful; they simply act in accordance with their nature and everything works out. But the person who has lost their innocence tries to force outcomes and only creates more problems.","Under heaven, thunder rolls: All things attain the natural state of Innocence. Thus the kings of ancient times, rich in virtue and in harmony with heaven, bestowed their gifts on the right time. Under heaven, thunder rolls — the creative force moves with power and everything responds with natural innocence. The ancient kings observed this and understood that all things have their proper time and their proper way. They bestowed their gifts at the right time, following the natural order rather than imposing their own will. This is the way of innocence — acting in harmony with the natural rhythm of things. 149. Natural innocence. The wise dragon advises you to act from natural innocence. Follow the rhythm of things rather than forcing outcomes. ○ Initial nine: Innocent behavior brings good fortune. Innocent BEHAVIOR brings GOOD FORTUNE. At the beginning of the time of innocence, one acts with pure and natural behavior. This innocence is not ignorance but a deep alignment with the way of nature. It brings good fortune because it is in harmony with the universe. 150. Innocent behavior. The wise dragon advises you to act with natural simplicity. Innocence aligned with the way brings good fortune. Six in the second place means: If one does not count on personal harvests, one can eat. If one does not clear new fields, one will have food. Favorable to have somewhere to go. If one does NOT COUNT on personal HARVESTS, one can EAT. If one does NOT CLEAR new FIELDS, one will have FOOD. FAVORABLE to have somewhere to GO. One does not calculate or plan for personal gain. One trusts in the natural abundance of the universe. By not counting on personal harvests, one eats. By not clearing new fields, one has food. This is the paradox of innocence — by not striving, one receives. 151. Trust in abundance. The wise dragon advises you to trust in natural abundance. By not striving for personal gain, you receive what you need. Six in the third place means: Undue misfortune. The cow that was tethered is the gain of the passerby. UNDUE MISFORTUNE. The COW that was TETHERED is the GAIN of the PASSERBY. One suffers misfortune that is not deserved. Like a cow that was tethered for its owner but is taken by a passerby, one's good fortune is taken by another. This is the misfortune of innocence — sometimes the innocent suffer because of the actions of others. But this misfortune is not caused by one's own fault. 152. Undue misfortune. The wise dragon advises you that sometimes the innocent suffer. This misfortune is not your fault. Remain innocent and the natural order will restore balance. Nine in the fourth place means: Whoever can remain persevering remains without blame. Whoever can REMAIN PERSEVERING remains WITHOUT BLAME. In a position of responsibility, one must remain persevering in innocence. If one maintains one's natural purity despite the pressures of the world, one remains without blame. 153. Persevering innocence. The wise dragon advises you to remain persevering in innocence despite worldly pressures. Natural purity keeps you without blame. Nine in the fifth place means: Use no medicine in an illness incurred through no fault of your own. It will pass of itself. Use NO MEDICINE in an ILLNESS incurred through NO FAULT of your own. It will PASS of ITSELF. One suffers an illness that was not caused by one's own actions. This is an illness of innocence — a temporary disturbance that will pass naturally. No medicine is needed; the natural healing power of the universe will restore balance. 154. Natural healing. The wise dragon advises you that some illnesses heal naturally. Trust in the natural order. Do not force a cure. At the top a nine means: Innocent action brings misfortune. Nothing that would further. Innocent ACTION brings MISFORTUNE. Nothing that would FURTHER. At the top of the hexagram, the time of innocence has reached its extreme. Even innocent action brings misfortune because the time has changed. One must recognize that the conditions have shifted and adapt accordingly. What was once innocent may no longer be appropriate. 155. The end of innocence. The wise dragon advises you to recognize when conditions have changed. Even innocence must adapt to new times."],
  [26,"The Taming Power of the Great",["accumulation", "potential", "containment", "study", "virtue"],"The taming power of the great. Perseverance is favorable. Not eating at home brings good fortune. It is favorable to cross the great waters. Nourishing the great is encouraged. Thanks to persistence. It is favorable not to eat at home and to cross the great waters. A GREAT offering of LIVESTOCK. A FAVORABLE ORACLE. AUSPICIOUS to EAT OUTSIDE of HOME. It is FAVORABLE to CROSS the GREAT RIVER. Firmly subduing the great creative powers and keeping them under control, as this hexagram proposes, requires a strong person with clear ideas who is honored by the ruler. The trigram Ch'ien points to a powerful and creative force. Kên indicates firmness and truth. Both point to light and clarity, as well as to the daily renewal of character. Only through daily self-renewal can a person maintain themselves at the pinnacle of the power of their personality. However, since those who are deserving receive honors, as in the case of a strong personality to whom the ruler has entrusted the leadership, it is advantageous not to eat at home. Rather, it is convenient to accept a public office. Such a person is in harmony with heaven. Consequently, even great and difficult projects, like crossing the great waters, are successful.","Heaven within the mountain: The image of the taming power of the great. Thus the superior person familiarizes themselves with many sayings of antiquity and many deeds of the past, in order to strengthen their character in that way. Heaven within the mountain speaks to us of hidden treasures. In the words and deeds of the past there is a hidden treasure that people can use to strengthen and elevate their own character. The path of studying the past does not seek that one simply accumulates historical knowledge but rather that one penetrates the spirit of the ancients and makes their wisdom one's own. 156. Hidden treasures. The wise dragon advises you to study the wisdom of the past. In ancient words and deeds there are hidden treasures that strengthen your character. ○ Initial nine: Danger threatens. It is favorable to desist. DANGER threatens. It is FAVORABLE to DESIST. At the beginning of the time of taming the great, danger threatens. One must desist and not advance. The creative force is too powerful to be confronted directly. One must wait and gather strength. 157. The wisdom of restraint. The wise dragon advises you to desist when danger threatens. Waiting is wiser than confronting overwhelming force. Nine in the second place means: The axles of the wagon are taken off. The AXLES of the WAGON are TAKEN OFF. One voluntarily stops one's advance. Like removing the axles of a wagon, one prevents oneself from moving forward. This is not cowardice but wisdom — recognizing that the time is not yet right for action. 158. Voluntary halt. The wise dragon advises you to voluntarily halt your advance when the time is not right. Self-restraint is wisdom. Nine in the third place means: A good horse that follows others. It is favorable to think of the difficulty and to practice horsemanship daily. It is favorable to practice guarding. A good HORSE that FOLLOWS others. It is FAVORABLE to think of the DIFFICULTY and to practice HORSEMANSHIP daily. It is FAVORABLE to practice GUARDING. One follows a good horse — a strong and wise leader. One practices daily, preparing for the difficulties ahead. This preparation — like practicing horsemanship and guarding — ensures that one is ready when the time comes. 159. Daily preparation. The wise dragon advises you to prepare daily for the challenges ahead. Follow wise leaders and practice consistently. Six in the fourth place means: The headboard of a young bull. Great good fortune. The HEADBOARD of a young BULL. Great GOOD FORTUNE. One tames the creative force at its source — like placing a headboard on a young bull before its horns grow dangerous. This is the most effective way to tame great power — at the source, before it becomes uncontrollable. 160. Taming at the source. The wise dragon advises you to address great power at its source. Prevention is more effective than confrontation. Six in the fifth place means: The tusk of a gelded boar. Good fortune. The TUSK of a GELDED BOAR. GOOD FORTUNE. One addresses the root of the problem rather than its symptoms. Like gelding a boar, which removes the source of its aggression, one removes the root cause of the difficulty. This brings good fortune because the problem is solved at its source. 161. Root solution. The wise dragon advises you to address problems at their root. Removing the source of difficulty brings lasting good fortune. Nine at the top means: One attains the way of heaven. Success. One attains the WAY of HEAVEN. SUCCESS. The taming of the great reaches its culmination. One has aligned with the way of heaven and achieved success. The great creative force has been harmonized and directed toward its proper purpose. 162. The way of heaven. The wise dragon advises you that the highest form of taming great power is alignment with the way of heaven. When power serves the cosmic order, success is assured."],
  [27,"Corners of the Mouth",["nourishment", "discernment", "sustenance", "mouth", "care"],"The corners of the mouth. Perseverance brings good fortune. Pay attention to the provision of nourishment, as well as to that with which a person seeks to fill their own mouth. THE CORNERS OF THE MOUTH. PERSEVERANCE brings GOOD FORTUNE. Pay attention to PROVIDING NOURISHMENT and to what one SEEKS to FILL one's own MOUTH with. This hexagram speaks of nourishment in the broadest sense — the nourishment of the body, of the mind, and of the spirit. What we take in through our mouths — food, words, impressions — shapes who we are. The superior person is careful about what they consume and what they express. They nourish themselves with what is wholesome and speak only what is true and beneficial. The hexagram also speaks of nourishing others — the duty of those in positions of authority to provide for those who depend on them. The one who nourishes others with what is wholesome fulfills their duty and brings good fortune.","At the foot of the mountain, thunder: The image of Nourishment. Thus the superior person is careful with their words and is moderate in eating and drinking. 'God manifests through nourishment.' At the foot of the mountain, thunder represents the stirring of life from below. The mountain provides stillness while the thunder provides movement. Together they represent the cycle of nourishment — the stillness of receiving and the movement of expressing. The superior person is careful with their words because words are a form of nourishment — they nourish or poison the minds of those who hear them. And they are moderate in eating and drinking because the body is the temple of the spirit and must be nourished with care. 163. Nourishing words. The wise dragon advises you to be careful with your words. Words nourish or poison. Choose to nourish. ○ Initial nine: You let your magical tortoise go and look at me with the corners of your mouth. Misfortune. You let your MAGICAL TORTOISE go and look at me with the CORNERS of your MOUTH. MISFORTUNE. One abandons one's own spiritual resources — the magical tortoise that could provide divine guidance — and instead looks enviously at what others have. This is a fundamental error: abandoning one's own inner resources to chase after external appearances. 164. Abandoning inner resources. The wise dragon advises you not to abandon your inner resources. Do not look enviously at others. Your own spiritual resources are sufficient. Six in the second place means: Turning to the summit for nourishment. Deviating from the path. Continuing brings misfortune. Turning to the SUMMIT for NOURISHMENT. DEVIATING from the PATH. CONTINUING brings MISFORTUNE. One seeks nourishment from those above but deviates from the right path in doing so. Seeking help is not wrong, but seeking it through improper means brings misfortune. 165. Proper seeking. The wise dragon advises you to seek nourishment through proper means. Deviating from the right path to get what you need brings misfortune. Six in the third place means: Turning away from nourishment. Perseverance brings misfortune. Do not act thus for ten years. Nothing that would further. Turning AWAY from NOURISHMENT. PERSEVERANCE brings MISFORTUNE. Do NOT act thus for TEN YEARS. Nothing FAVORABLE. One turns away from proper nourishment and pursues what is harmful. This is a fundamental deviation from the way. One must not continue on this path for a long time. 166. Turning from nourishment. The wise dragon advises you not to turn away from proper nourishment. What is harmful must be avoided, not pursued. Six in the fourth place means: Turning to the summit for nourishment brings good fortune. Turning to the SUMMIT for NOURISHMENT brings GOOD FORTUNE. One turns to the summit — to those above — for nourishment, and this time does so correctly. The seeking is humble and appropriate. The nourishment received is wholesome and brings good fortune. 167. Wholesome seeking. The wise dragon advises you to seek nourishment humbly from appropriate sources. Wholesome nourishment brings good fortune. Six in the fifth place means: Deviating from the path. To remain persevering brings good fortune. One should not cross the great waters. DEVIATING from the PATH. To REMAIN PERSEVERING brings GOOD FORTUNE. One should NOT CROSS the GREAT WATERS. One is in a position of authority but has deviated from the right path. By remaining persevering and not undertaking great enterprises, one can still achieve good fortune. 168. Correcting deviation. The wise dragon advises you to correct your deviation from the right path. Perseverance in correction brings good fortune. Nine at the top means: The source of nourishment. Awareness of danger brings good fortune. It is favorable to cross the great waters. The SOURCE of NOURISHMENT. Awareness of DANGER brings GOOD FORTUNE. It is FAVORABLE to CROSS the GREAT WATERS. One has become the source of nourishment for others. This is the highest form of nourishment — providing for the sustenance of others. But one must remain aware of the danger that comes with this responsibility. 169. The source of nourishment. The wise dragon advises you to become a source of nourishment for others. This highest calling requires awareness of its responsibilities."],
  [28,"Preponderance of the Great",["excess", "crisis", "burden", "decisive step", "originality"],"Preponderance of the great. The ridgepole sags to the breaking point. It is favorable to go somewhere. Success. Excess. The ridgepole yields. It is FAVORABLE to HAVE somewhere to GO. SUCCESS. This hexagram represents a time of extraordinary tension. The great powers are accumulated to such a degree that the structure threatens to collapse — like a beam that sags under excessive weight. This is a critical moment that requires decisive action. One cannot remain in the current situation; one must go somewhere, do something. The preponderance of the great is not inherently bad — it represents an abundance of power and possibility. But this abundance must be directed or it will collapse under its own weight. The exceptional person who can handle this situation must be extraordinary — someone who stands alone without fear and renounces the world without sorrow.","The lake rises above the trees: The image of the preponderance of the great. Thus the superior person, when alone, is not concerned, and when renouncing the world, is without sorrow. The lake has risen above the trees — an extraordinary situation in which the normal order is inverted. The great is preponderant; the structure is under extreme pressure. The superior person responds to this extraordinary situation with extraordinary equanimity. When alone, they are not concerned — they face the pressure with inner calm. When renouncing the world, they are without sorrow — they accept the transitory nature of all things. This is the attitude of the exceptional person who can navigate times of great tension. 170. Extraordinary equanimity. The wise dragon advises you to face extraordinary pressure with extraordinary calm. Inner equanimity is the key to navigating crisis. ○ Initial six: To spread white reed grass on the ground. Without blame. To SPREAD WHITE REED GRASS on the GROUND. WITHOUT BLAME. At the beginning of the time of preponderance, one takes extraordinary precautions. Like spreading white reed grass on the ground before placing offerings, one prepares with extreme care. This careful preparation is without blame. 171. Extraordinary care. The wise dragon advises you to take extraordinary precautions in times of crisis. Careful preparation prevents disaster. Nine in the second place means: A dry poplar sprouts at the root. An older man takes a young wife. Everything is favorable. A DRY POPLAR SPROUTS at the ROOT. An OLDER MAN takes a YOUNG WIFE. Everything FAVORABLE. New life emerges from what seemed dead. Like a dry poplar that sprouts from its root, or an older man who takes a young wife, the impossible becomes possible. This is the creative response to the preponderance of the great — finding new life in unexpected places. 172. New life from the old. The wise dragon advises you that even in times of crisis, new life can emerge from unexpected sources. Remain open to the impossible. Nine in the third place means: The ridgepole sags. Misfortune. The RIDGEPOAL SAGS. MISFORTUNE. The structure is failing. The ridgepole — the central support of the building — sags under the weight. This is misfortune. The preponderance of the great has overwhelmed the capacity of the structure to contain it. 173. Structural failure. The wise dragon advises you to recognize when a structure can no longer contain the forces acting upon it. Acknowledge the limits. Nine in the fourth place means: The ridgepole braces. Good fortune. If there are ulterior motives, humiliation. The RIDGEPOLE BRACES. GOOD FORTUNE. If there are ULTERIOR MOTIVES, HUMILIATION. The ridgepole is braced — the structure is reinforced. This brings good fortune. But if one has ulterior motives — if one uses the crisis for personal gain — the result is humiliation. 174. Bracing the structure. The wise dragon advises you to reinforce what is essential in times of crisis. Act with pure motives. Nine in the fifth place means: A withered poplar puts forth flower. An older woman takes a husband. No blame. No praise. A WITHERED POPLAR puts forth FLOWER. An OLDER WOMAN takes a HUSBAND. NO BLAME. NO PRAISE. Something extraordinary occurs — a withered tree flowers, an older woman finds a husband. These are unusual events that are neither blameworthy nor praiseworthy. They simply are. In times of preponderance, the extraordinary becomes normal. 175. The extraordinary normal. The wise dragon advises you to accept the extraordinary events of crisis without judgment. Neither blame nor praise is appropriate. At the top a six means: One must go through the water. It goes over one's head. Misfortune. No blame. One must go through the WATER. It goes OVER one's HEAD. MISFORTUNE. NO BLAME. The crisis reaches its peak. The water rises over one's head — the situation is overwhelming. One must go through it, even though it means going under. This is misfortune, but it is without blame — one did what one could in an impossible situation. 176. The overwhelming. The wise dragon advises you that sometimes the crisis is overwhelming. Going through it with dignity, even in failure, is without blame."],
  [29,"The Abysmal",["danger", "trust", "flow", "water", "sincerity"],"The abysmal repeated. If you are sincere, you have success in your heart. And whatever you undertake, you will succeed. The abyss followed by the abyss. Maintain sincerity. Success in the heart. THE ABYSS repeated. If you are SINCERE, you have SUCCESS in your HEART. And whatever you UNDERTAKE, you will SUCCEED. This hexagram is a doubling of the trigram Kan, the Abysmal, Water. It represents danger upon danger — the repetition of the abyss. The way through this double danger is sincerity. When one is truly sincere, one passes through danger as water passes through the deepest ravines — it fills them and flows onward. Water is the image of danger but also of the way through danger. It does not shrink from any depth but fills every hollow and continues on its way to the sea. The person who is sincere in the midst of danger finds success in their heart and accomplishes what they undertake.","Water flows without stopping and reaches its goal: The image of the Abysmal repeated. Thus the superior person walks always in virtue and practices teaching. Water flows without stopping — it never ceases to move. It fills every hollow, overcomes every obstacle, and reaches its goal: the sea. This is the image of how one should navigate repeated danger. The superior person walks always in virtue — like water that never stops flowing, one never stops practicing virtue. And one practices teaching — like water that fills every hollow, one addresses every challenge with knowledge and skill. 177. Flowing through danger. The wise dragon advises you to flow through danger like water. Never stop moving, never stop practicing virtue. ○ Initial six: Repetition of the abysmal. In the abyss one falls into a pit. Misfortune. REPETITION of the ABYSMAL. In the ABYSS one falls into a PIT. MISFORTUNE. At the beginning of the time of repeated danger, one falls deeper into the abyss. This is the worst form of danger — danger within danger. One must not try to escape through force but must accept the situation and find the way through sincerity. 178. Danger within danger. The wise dragon advises you that in the deepest danger, force will not help. Only sincerity can find the way through. Nine in the second place means: The abyss is dangerous. One should strive to attain small things only. The ABYSS is DANGEROUS. One should strive to attain SMALL things only. In the midst of danger, one should not aim for great achievements but should focus on small, attainable goals. Like water that fills a small hollow before flowing onward, one should address what is immediately at hand. 179. Small attainments. The wise dragon advises you to focus on small, attainable goals in times of danger. Great achievements must wait. Six in the third place means: Forward and backward, abyss on abyss. In danger like this, do not act first of all. Wait and contain yourself. Forward and BACKWARD, ABYSS on ABYSS. In DANGER like this, do NOT ACT first of all. WAIT and CONTAIN yourself. Danger surrounds on all sides — forward and backward, abyss on abyss. In this situation, one must not act but must wait and contain oneself. Action would only deepen the danger. 180. The wisdom of waiting. The wise dragon advises you to wait when surrounded by danger on all sides. Containment is wiser than action. Six in the fourth place means: A jug of wine, a bowl of rice therewith. Truly receive in this way through the window. A JUG of WINE, a BOWL of RICE therewith. Truly RECEIVE in this way through the WINDOW. In the midst of danger, one receives sustenance in the simplest way — a jug of wine, a bowl of rice, received through the window. This represents the minimal sustenance needed to survive. In times of danger, one must be content with what is essential. 181. Essential sustenance. The wise dragon advises you to be content with essentials in times of danger. Simplicity is the key to survival. Nine in the fifth place means: The abyss is not filled to overflowing. It is filled only to the rim. Without blame. The ABYSS is not filled to OVERFLOWING. It is filled only to the RIM. WITHOUT BLAME. The danger has reached its limit but has not overflowed. Like a hollow that is filled to the brim but not beyond, the danger has reached its maximum. By maintaining this balance, one avoids blame. 182. The limit of danger. The wise dragon advises you that danger has its limits. When the hollow is filled to the brim, the water begins to flow onward. At the top a six means: Bound with cords and thorns. In the thorn bush, for three years one does not find anything. Misfortune. BOUND with CORDS and THORNS. In the THORN BUSH, for THREE YEARS one does NOT find anything. MISFORTUNE. One is trapped in danger — bound with cords and thorns, lost in a thorn bush. For three years — a long time — one finds no way out. This is the consequence of having rejected the way of sincerity and fallen into the trap of one's own making. 183. The trap of insincerity. The wise dragon advises you that rejecting sincerity leads to entrapment. The way through danger is always sincerity."],
  [30,"The Clinging Fire",["clarity", "light", "consciousness", "fire", "dependence"],"The clinging. Perseverance brings success. Tending the cow brings good fortune. Radiance. Beauty. Continuing on the path brings success. The CARE of the COW brings GOOD FORTUNE. This hexagram is a doubling of the trigram Li, the Clinging, Fire. Fire clings to what it burns — it has no independent existence but depends on its fuel. Likewise, consciousness clings to its object — it has no independent existence but depends on what it illuminates. The clinging represents the nature of consciousness and light. Fire illuminates everything it touches but depends on what it consumes. The perseverance that brings success is the perseverance of the flame that continues to burn by constantly renewing its fuel. Tending the cow — the symbol of gentle devotion — brings good fortune because fire must be tended with care and gentleness.","The luminous rises twice: The image of Fire. Thus the great person, by perpetuating their brightness, illuminates the four quarters of the world. Each of the two trigrams represents the sun. The doubling represents the continuity of light — the sun that rises today and will rise again tomorrow. The great person, observing this perpetual renewal of light, perpetuates their own brightness through constant self-renewal. By perpetuating their inner light, they illuminate the four quarters of the world — their influence extends in all directions. This is the power of consciousness — like fire that illuminates everything around it, the illuminated person brings clarity to all they encounter. 184. Perpetual light. The wise dragon advises you to perpetuate your inner light through constant self-renewal. Your illumination extends to all you encounter. ○ Initial nine: The footprints run crisscross. If one is serious, no blame. The FOOTPRINTS run CRISSCROSS. If one is SERIOUS, NO BLAME. At the beginning of the time of the clinging, there is confusion — footprints running crisscross. But if one approaches the situation with seriousness and respect, there is no blame. 185. Serious approach. The wise dragon advises you to approach confusion with seriousness. Respect for the situation prevents error. Six in the second place means: Yellow light. Supreme good fortune. YELLOW LIGHT. Supreme GOOD FORTUNE. The yellow light is the light of the middle way — balanced, warm, and nourishing. This is the highest form of illumination — the light that is neither too intense nor too dim but perfectly balanced. It brings supreme good fortune. 186. The middle light. The wise dragon advises you to cultivate the light of the middle way. Balanced illumination brings supreme good fortune. Nine in the third place means: In the light of the setting sun, one either beats a pot and sings or laments the approach of old age. Misfortune. In the light of the SETTING SUN, one either BEATS a POT and SINGS or LAMENTS the approach of OLD AGE. MISFORTUNE. The setting sun represents the decline of the light. One can either accept this with joy — beating a pot and singing — or lament it. But lamentation is misfortune. One must accept the natural cycle of light and darkness. 187. Accepting the cycle. The wise dragon advises you to accept the natural cycles of light and darkness. Lamentation brings misfortune; acceptance brings peace. Nine in the fourth place means: Its coming is sudden. It flames up, dies down, is thrown away. Its COMING is SUDDEN. It FLAMES UP, DIES DOWN, is THROWN AWAY. The light comes suddenly and intensely — like a flash that burns brightly and then dies. This is the light that is not sustained — the inspiration that is not followed by perseverance. It is thrown away because it cannot be maintained. 188. Unsustained light. The wise dragon advises you to sustain your light. Inspiration without perseverance is quickly extinguished. Six in the fifth place means: Tears in floods, sighing, lamenting. Good fortune. TEARS in FLOODS, SIGHING, LAMENTING. GOOD FORTUNE. One weeps and laments — but this is not the lamentation of the third line. This is the lamentation of one who recognizes their error and grieves for it. This sincere grief brings good fortune because it leads to transformation. 189. Transformative grief. The wise dragon advises you that sincere grief for one's errors leads to transformation. Weeping with authenticity brings good fortune. At the top a nine means: The king uses them to march forth and punish. Then it is best to kill the leaders and capture the followers. No blame. The KING uses them to MARCH FORTH and PUNISH. Then it is best to KILL the LEADERS and CAPTURE the FOLLOWERS. NO BLAME. The king uses the light of consciousness to distinguish right from wrong and to punish the guilty. But the punishment is measured — the leaders are punished while the followers are captured and reformed. This is the just use of illuminating power. 190. Just illumination. The wise dragon advises you to use your illuminating power justly. Distinguish right from wrong with clarity, and punish with measure."],
  [31,"Influence",["influence", "attraction", "sensitivity", "heart", "openness"],"Influence. Success. Perseverance is favorable. Taking a maiden brings good fortune. Influence. Attraction. Continuing brings success. Taking a MAIDEN brings GOOD FORTUNE. This hexagram represents the mutual attraction between the masculine and feminine principles. The trigram Tui, the Joyous, the youngest daughter, is above; the trigram Kên, Keeping Still, the youngest son, is below. The son places himself below the daughter, and she is attracted to him. This is the way of courtship — the one who desires must humble themselves before the one they desire. Influence operates through receptivity and attraction, not through force. When the superior person is receptive to those below, they are influenced and attracted naturally. This is the principle that governs all human relationships and, indeed, all of nature.","A lake on the mountain: The image of Influence. Thus the superior person encourages others to approach through their readiness to receive them. A lake on the mountain — the mountain is below and the lake is above. The moisture of the lake penetrates the mountain, and the mountain supports the lake. This mutual penetration represents the way of influence. The superior person, like the mountain that receives the moisture of the lake, encourages others to approach by being open and receptive. When one is genuinely open to others, they are naturally attracted and influenced. This is the principle of all true teaching and leadership. 191. Receptive influence. The wise dragon advises you to influence others through receptivity and openness. Being genuinely open attracts others naturally. ○ Initial six: The influence shows itself in the toes. The influence shows itself in the TOES. At the beginning of the time of influence, the attraction is felt at the lowest level — in the toes. One feels the impulse to move toward the object of attraction but has not yet committed to action. This is the first stirring of influence. 192. First stirring. The wise dragon advises you to recognize the first stirrings of attraction. The impulse to move toward another is the beginning of influence. Six in the second place means: The influence shows itself in the calves of the legs. Misfortune. Tarrying brings good fortune. The influence shows itself in the CALVES of the LEGS. MISFORTUNE. Tarrying brings GOOD FORTUNE. The attraction moves upward to the calves — the impulse to move is stronger. But moving now would be premature. One must tarry — wait — and the result will be good fortune. 193. Patient attraction. The wise dragon advises you to be patient with attraction. Moving too soon brings misfortune; waiting brings good fortune. Nine in the third place means: The influence shows itself in the thighs. Holds to that which follows it. To continue brings humiliation. The influence shows itself in the THIGHS. Holds to that which FOLLOWS it. To CONTINUE brings HUMILIATION. The attraction moves to the thighs — the impulse to follow is strong. But if one follows blindly, without discernment, the result is humiliation. One must maintain one's own direction even while being attracted. 194. Discerning attraction. The wise dragon advises you to maintain discernment even when strongly attracted. Blind following leads to humiliation. Nine in the fourth place means: Perseverance brings good fortune. Remorse disappears. If one is agitated and one's thoughts go back and forth, only friends will follow. PERSEVERANCE brings GOOD FORTUNE. REMORSE disappears. If one is AGITATED and one's THOUGHTS go BACK and FORTH, only FRIENDS will follow. One must persevere in the influence to achieve good fortune. If one is agitated and indecisive, only close friends will follow — the broader influence will be lost. 195. Steadfast influence. The wise dragon advises you to be steadfast in your influence. Indecision limits your reach to only the closest companions. Nine in the fifth place means: The influence shows itself in the back of the neck. No remorse. The influence shows itself in the BACK of the NECK. NO REMORSE. The attraction has reached the back of the neck — the most sensitive point. One is deeply affected by the influence but maintains one's composure. There is no remorse because the influence is genuine and the response is appropriate. 196. Deep influence. The wise dragon advises you that genuine influence reaches the deepest levels. When the response is appropriate, there is no remorse. At the top a six means: The influence shows itself in the jaws, cheeks, and tongue. The influence shows itself in the JAWS, CHEEKS, and TONGUE. The influence has reached the speech center — the jaws, cheeks, and tongue. The attraction expresses itself in words. But influence that is merely verbal — that exists only in speech — is the weakest form. True influence must be embodied, not just spoken. 197. The limits of words. The wise dragon advises you that influence expressed only in words is the weakest form. True influence must be embodied in action."],
  [32,"Duration",["perseverance", "constancy", "firmness", "renewal", "direction"],"Duration. Success. Without blame. Perseverance is favorable. It is favorable to have goals. Long duration. Success. Without error. Continuing brings good fortune. It is FAVORABLE to HAVE a PLACE to GO. LONG DURATION. SUCCESS. WITHOUT ERROR. Continuing brings GOOD FORTUNE. It is FAVORABLE to HAVE somewhere to GO. This hexagram represents the principle of duration — the capacity to endure over time. The trigram Chên, the Arousing, Thunder, is above; the trigram Sun, the Gentle, Wind, is below. Thunder and wind — these are the most enduring phenomena of nature. Thunder has rolled and wind has blown since the beginning of time, and they will continue to the end. Their duration comes from their constant movement and renewal. The principle of duration is not rigidity but constant renewal — like the thunder that renews itself with every storm and the wind that renews itself with every breath.","Thunder and wind: The image of Duration. Thus the superior person stands firm and does not change direction. Thunder rolls and wind blows; both are phenomena of constant movement and renewal. But they also represent constancy — they have been present since the beginning and will continue to the end. The superior person, observing this principle, stands firm in their direction and does not change. This is not stubbornness but the constancy of one who has found their true path and remains on it through all changes. Duration is not about remaining the same but about remaining true to one's essential direction through all the mutations of time. 198. True constancy. The wise dragon advises you to stand firm in your true direction. Constancy through change is the essence of duration. ○ Initial six: Seeking duration too quickly. Misfortune. Nothing that would further. Seeking DURATION too QUICKLY. MISFORTUNE. Nothing that would FURTHER. At the beginning of the time of duration, one tries to achieve lasting results too quickly. Duration cannot be rushed. Trying to force permanence only leads to misfortune. 199. The patience of duration. The wise dragon advises you that duration cannot be rushed. Lasting results come from patient cultivation, not from haste. Nine in the second place means: Remorse disappears. Remorse DISAPPEARS. One has found the right path and remains on it. The remorse that came from wavering disappears when one commits to the path of duration. 200. Commitment to duration. The wise dragon advises you to commit to your path. When wavering ceases, remorse disappears. Nine in the third place means: One does not give duration to one's character. One meets with disgrace. Persistent humiliation. One does NOT give DURATION to one's CHARACTER. One meets with DISGRACE. Persistent HUMILIATION. One fails to maintain consistency of character. This inconsistency leads to disgrace and persistent humiliation. Without duration, one cannot maintain the respect of others or the integrity of one's own being. 201. The cost of inconsistency. The wise dragon advises you that inconsistency of character leads to disgrace. Duration requires maintaining your essential nature. Six in the fourth place means: No game in the field. No GAME in the FIELD. One hunts but finds nothing. The field is empty. This represents the frustration of one who has not maintained duration — they have not cultivated their field long enough for it to bear fruit. 202. The empty field. The wise dragon advises you to cultivate your field with patience. Duration is required for the harvest. Nine in the fifth place means: Giving duration to one's character through perseverance. This brings good fortune for a woman, misfortune for a man. Giving DURATION to one's CHARACTER through PERSEVERANCE. This brings GOOD FORTUNE for a WOMAN, MISFORTUNE for a MAN. One maintains consistency of character through perseverance. For a woman — representing the receptive principle — this constancy brings good fortune. For a man — representing the creative principle — rigid constancy without adaptation brings misfortune. 203. Adaptive constancy. The wise dragon advises you that constancy must be adapted to one's nature. Receptive constancy differs from creative constancy. At the top a six means: Restlessness as an enduring condition. Misfortune. RESTLESSNESS as an ENDURING CONDITION. MISFORTUNE. One makes restlessness into a permanent condition. This is the opposite of true duration — it is the persistence of instability. Constant change without a guiding principle leads to misfortune. 204. The error of restlessness. The wise dragon advises you that restlessness is the enemy of duration. True constancy requires a steady guiding principle, not constant change."],
  [33,"Retreat",["retreat", "distance", "freedom", "discretion", "strategy"],"Retreat brings success. In small things, perseverance is favorable. Retreat. The small and weak withdraws before the great and strong. RETREAT. In SMALL THINGS, PERSEVERANCE is FAVORABLE. This is not a retreat of cowardice but of strategy. The small recognizes the power of the great and withdraws at the right time. This is the way of the sage who knows that not every battle can be won and that sometimes the wisest action is to withdraw. Retreat brings success because it preserves one's strength for a more favorable time. It is not a defeat but a strategic repositioning. The superior person retreats not out of fear but out of wisdom, knowing when to advance and when to withdraw.","Under heaven there is a mountain: The image of Retreat. Thus the superior person keeps the inferior person at a distance, not with anger but with dignity. Under heaven there is a mountain — the mountain rises toward heaven but heaven towers above it. The mountain does not try to reach heaven but remains content in its own nature. This is the image of retreat — knowing one's place and maintaining it with dignity. The superior person keeps the inferior at a distance not through anger or hostility but through quiet dignity. By maintaining a respectful distance, the superior person avoids conflict while preserving their integrity. 205. Dignified retreat. The wise dragon advises you to retreat with dignity when the time demands it. Strategic withdrawal preserves strength. ○ Initial six: At the tail in retreat. Danger. One should not wish to undertake anything. At the TAIL in RETREAT. DANGER. One should NOT wish to undertake anything. One is at the very end — the tail — of the situation. Retreat is already difficult because one is the last to leave. Danger threatens. One should not undertake anything but should focus entirely on withdrawing. 206. The last to leave. The wise dragon advises you to withdraw promptly when you are the last to recognize the need. Delay brings danger. Six in the second place means: One holds them fast with yellow ox hide. No one can tear them loose. One holds them fast with YELLOW OX HIDE. No one can TEAR them LOOSE. One is held fast by something strong and enduring — like yellow ox hide, which is tough and difficult to tear. One's commitment to the right path is unshakeable. Even in retreat, one maintains one's principles. 207. Unshakeable principles. The wise dragon advises you to maintain your principles even in retreat. Commitment to the right path cannot be torn away. Nine in the third place means: A halted retreat is weary and dangerous. To keep servants and maids brings good fortune. A HALTED RETREAT is WEARY and DANGEROUS. To keep SERVANTS and MAIDS brings GOOD FORTUNE. One wants to retreat but is held back by obligations. This creates weariness and danger. One must attend to one's immediate responsibilities — the servants and maids — before completing the retreat. 208. Obligations in retreat. The wise dragon advises you to attend to your obligations even when you wish to withdraw. Responsibilities must be fulfilled. Nine in the fourth place means: Voluntary retreat. Good fortune for the superior person, misfortune for the small. VOLUNTARY RETREAT. GOOD FORTUNE for the SUPERIOR PERSON, MISFORTUNE for the SMALL. One retreats voluntarily, at the right time and for the right reasons. This brings good fortune for the superior person who understands the wisdom of retreat. But the small person, who cannot understand voluntary withdrawal, sees it as misfortune. 209. Understanding retreat. The wise dragon advises you that voluntary retreat is a sign of wisdom. Those who cannot understand retreat are the truly unfortunate. Nine in the fifth place means: Friendly retreat. Perseverance brings good fortune. FRIENDLY RETREAT. PERSEVERANCE brings GOOD FORTUNE. One retreats in a friendly manner, maintaining good relations with those one leaves behind. This is the ideal form of retreat — one that preserves relationships while ensuring one's own safety. 210. Friendly retreat. The wise dragon advises you to maintain good relations even when withdrawing. Friendly retreat preserves bonds for the future. At the top a nine means: Cheerful retreat. Everything acts to further. CHEERFUL RETREAT. Everything acts to FURTHER. The highest form of retreat is cheerful — one withdraws with joy and lightness, without regret or reluctance. This cheerful retreat is the mark of one who has fully understood the way of timing. Everything acts to further because the retreat is perfectly timed and perfectly executed. 211. The cheerful retreat. The wise dragon advises you to retreat with joy when the time demands it. Cheerful withdrawal is the highest form of strategic wisdom."],
  [34,"The Power of the Great",["power", "strength", "rectitude", "prudence", "containment"],"The power of the great. Perseverance is favorable. The power of the great. Continuing in the way of the Tao brings reward. GREAT FORTALEZA. A FAVORABLE ORACLE. This hexagram speaks of a time in which inner valor is combined with great force, and the result is power. However, this power has already passed beyond the middle line, hence the danger that one might rely entirely on one's own power and forget to consider what is right. There is also danger that, given the desire to move, one does not wait for the right moment. Hence the additional indication about what is favorable in persevering. For the power that is truly great does not degenerate into mere force; it remains inwardly united with the fundamental principles of correctness and justice. When we are able to understand this point — that greatness and justice go indissolubly together — we understand the true meaning of everything that happens in heaven and earth.","Thunder in the sky above: The image of the power of the great. Thus the superior person does not walk paths that do not correspond to the established order. Thunder — that is, electrical energy — rises high in the sky in spring. The direction of this movement is in harmony with the direction of the movement of heaven. It is, therefore, a movement according to heaven, which provokes great power. However, true greatness depends on being in harmony with what is right. Consequently, in times of great power, the superior person avoids anything that is not in tune with the established order. 212. Power in harmony. The wise dragon advises you that true power must be in harmony with what is right. Greatness without justice is mere force. ○ Initial nine: Power in the toes. Continuing brings misfortune. This is certainly true. POWER in the TOES. CONTINUING brings MISFORTUNE. This is certainly TRUE. At the beginning of the time of great power, the impulse to act is felt in the toes — the lowest level. If one acts on this impulse without reflection, misfortune follows. One must not let the impulse to power drive one's actions. 213. Restrained impulse. The wise dragon advises you not to act on the first impulse of power. Reflection must precede action. Nine in the second place means: Perseverance brings good fortune. PERSEVERANCE brings GOOD FORTUNE. One channels the great power through perseverance. Instead of acting impulsively, one remains steady and true. This perseverance brings good fortune because it keeps the power aligned with the right path. 214. Channeled power. The wise dragon advises you to channel power through perseverance. Steadiness keeps power on the right path. Nine in the third place means: The small person uses power. The superior person does not do so. To continue is like a ram butting against a hedge and getting its horns entangled. The SMALL PERSON uses POWER. The SUPERIOR PERSON does NOT do so. To CONTINUE is like a RAM butting against a HEDGE and getting its HORNS ENTANGLED. The small person uses power recklessly, like a ram that charges into a hedge and gets its horns stuck. The superior person understands that power must be used with wisdom, not brute force. 215. The ram's error. The wise dragon advises you not to use power recklessly. Brute force leads to entanglement. Nine in the fourth place means: Perseverance brings good fortune. Remorse disappears. The hedge opens, there is no entanglement. Power depends upon the axle of a big wagon. PERSEVERANCE brings GOOD FORTUNE. REMORSE disappears. The HEDGE OPENS, there is NO ENTANGLEMENT. POWER depends upon the AXLE of a BIG WAGON. Through perseverance, the hedge opens and the entanglement disappears. Power is like the axle of a great wagon — it must be strong and reliable to carry the load. When one perseveres in the right use of power, obstacles dissolve. 216. Dissolving obstacles. The wise dragon advises you that perseverance in the right use of power dissolves obstacles. Strength with integrity opens every hedge. Six in the fifth place means: One loses the goat with ease. Do not persevere. One LOSES the GOAT with EASE. Do NOT PERSEVERE. One loses something stubborn and willful — like a goat — with ease. The obstinate element is removed without difficulty. But one must not persevere in this removal — once the obstacle is gone, one must change approach. 217. Removing obstinacy. The wise dragon advises you to remove obstinacy with ease but not to persist in force once the obstacle is cleared. At the top a six means: A goat butts against a hedge. It cannot go backward, cannot go forward. Nothing acts to further. If one notes the difficulty, this brings good fortune. A GOAT butts against a HEDGE. It cannot go BACKWARD, cannot go FORWARD. Nothing acts to FURTHER. If one notes the DIFFICULTY, this brings GOOD FORTUNE. One is trapped — like a goat whose horns are caught in a hedge, unable to go forward or backward. This is the consequence of using power without wisdom. But if one recognizes the difficulty, one can find a way out. Awareness of the problem is the first step to resolution. 218. Awareness in entrapment. The wise dragon advises you that recognizing your entrapment is the first step to freedom. Awareness brings good fortune even in the most difficult situations."],
  [35,"Progress",["progress", "rising light", "clarity", "advance", "reward"],"Progress. The powerful prince is honored with horses in multitude. In one day he is received three times. PROGRESS. The POWERFUL PRINCE is HONORED with HORSES in MULTITUDE. In one DAY he is RECEIVED THREE TIMES. Progress is like the sun rising over the earth — it brings light to all things. The powerful prince who advances is honored by the sovereign with many horses and received in audience three times in a single day. This represents rapid advancement and recognition. The person who makes progress is seen and honored. Their talents are recognized and rewarded. But progress must be based on substance, not mere appearance. The sun that rises over the earth illuminates everything it touches, but its light comes from its own inner fire.","The sun rises over the earth: The image of Progress. Thus the sage shines with brilliant virtue. The sun rises over the earth — light spreads across the world, illuminating everything. The sage, observing this, shines with brilliant virtue. Like the sun that illuminates without effort, the sage's virtue radiates naturally to all who encounter it. This is the true nature of progress — not the accumulation of external honors but the radiation of inner light. 219. Radiant virtue. The wise dragon advises you to let your virtue shine like the sun. True progress comes from inner light, not external recognition. ○ Initial six: Progressing, turning back. Perseverance brings good fortune. If one lacks confidence, to remain composed is without blame. PROGRESSING, TURNING BACK. PERSEVERANCE brings GOOD FORTUNE. If one LACKS CONFIDENCE, to REMAIN COMPOSED is WITHOUT BLAME. At the beginning of progress, one advances but then turns back. This is not failure but caution. If one lacks confidence, remaining composed and not forcing the advance is without blame. 220. Cautious progress. The wise dragon advises you that turning back when one lacks confidence is wisdom, not failure. Composed patience is without blame. Six in the second place means: Progressing, in sorrow. Perseverance brings good fortune. Then one receives great happiness from one's ancestress. Progressing, in SORROW. PERSEVERANCE brings GOOD FORTUNE. Then one receives GREAT HAPPINESS from one's ANCESTRESS. One progresses through sorrow. The path is difficult and painful. But perseverance brings good fortune, and eventually great happiness arrives from an unexpected source — the ancestress, representing the support of the past. 221. Progress through sorrow. The wise dragon advises you that progress through sorrow, sustained by perseverance, eventually brings great happiness. Six in the third place means: All are in accord. Remorse disappears. ALL are in ACCORD. REMORSE disappears. One has found allies who share one's purpose. All are in accord, and remorse disappears. When one's advance is supported by others who share the same vision, progress flows naturally. 222. Accord in progress. The wise dragon advises you that shared purpose removes remorse. When allies agree, progress flows. Nine in the fourth place means: Progress like a hamster. Perseverance brings danger. Progress LIKE a HAMSTER. PERSEVERANCE brings DANGER. One progresses like a hamster — busy but going nowhere. This is progress that is all motion and no direction. If one perseveres in this aimless activity, danger follows. 223. Aimless motion. The wise dragon advises you to ensure your progress has direction. Busy motion without purpose leads to danger. Six in the fifth place means: Remorse disappears. Take not gain and loss to heart. Undertaking brings good fortune. Everything acts favorably. REMORSE disappears. Take NOT GAIN and LOSS to HEART. UNDERTAKING brings GOOD FORTUNE. Everything acts FAVORABLY. One has reached the position of honor. Remorse disappears. One does not take gain and loss to heart — one is above such concerns. Undertaking brings good fortune because one acts from a position of inner strength. 224. Above gain and loss. The wise dragon advises you to rise above concerns about gain and loss. Inner strength makes external outcomes irrelevant. At the top a nine means: Progressing in stature. One has not received commands. It is favorable to undertake the punishment of one's own city. Perseverance brings humiliation. PROGRESSING in STATURE. One has NOT RECEIVED COMMANDS. It is FAVORABLE to undertake the PUNISHMENT of one's OWN CITY. PERSEVERANCE brings HUMILIATION. One has advanced in stature but has not received proper authorization. One tries to impose order on one's own domain. But without proper authority, perseverance in this brings only humiliation. 225. The limit of self-authorization. The wise dragon advises you that progress without proper authority leads to humiliation. Seek legitimate authorization before acting."],
  [36,"Darkening of the Light",["adversity", "discretion", "perseverance", "resilience", "concealment"],"Darkening of the light. Perseverance in adversity is favorable. DARKENING of the LIGHT. PERSEVERANCE in ADVERSITY is FAVORABLE. The light has sunk into the earth. This represents a time when the forces of darkness are ascendant and the forces of light are in retreat. The superior person must hide their light and maintain their brightness in the midst of darkness. This is not a time for open action but for inner perseverance. The light is not extinguished — it is merely hidden, waiting for the time when it can shine again. The person who perseveres in adversity, maintaining their inner brilliance despite external darkness, will be ready when the time of light returns.","The light sinks into the earth: The image of Darkening of the Light. Thus the sage lives among the many: they dim their light yet remain brilliant. The light has sunk into the earth — it is hidden beneath the surface. The sage, living in a time of darkness, dims their light so as not to attract the attention of the powerful. But they remain brilliant within. This is the art of surviving adversity — appearing ordinary on the outside while maintaining inner brilliance. The sage does not extinguish their light but conceals it, waiting for the right moment to shine again. 226. Hidden brilliance. The wise dragon advises you to conceal your brilliance in times of adversity. Inner light preserved is light that will shine again. ○ Initial nine: Darkening of the light in flight. One folds one's wings. The superior person does not eat for three days. But wherever one goes, one has something to say. The truly superior person may be discarded. DARKENING of the LIGHT in FLIGHT. One FOLDS one's WINGS. The SUPERIOR PERSON does NOT EAT for THREE DAYS. But wherever one GOES, one has somethings to SAY. The truly SUPERIOR PERSON may be DISCARDED. One must flee and hide one's light. Like a bird that folds its wings in flight, one conceals one's brilliance. One may go hungry, but one's words carry truth. Even when discarded by the world, the superior person maintains their integrity. 227. Flight with integrity. The wise dragon advises you to flee when necessary but never abandon your integrity. Even in hiding, your truth endures. Six in the second place means: Darkening of the light. One hurts one's left thigh. One rescues oneself with the strength of a horse. Good fortune. DARKENING of the LIGHT. One HURTS one's LEFT THIGH. One RESCUES oneself with the STRENGTH of a HORSE. GOOD FORTUNE. One is wounded but not defeated. Like a rider on a strong horse, one rescues oneself through swift action. The wound is painful but not fatal. Good fortune follows because one acted decisively. 228. Swift rescue. The wise dragon advises you to act decisively when wounded. Swift action brings rescue and good fortune. Nine in the third place means: Darkening of the light in the south. One captures the leader of the darkness. One must not expect perseverance too soon. DARKENING of the LIGHT in the SOUTH. One CAPTURES the LEADER of the DARKNESS. One must NOT expect PERSEVERANCE too SOON. One is in the south — the place of light — and captures the leader of darkness. This is a great victory. But one must not expect the full restoration of light too soon. The process takes time. 229. Capturing darkness. The wise dragon advises you that even in darkness, you can capture its leader. But patience is needed for full restoration. Six in the fourth place means: One penetrates the left side of the belly. One discovers the gate of the courtyard. One PENETRATES the LEFT SIDE of the BELLY. One DISCOVERS the GATE of the COURTYARD. One penetrates to the heart of the darkness — the left side of the belly. There one discovers the gate — the way out. Even in the deepest darkness, there is a way to the light. 230. The gate in darkness. The wise dragon advises you that even in the deepest darkness, there is a gate to the light. Seek it patiently. Six in the fifth place means: Darkening of the light as with Prince Ji. Perseverance is favorable. DARKENING of the LIGHT as with PRINCE JI. PERSEVERANCE is FAVORABLE. One is like Prince Ji, who hid his brilliance and endured slavery rather than abandon his principles. His perseverance in adversity was favorable because it preserved the light for the future. 231. The perseverance of Prince Ji. The wise dragon advises you to persevere in adversity like Prince Ji. Endurance preserves the light for the future. At the top a six means: Not light but darkness. First one climbs to heaven, then one plunges into the depths of the earth. NOT LIGHT but DARKNESS. First one CLIMBS to HEAVEN, then one PLUNGES into the DEPTHS of the EARTH. The darkness is complete. One who was in a high place — who climbed to heaven — now plunges into the depths. This is the fate of the tyrant who rose too high and fell too far. 232. The fall of the tyrant. The wise dragon advises you that those who rise through darkness will eventually fall into the deepest depths. True light endures; false light collapses."],
  [37,"The Family",["family", "domestic order", "roles", "responsibility", "home"],"The family. The perseverance of the woman is favorable. THE FAMILY. The PERSEVERANCE of the WOMAN is FAVORABLE. This hexagram speaks of the internal order of the family — the relationships between its members and the roles each plays. The wind comes from fire — just as fire creates a draft that generates wind, so the inner warmth of the family generates the influence that extends outward. The family is the foundation of society. If the family is well ordered, society will be well ordered. The perseverance of the woman — her constancy in maintaining the inner life of the family — is the key to this order. The woman's role in the family is not secondary but essential. Without her perseverance, the family dissolves and society follows.","The wind that comes from fire: The image of the Family. Thus the superior person gives substance to their words and endurance to their conduct. The wind comes from fire — the inner warmth generates outward influence. The superior person, observing this, ensures that their words have substance and their conduct has endurance. Just as the family is ordered by the consistency of its members' words and actions, so the superior person orders their life through consistency between what they say and what they do. Words without substance are like fire without fuel — they cannot generate the wind of influence. 233. Consistent words and deeds. The wise dragon advises you to ensure consistency between your words and your actions. Substance in speech and endurance in conduct create lasting influence. ○ Initial nine: Establish rules for the family early. Good fortune. Establish RULES for the FAMILY EARLY. GOOD FORTUNE. At the beginning of the family's formation, rules must be established. Like setting the foundation of a house, early rules prevent later chaos. This brings good fortune because order is established from the start. 234. Early order. The wise dragon advises you to establish order early in any undertaking. Clear rules from the beginning prevent later confusion. Six in the second place means: One should not follow one's own whims. One should persevere in the family. Good fortune for the wife. One should NOT follow one's own WHIMS. One should PERSEVERE in the FAMILY. GOOD FORTUNE for the WIFE. One must not follow personal whims but should persevere in the duties of the family. For the wife — the one who maintains the inner order — this devotion brings good fortune. 235. Devotion to duty. The wise dragon advises you to devote yourself to your duties rather than following personal whims. Devotion brings order and good fortune. Nine in the third place means: When there is tension in the family, reproach brings danger. Children and servants, the wife and the concubine — when there is tension, even reproach is dangerous. When there is TENSION in the FAMILY, REPROACH brings DANGER. Even children and servants — when there is tension, reproach only makes things worse. One must address tension with care, not with harsh words. 236. Careful correction. The wise dragon advises you to address family tension with care. Harsh words in times of tension only deepen the wound. Six in the fourth place means: She is the treasure of the house. Great good fortune. She is the TREASURE of the HOUSE. Great GOOD FORTUNE. The woman who maintains the inner order of the family is its treasure. Her devotion and constancy are the foundation of the family's well-being. This brings great good fortune. 237. The family treasure. The wise dragon advises you to recognize and honor those who maintain the inner order. Their devotion is the foundation of all well-being. Nine in the fifth place means: As a king approaches his family, there is no need for worry. Good fortune. As a KING approaches his FAMILY, there is NO NEED for WORRY. GOOD FORTUNE. The king approaches his family with the same care and order that he brings to his kingdom. When the family is well ordered, there is no need for worry. The king's example extends to all. 238. The ordered kingdom. The wise dragon advises you that a well-ordered family is the foundation of a well-ordered life. When the inner world is in order, there is no need for worry. At the top a nine means: The ruler's presence inspires awe. In the end, good fortune. The RULER's PRESENCE inspires AWE. In the END, GOOD FORTUNE. The ruler's presence inspires awe — not through fear but through the dignity of their character. This awe, based on genuine respect, brings good fortune in the end. 239. Awe through dignity. The wise dragon advises you that true authority comes from the dignity of character, not from fear. Dignity inspires lasting respect."],
  [38,"Opposition",["polarity", "contraries", "misunderstanding", "reconciliation", "duality"],"Opposition. In small things there is good fortune. OPPOSITION. In SMALL THINGS there is GOOD FORTUNE. This hexagram represents a time of opposition and misunderstanding. People are divided; their views are opposed. In such times, great achievements are not possible because unity is lacking. But in small things, good fortune can still be found. The fire burns upward, the lake flows downward — they move in opposite directions despite being together. Similarly, people can be in the same situation but see it from completely different perspectives. The sage understands this and does not try to force unity but finds what is common despite the opposition.","Fire above, the lake below: The image of Opposition. The sage is in agreement about what is common and differs about what is particular. Fire above, the lake below — they move in opposite directions. The sage, observing this, recognizes that opposition is a natural part of life. Rather than trying to eliminate all difference, the sage finds agreement in what is common and accepts difference in what is particular. This is the art of living with opposition — not forcing unity but finding the common ground while respecting individual differences. 240. Unity in diversity. The wise dragon advises you to find common ground despite opposition. Respect differences while building on what you share. ○ Initial nine: Remorse disappears. If you lose your horse, do not run after it; it will return on its own. You see evil people. Guard yourself against error. REMORSE disappears. If you LOSE your HORSE, do NOT RUN after it; it will RETURN on its own. You see EVIL PEOPLE. Guard yourself against ERROR. At the beginning of opposition, one loses something — the horse. But one should not chase after it; it will return on its own. When encountering evil people, one must guard against being drawn into their errors. 241. Letting go. The wise dragon advises you not to chase after what is lost in times of opposition. What belongs to you will return. Guard against the errors of others. Nine in the second place means: One meets the ruler in a narrow street. No blame. One meets the RULER in a NARROW STREET. NO BLAME. One encounters authority in an unexpected place — a narrow street. This is not the formal meeting one might expect, but it is genuine and without blame. In times of opposition, meetings happen in unlikely places. 242. Unexpected meetings. The wise dragon advises you that in times of opposition, genuine encounters happen in unexpected places. Be open. Six in the third place means: One sees the wagon dragged back, the oxen halted, one's hair and nose cut off. Not a good beginning, but a good end. One sees the WAGON DRAGGED back, the OXEN HALTED, one's HAIR and NOSE CUT off. Not a good BEGINNING, but a good END. One faces violent opposition — one's progress is halted, one is humiliated. But this is only the beginning. In the end, the situation resolves favorably. 243. From bad beginning to good end. The wise dragon advises you that opposition at the beginning does not determine the end. Persevere through difficulty. Nine in the fourth place means: Isolated through opposition, one meets a like-minded person. One unites with them in spirit. Isolated through OPPOSITION, one meets a LIKE-MINDED person. One UNITES with them in SPIRIT. One is isolated by the opposition — surrounded by those who disagree. But one meets a kindred spirit — someone who shares one's view. This meeting of minds across the opposition is a source of strength. 244. Kindred spirits. The wise dragon advises you that even in isolation, kindred spirits can be found. Their union in spirit provides strength against opposition. Six in the fifth place means: Remorse disappears. Does one's companion bite through the wrappings? If one goes, what blame? REMORSE disappears. Does one's COMPANION BITE THROUGH the WRAPPINGS? If one GOES, what BLAME? Remorse disappears. One's companion bites through the obstacles that separate. If one goes to meet them, there is no blame. The barriers between opposing parties are overcome. 245. Overcoming barriers. The wise dragon advises you that barriers between opposing parties can be overcome. Go to meet the other with openness. At the top a nine means: Isolated one sees the pig covered with mud, the wagon full of demons. First one draws the bow, then one lays it aside. They are not robbers but relatives. Going brings rain, then good fortune comes. Isolated one sees the PIG covered with MUD, the WAGON full of DEMONS. First one DRAWS the BOW, then one LAYS it ASIDE. They are NOT ROBBERS but RELATIVES. Going brings RAIN, then GOOD FORTUNE comes. In isolation, one sees the other as monstrous — like a pig covered in mud, a wagon full of demons. One prepares to attack. But then one lays aside the bow, recognizing that they are not enemies but relatives. Going toward them brings rain — the tension dissolves like rain after drought — and good fortune arrives. 246. From enemy to relative. The wise dragon advises you that those you see as enemies may be relatives in disguise. Lay aside your bow and go to meet them. Understanding transforms enemies into allies."],
  [39,"Obstruction",["obstacle", "help", "reflection", "strategic withdrawal", "humility"],"Obstruction. The southwest is favorable; the northeast is not. It is favorable to see the great man. OBSTRUCTION. The SOUTHWEST is FAVORABLE; the NORTHEAST is NOT. It is FAVORABLE to SEE the GREAT MAN. Water on the mountain — this is the image of obstruction. The water cannot flow forward because the mountain blocks it. It can only flow back. This represents a situation in which advance is impossible and the only wise course is to retreat and reflect. The southwest — the place of the receptive — is favorable because it represents the gentle, yielding approach. The northeast — the place of the creative — is not favorable because force will not overcome the obstruction. It is favorable to see the great man because wise counsel is needed to navigate the obstacle.","There is water above the mountain: The image of Obstruction. Thus the superior person turns back to themselves and cultivates virtue. Water above the mountain — the water cannot flow forward and must accumulate. The superior person, facing obstruction, turns back to themselves. Instead of trying to overcome the obstacle through force, they cultivate their inner virtue. This self-cultivation is the preparation for the time when the obstacle can be overcome. By strengthening oneself internally, one becomes ready for the moment when advance becomes possible. 247. Inner cultivation. The wise dragon advises you to turn inward when facing obstruction. Self-cultivation prepares you for the moment when advance becomes possible. ○ Initial six: Going leads to obstructions, coming meets with recognition. GOING leads to OBSTRUCTIONS, COMING meets with RECOGNITION. At the beginning of obstruction, one discovers that going forward leads only to more obstacles. But coming back — retreating — meets with recognition. Others see the wisdom in one's retreat. 248. Recognized retreat. The wise dragon advises you that retreating from obstruction is recognized as wisdom, not cowardice. Six in the second place means: The ruler's servant is beset by obstruction upon obstruction. It is not their own fault. The RULER's SERVANT is beset by OBSTRUCTION upon OBSTRUCTION. It is NOT their OWN FAULT. One is sent on a mission by the ruler but encounters obstruction after obstruction. This is not one's own fault — the obstacles are inherent in the situation. One must persevere in the mission despite the difficulties. 249. Obstacles not of one's making. The wise dragon advises you that some obstacles are not of your making. Persevere in your mission despite them. Nine in the third place means: Going leads to obstructions. Therefore one comes back. GOING leads to OBSTRUCTIONS. Therefore one COMES BACK. One tries to advance but encounters obstacles at every turn. The wise response is to come back — to retreat and reassess. This is not defeat but strategy. 250. Strategic retreat. The wise dragon advises you to retreat when every path leads to obstruction. Strategic withdrawal allows reassessment. Nine in the fourth place means: Going leads to obstructions, coming leads to union. GOING leads to OBSTRUCTIONS, COMING leads to UNION. One discovers that going forward leads to obstacles, but coming back leads to union with others. The obstacle cannot be overcome alone; one must join forces with others. 251. Union against obstacles. The wise dragon advises you to seek union with others when facing obstacles. What cannot be overcome alone can be overcome together. Nine in the fifth place means: In great obstructions, friends arrive. In GREAT OBSTRUCTIONS, FRIENDS ARRIVE. The obstacles are great, but friends arrive to help. When the difficulty is severe, allies appear. This is the reward of having maintained good relationships. 252. Friends in difficulty. The wise dragon advises you that maintaining good relationships ensures help in times of great difficulty. At the top a six means: Going leads to obstructions, coming leads to great good fortune. It is favorable to see the great man. GOING leads to OBSTRUCTIONS, COMING leads to GREAT GOOD FORTUNE. It is FAVORABLE to SEE the GREAT MAN. The obstruction reaches its peak. Going forward is impossible. But coming back brings great good fortune. One seeks the counsel of the great man, whose wisdom reveals the way through the obstacle. 253. The counsel of wisdom. The wise dragon advises you to seek wise counsel when facing the greatest obstacles. The wisdom of others reveals the way forward."],
  [40,"Deliverance",["liberation", "relief", "forgiveness", "movement", "resolution"],"Deliverance. The southwest is favorable. If there is nowhere to go, return brings good fortune. If there is somewhere to go, hastening brings good fortune. DELIVERANCE. The SOUTHWEST is FAVORABLE. If there is NOWHERE to GO, RETURN brings GOOD FORTUNE. If there IS somewhere to GO, HASTENING brings GOOD FORTUNE. Thunder and rain come — the tension that built up during the time of obstruction is released. The storm breaks and the air is cleared. This is deliverance — the liberation from the pressure of obstacles. If there is nothing more to be done, returning to normal life brings good fortune. But if there is still something to do — if the deliverance is not yet complete — one must act quickly to finish the work before new obstacles can form.","Thunder and rain come: The image of Deliverance. Thus the sage forgave mistakes and pardoned crimes. Thunder and rain — the storm that breaks the tension. The air is washed clean. The sage, observing this, forgives mistakes and pardons crimes. Just as the rain washes the earth clean, the sage washes the social order clean through forgiveness and pardon. This is the way of deliverance — not punishment but release. By forgiving past errors, one frees the energy that was trapped in resentment and allows new life to begin. 254. The cleansing rain. The wise dragon advises you to forgive and pardon as the rain washes the earth clean. Forgiveness frees trapped energy and allows new life. ○ Initial six: Without blame. WITHOUT BLAME. At the beginning of deliverance, one simply accepts the liberation without adding anything. There is no blame in simply receiving the gift of freedom. 255. Receiving freedom. The wise dragon advises you to receive freedom graciously. Sometimes the best action is to simply accept the deliverance that has come. Nine in the second place means: One kills three foxes in the field and catches a yellow arrow. Perseverance brings good fortune. One KILLS THREE FOXES in the FIELD and catches a YELLOW ARROW. PERSEVERANCE brings GOOD FORTUNE. One removes the remaining obstacles — the foxes that lurk in the field. The yellow arrow represents the middle way — the straight and balanced approach that eliminates what is harmful. 256. Removing remaining obstacles. The wise dragon advises you to remove remaining obstacles with the straight arrow of the middle way. Six in the third place means: Carrying a burden on one's back while riding in a wagon encourages robbers to draw near. One should be resolved. Carrying a BURDEN on one's BACK while RIDING in a WAGON encourages ROBBERS to draw near. One should be RESOLVED. One carries a burden that is inappropriate to one's position — like carrying a load on one's back while riding in a wagon. This inconsistency attracts trouble. One must be resolved to act appropriately to one's position. 257. Appropriate conduct. The wise dragon advises you to act appropriately to your position. Inconsistency attracts trouble. Nine in the fourth place means: Free yourself from your great toe. Then the companion comes. Free yourself from your GREAT TOE. Then the COMPANION comes. One frees oneself from a petty attachment — the great toe, the lowest part. When one releases this small but persistent attachment, the true companion arrives. 258. Releasing petty attachments. The wise dragon advises you to release petty attachments. Letting go of what is small makes room for what is great. Six in the fifth place means: If only the superior person delivers themselves, good fortune comes. For the small person, it means captivity. If only the SUPERIOR PERSON DELIVERS themselves, GOOD FORTUNE comes. For the SMALL PERSON, it means CAPTIVITY. The superior person delivers themselves through their own effort and wisdom. This brings good fortune. But the small person, who cannot deliver themselves, remains captive to their own limitations. 259. Self-deliverance. The wise dragon advises you to deliver yourself through your own effort. Self-liberation brings good fortune; dependence on others leads to captivity. At the top a six means: The prince shoots at a hawk on a high wall. He kills it. Everything acts to further. The PRINCE shoots at a HAWK on a HIGH WALL. He KILLS it. Everything acts to FURTHER. The prince removes the last obstacle — a hawk perched on a high wall. The hawk represents a powerful enemy or obstacle that has been causing trouble from a position of advantage. The prince, with precision and authority, eliminates it. Everything acts to further because the deliverance is now complete. 260. The final obstacle. The wise dragon advises you to eliminate the final obstacle with precision and authority. When the deliverance is complete, everything acts to further."],
  [41,"Decrease",["moderation", "simplification", "sacrifice", "sincerity", "renunciation"],"Decrease. Being truthful, there will be good fortune. Without blame. One can be persevered. It is favorable to have somewhere to go. DECREASE. Being TRUTHFUL, there will be GOOD FORTUNE. WITHOUT BLAME. One can be PERSEVERED. It is FAVORABLE to HAVE somewhere to GO. Decrease combined with sincerity brings supreme good fortune. The lake at the base of the mountain — the mountain is diminished so that the lake may be deepened. This is the principle of decrease: what is above diminishes so that what is below may increase. But decrease is not loss when it is done with sincerity. A small offering given with genuine heart is worth more than a great offering given without feeling. The time of decrease requires simplification — stripping away the non-essential to reveal what is truly important.","The lake at the base of the mountain: The image of Decrease. Thus the superior person controls their anger and restrains their instincts. The lake at the base of the mountain — the mountain diminishes its height so that the lake may deepen. The superior person, observing this, diminishes what is excessive in themselves — controlling anger and restraining instincts. This is the inner work of decrease: reducing what is harmful so that what is beneficial may grow. Like the mountain that gives of its substance to deepen the lake, the superior person gives up lower impulses to strengthen higher qualities. 261. Inner decrease. The wise dragon advises you to diminish what is excessive within yourself. Controlling anger and restraining instincts strengthens higher qualities. ○ Initial nine: Going quickly when one's tasks are finished is without blame. But one must consider how much one may decrease others. GOING QUICKLY when one's TASKS are FINISHED is WITHOUT BLAME. But one must CONSIDER how much one may DECREASE others. One finishes one's tasks quickly and goes to help those above. This is without blame. But one must consider how much one can truly decrease oneself to benefit others. 262. Considerate decrease. The wise dragon advises you to consider how much you can genuinely give. Overextending yourself helps no one. Nine in the second place means: Perseverance brings good fortune. If one does not decrease oneself, one can bring increase to others. PERSEVERANCE brings GOOD FORTUNE. If one does NOT DECREASE oneself, one can bring INCREASE to others. One does not diminish oneself but instead increases others through perseverance. Sometimes the best way to decrease is not to give what you don't have but to strengthen what you do. 263. Increase through strength. The wise dragon advises you that strengthening yourself can be the best way to help others. Six in the third place means: When three people walk together, their number decreases by one. When one person walks alone, they find a companion. When THREE PEOPLE walk TOGETHER, their NUMBER DECREASES by ONE. When ONE PERSON walks ALONE, they find a COMPANION. The group is diminished by internal disagreement. But the solitary person, through sincerity, finds a true companion. Decrease can lead to genuine connection. 264. The power of one. The wise dragon advises you that sincerity in solitude can find truer connection than disharmony in a group. Six in the fourth place means: If one decreases one's faults, one makes the other hasten to come with joy. Without blame. If one DECREASES one's FAULTS, one makes the other HASTEN to come with JOY. WITHOUT BLAME. One works on decreasing one's own faults. This self-improvement attracts others with joy. When one improves oneself, others are drawn to the improvement. 265. Self-improvement attracts. The wise dragon advises you to decrease your own faults. Self-improvement is the most powerful way to attract others. Six in the fifth place means: Someone does indeed increase them. Ten pairs of tortoises cannot oppose it. Supreme good fortune. Someone does indeed INCREASE them. TEN PAIRS of TORTOISES cannot OPPOSE it. Supreme GOOD FORTUNE. One receives increase from a higher source. This increase is so powerful that no opposition can prevent it. The oracle of the tortoises confirms: supreme good fortune. 266. Unstoppable increase. The wise dragon advises you that increase from a higher source cannot be opposed. Accept it with gratitude. Nine at the top means: If one is increased without depriving others, there is no blame. Perseverance brings good fortune. It is favorable to have somewhere to go. One obtains servants but no longer has a separate home. If one is INCREASED without DEPRIVING others, there is NO BLAME. PERSEVERANCE brings GOOD FORTUNE. It is FAVORABLE to HAVE somewhere to GO. One OBTAINS SERVANTS but no longer has a SEPARATE HOME. One is increased without taking from others. This is the highest form of increase — gain that does not cause loss to anyone. One's influence expands so much that one obtains helpers and one's home becomes the world. 267. Increase without deprivation. The wise dragon advises you to seek increase that does not deprive others. True gain enriches everyone."],
  [42,"Increase",["generosity", "growth", "benefit", "movement", "abundance"],"Increase. It is favorable to have somewhere to go. It is favorable to cross the great water. INCREASE. It is FAVORABLE to HAVE somewhere to GO. It is FAVORABLE to CROSS the GREAT WATER. Wind and thunder — the wind blows and thunder rumbles, each increasing the other. This is the principle of increase: what is above diminishes itself to benefit what is below. The ruler diminishes their wealth to benefit the people, and the people, enriched, strengthen the state. This circular flow of increase benefits all. The time of increase is favorable for great undertakings — for crossing the great water, for beginning new projects. The abundance of the time supports bold action.","Wind and thunder: The image of Increase. Thus the sage, seeing good, imitates it; having faults, he corrects them. Wind and thunder — each increases the other. The sage, observing this, increases themselves by imitating what is good and correcting what is faulty. This is the inner work of increase: constantly adding what is beneficial and removing what is harmful. Like the wind and thunder that amplify each other, the sage's virtues grow through constant practice and their faults diminish through constant correction. 268. Constant self-improvement. The wise dragon advises you to continuously imitate what is good and correct what is faulty. Constant improvement is the essence of increase. ○ Initial nine: It furthers one to accomplish great deeds. Supreme good fortune. Without blame. It FURTHERS one to accomplish GREAT DEEDS. Supreme GOOD FORTUNE. WITHOUT BLAME. At the beginning of the time of increase, one has the capacity and the support to accomplish great deeds. This brings supreme good fortune and is without blame. 269. Great deeds. The wise dragon advises you to take advantage of the time of increase to accomplish great deeds. The energy of the time supports bold action. Six in the second place means: Someone does indeed increase them. Ten pairs of tortoises cannot oppose it. Perseverance brings good fortune. The king presents him before God. Good fortune. Someone does indeed INCREASE them. TEN PAIRS of TORTOISES cannot OPPOSE it. PERSEVERANCE brings GOOD FORTUNE. The KING PRESENTS them before GOD. GOOD FORTUNE. One receives increase from a powerful source. This increase is confirmed by the oracle and by the king's presentation before God. It is unquestionable and brings good fortune. 270. Divine increase. The wise dragon advises you to accept increase from higher sources with gratitude. Divine blessing cannot be opposed. Six in the third place means: One is enriched through unfortunate events. No blame if one is sincere. One walks in the middle and reports to the prince with a seal. One is ENRICHED through UNFORTUNATE EVENTS. NO BLAME if one is SINCERE. One WALKS in the MIDDLE and REPORTS to the PRINCE with a SEAL. One is enriched even through unfortunate events — adversity becomes a source of growth. If one is sincere and walks the middle path, one's report is accepted with authority. 271. Growth through adversity. The wise dragon advises you that even unfortunate events can enrich you. Sincerity transforms adversity into growth. Six in the fourth place means: If one walks in the middle and reports to the prince, he will follow. It is favorable to use this occasion to move the capital. If one WALKS in the MIDDLE and REPORTS to the PRINCE, he will FOLLOW. It is FAVORABLE to use this OCCASION to MOVE the CAPITAL. One has the trust of the ruler. One's counsel is followed. This is the time for bold decisions — like moving the capital. The increase of the time supports great changes. 272. Trusted counsel. The wise dragon advises you that trusted counsel can inspire bold changes. The time of increase supports great decisions. Nine in the fifth place means: If in truth you have a kind heart, ask not. Supreme good fortune. Truly, kindness will be recognized as your virtue. If in TRUTH you have a KIND HEART, ask NOT. Supreme GOOD FORTUNE. Truly, KINDNESS will be RECOGNIZED as your VIRTUE. One has a genuinely kind heart. There is no need to ask whether one's actions will be rewarded — kindness is its own reward and is recognized as virtue. Supreme good fortune follows naturally. 273. The kind heart. The wise dragon advises you to act from genuine kindness. A kind heart needs no validation; its virtue is self-evident. Nine at the top means: One brings increase to no one. Indeed, one even brings misfortune. If one is not single-minded in one's intention, misfortune comes. One brings INCREASE to NO ONE. Indeed, one even brings MISFORTUNE. If one is NOT SINGLE-MINDED in one's INTENTION, MISFORTUNE comes. One fails to increase anyone, including oneself. Instead, one brings misfortune. This is the consequence of not being single-minded — of lacking genuine intention. Increase requires wholeheartedness. 274. The cost of half-heartedness. The wise dragon advises you that half-heartedness brings misfortune. Increase requires wholehearted intention."],
  [43,"Breakthrough",["decision", "breakthrough", "courage", "proclaim", "determination"],"Breakthrough. One must resolutely make the matter known at the king's court. One must speak with loyalty. Danger! One must notify one's own city. It is not favorable to resort to arms. It is favorable to undertake something. BREAKTHROUGH. One must RESOLUTELY make the matter KNOWN at the KING's COURT. One must SPEAK with LOYALTY. DANGER! One must NOTIFY one's own CITY. It is NOT FAVORABLE to RESORT to ARMS. It is FAVORABLE to UNDERTAKE something. The lake has risen to heaven — it threatens to burst its bounds. This represents a time when the inferior element is about to be pushed out by the superior, but the process must be done resolutely and openly. One must proclaim the truth at the king's court, speaking with loyalty despite the danger. But one must not resort to force — the breakthrough must be achieved through moral power, not military might.","The lake has risen to heaven: The image of Breakthrough. Thus the superior person dispenses riches downward and avoids dwelling on their virtue. The lake has risen to heaven — it is about to rain. The superior person, observing this, dispenses riches downward, like rain that falls from the sky to nourish the earth. And they avoid dwelling on their virtue — they do not make a show of their goodness but simply act. True breakthrough comes from generous action, not from self-righteous display. 275. Generous breakthrough. The wise dragon advises you to achieve breakthrough through generosity, not through force. Dispense your riches downward like rain from heaven. ○ Initial nine: Mighty in the forward-striding toes. When one goes and is not equal to the task, one makes a mistake. MIGHTY in the FORWARD-STRIDING TOES. When one GOES and is NOT EQUAL to the TASK, one makes a MISTAKE. One is eager to advance but is not yet equal to the task. Rushing forward without adequate preparation leads to mistakes. 276. Premature advance. The wise dragon advises you not to rush forward before you are ready. Premature action leads to mistakes. Nine in the second place means: Cries of alarm. Weapons in the evening and at night. One should not be afraid. CRIES of ALARM. WEAPONS in the EVENING and at NIGHT. One should NOT be AFRAID. One is alert to danger — cries of alarm sound, weapons are ready. But one should not be afraid. Vigilance, not fear, is the proper response to danger. 277. Vigilant courage. The wise dragon advises you to be vigilant but not afraid. Alertness without fear is the proper response to danger. Nine in the third place means: To be powerful in the cheekbones brings misfortune. The superior person walks resolutely. TO BE POWERFUL in the CHEEKBONES brings MISFORTUNE. The SUPERIOR PERSON WALKS RESOLUTELY. Showing anger in one's face — power in the cheekbones — brings misfortune. The superior person does not show anger but walks resolutely alone. Inner determination, not outward display, is the way. 278. Inner determination. The wise dragon advises you to cultivate inner determination rather than showing outward anger. Resolute walking is more powerful than angry words. Nine in the fourth place means: There is no skin on the thighs, and walking is difficult. If one were to let oneself be led like a sheep, remorse would disappear. There is NO SKIN on the THIGHS, and WALKING is DIFFICULT. If one were to let oneself be LED like a SHEEP, REMORSE would DISAPPEAR. One's power is damaged — the thighs are wounded and walking is difficult. One must accept help — letting oneself be led like a sheep. This is not weakness but wisdom. 279. Accepting help. The wise dragon advises you to accept help when your own power is damaged. Being led is not weakness when you cannot walk alone. Nine in the fifth place means: In walking, one is like a weed. Only in the middle does one feel. One should know better. In WALKING, one is like a WEED. Only in the MIDDLE does one FEEL. One should KNOW BETTER. One walks like a weed — without firm roots, swaying with every wind. One must find the middle way and stand firm. One should know better than to be so easily swayed. 280. Finding the middle. The wise dragon advises you to find firm ground in the middle way. Being swayed by every wind is not the path of breakthrough. At the top a six means: No cry. In the end there will be misfortune. No CRY. In the END there will be MISFORTUNE. One does not cry out — one does not proclaim the truth. By remaining silent when one should speak, one allows misfortune to develop. The breakthrough fails because the truth was not proclaimed. 281. The cost of silence. The wise dragon advises you that silence when truth should be spoken leads to misfortune. Breakthrough requires the courage to proclaim what is true."],
  [44,"Coming to Meet",["encounter", "caution", "feminine influence", "duality", "threshold"],"Coming to meet. The woman is powerful. One should not take such a woman. SUDDEN ENCOUNTER. The WOMAN is POWERFUL. Do NOT TAKE this WOMAN. The ascent of the inferior element presents itself here in the image of a bold young woman who lightly gives herself and thus gains power. This would not be possible if the strong and illuminating element had not come to meet her. The inferior seems so innocuous and inviting that one revels in it. The inferior rises only because the superior does not see how dangerous it is and thus gives it power. If the superior had resisted from the beginning, the inferior would never have gained influence.","Under heaven there is wind: The image of Coming to Meet. Thus the prince acts when he proclaims his orders to the four quarters of heaven. Under heaven there is wind — the wind blows everywhere, penetrating all spaces. The prince, observing this, proclaims his orders to the four quarters — his influence reaches everywhere, like the wind. But the prince must be vigilant: just as the wind can carry both fragrance and poison, so the prince's orders must be carefully considered to ensure they carry only what is beneficial. 282. Vigilant proclamation. The wise dragon advises you to be vigilant about what you proclaim. Your influence reaches everywhere — ensure it carries only what is beneficial. ○ Initial six: One must restrain it with a brake of bronze. Perseverance brings good fortune. If one lets it go, one experiences misfortune. A fat pig lacks influence. Its tail keeps moving. One must RESTRAIN it with a BRAKE of BRONZE. PERSEVERANCE brings GOOD FORTUNE. If one LETS it GO, one experiences MISFORTUNE. A fat PIG LACKS INFLUENCE. Its TAIL keeps MOVING. One must restrain the inferior element at the very beginning — like applying a bronze brake to a wheel. If one lets it go, it will grow and cause misfortune. Even a fat pig that seems harmless keeps moving its tail — the inferior element is never truly still. 283. Early restraint. The wise dragon advises you to restrain the inferior element at its very beginning. Early restraint prevents later misfortune. Nine in the second place means: There is a fish in the tank. No blame. Not favorable to receive guests. There is a FISH in the TANK. NO BLAME. NOT FAVORABLE to RECEIVE GUESTS. The inferior element is contained — like a fish in a tank. It is under control and there is no blame. But one should not expose it to others — receiving guests would mean showing the inferior element to the world. 284. Contained inferiority. The wise dragon advises you to keep inferior elements contained. Do not expose them to the world. Nine in the third place means: There is no skin on the thighs, and walking is difficult. If one were to let oneself be led like a sheep, remorse would disappear. There is NO SKIN on the THIGHS, and WALKING is DIFFICULT. If one were to let oneself be LED like a SHEEP, REMORSE would DISAPPEAR. One is in a difficult position — unable to walk properly. One must accept guidance from others rather than trying to force one's way. 285. Guided movement. The wise dragon advises you to accept guidance when you cannot find your own way. Being led is better than wandering lost. Nine in the fourth place means: No fish in the tank. This brings misfortune. No FISH in the TANK. This brings MISFORTUNE. The inferior element has escaped containment — the fish is gone from the tank. Without containment, the inferior element causes misfortune. One has lost control of the situation. 286. Lost containment. The wise dragon advises you that losing containment of inferior elements leads to misfortune. Maintain control. Nine in the fifth place means: A melon covered with leaves. It contains a hidden line. If it falls from heaven, A MELON covered with LEAVES. It contains a HIDDEN LINE. If it FALLS from HEAVEN. The superior element wraps and protects the inferior — like leaves covering a melon. Within the melon is a hidden line — a seed of future development. If this seed falls from heaven — if it is given divine opportunity — it will grow into something great. 287. Hidden potential. The wise dragon advises you that even within the inferior, there may be a hidden seed of greatness. Protect it and give it opportunity. At the top a nine means: Coming to meet with horns. No blame. Coming to MEET with HORNS. NO BLAME. One meets the inferior element at the very top — the horns, the highest point. This is a position of isolation from the inferior element. One has maintained one's distance and is therefore without blame. 288. Isolated from the inferior. The wise dragon advises you that maintaining distance from inferior elements preserves your integrity. Isolation from what is harmful is without blame."],
  [45,"Gathering Together",["gathering", "community", "congregation", "offering", "solidarity"],"Gathering together. Success. The king approaches his temple. It is favorable to see the great man. Success through perseverance. Great offerings bring good fortune. Favorable to have somewhere to go. GATHERING TOGETHER. SUCCESS. The KING approaches his TEMPLE. It is FAVORABLE to SEE the GREAT MAN. SUCCESS through PERSEVERANCE. GREAT OFFERINGS bring GOOD FORTUNE. It is FAVORABLE to HAVE somewhere to GO. The lake over the earth — water gathers on the earth, forming lakes. This is the image of gathering together. People gather around a central figure — the king who approaches his temple. The gathering is not aimless but purposeful, centered on a shared purpose or sacred objective.","The lake over the earth: The image of Gathering Together. Thus the superior person renews their weapons in order to guard against the unforeseen. The lake over the earth — water gathers and can overflow at any moment. The superior person, observing this, renews their weapons to guard against the unforeseen. Even in times of gathering and community, one must be prepared for unexpected danger. The gathering provides strength, but it also creates vulnerability — a large group is a large target. Prudence requires preparation. 289. Prepared community. The wise dragon advises you that even in community, one must be prepared for the unforeseen. Strength in numbers requires vigilance. ○ Initial six: If one is sincere, but not to the end, there will sometimes be confusion, sometimes gathering together. If one calls out, one makes the right grasp. One is SINCERE, but NOT to the END. There will sometimes be CONFUSION, sometimes GATHERING TOGETHER. If one CALLS OUT, one makes the right GRASP. One's sincerity is not complete — it wavers between confusion and gathering. But if one calls out — if one reaches out genuinely — one makes the right connection. 290. Wavering sincerity. The wise dragon advises you to make your sincerity complete. Reaching out genuinely overcomes confusion. Six in the second place means: Letting oneself be drawn brings good fortune and remains without blame. If one is sincere, it is favorable to make even a small offering. Letting oneself be DRAWN brings GOOD FORTUNE and remains WITHOUT BLAME. If one is SINCERE, it is FAVORABLE to make even a SMALL OFFERING. One allows oneself to be drawn into the gathering. This is favorable if done with sincerity. Even a small offering, given with genuine heart, is acceptable. 291. Drawn by sincerity. The wise dragon advises you to let yourself be drawn into community with sincerity. Small offerings given with genuine heart are sufficient. Six in the third place means: Gathering together amid sighs. Nothing that would be favorable. One weeps and laments but no blame. GATHERING TOGETHER amid SIGHS. Nothing FAVORABLE. One WEEPS and LAMENTS but NO BLAME. One gathers with others but with sighs and lamentation. One is not in the right company or the right situation. But the weeping and lamentation show genuine feeling, so there is no blame. 292. Wrong company. The wise dragon advises you that gathering with the wrong people brings sighs. But genuine feeling is never blameworthy. Nine in the fourth place means: Great good fortune. All becomes without blame. Great GOOD FORTUNE. All becomes WITHOUT BLAME. One is in the right position and the right gathering. Great good fortune prevails, and everything is without blame. When the gathering is correct and one's position is right, everything flows naturally. 293. Right gathering. The wise dragon advises you that when the gathering is correct, everything flows naturally. Right company brings great good fortune. Nine in the fifth place means: If one is permanent in one's virtue, perseverance brings good fortune. Remorse disappears. If one is not satisfied, one gathers the people. No blame. If one is PERMANENT in one's VIRTUE, PERSEVERANCE brings GOOD FORTUNE. REMORSE disappears. If one is NOT SATISFIED, one GATHERS the PEOPLE. NO BLAME. One maintains permanent virtue through perseverance. If one is not yet satisfied with the gathering, one works to bring more people together. This effort is without blame. 294. Virtuous gathering. The wise dragon advises you to maintain permanent virtue while gathering people. Persistent effort in building community is without blame. At the top a six means: Lamenting, weeping, sighing. No blame. LAMENTING, WEEPING, SIGHING. NO BLAME. One laments the lack of proper gathering. The sighs and tears show genuine concern for the community. This grief is not blameworthy but shows the depth of one's commitment. 295. Grief for community. The wise dragon advises you that genuine grief for the state of community shows the depth of your commitment. Caring enough to weep is never blameworthy."],
  [46,"Pushing Upward",["ascent", "effort", "gradual advance", "perseverance", "growth"],"Pushing upward brings supreme success. One must see the great man. Have no fear. Departure toward the south brings good fortune. PUSHING UPWARD brings SUPREME SUCCESS. One must SEE the GREAT MAN. Have NO FEAR. DEPARTURE toward the SOUTH brings GOOD FORTUNE. Trees grow in the earth, pushing upward with steady effort. This is the image of pushing upward — the gradual, persistent effort that leads from the depths to the heights. The person who pushes upward must see the great man — must seek guidance from someone who has already achieved the heights. And they must have no fear, for the path upward requires courage.","In the earth, trees grow: The image of Pushing Upward. Thus the superior person devotes themselves diligently to small virtues. Trees grow in the earth — slowly, steadily, unceasingly. They do not rush but push upward with patient effort. The superior person, observing this, devotes themselves diligently to small virtues. Like the tree that grows a little each day, the superior person accumulates small virtues until they become great. There is no shortcut to the heights — only the steady accumulation of daily effort. 296. Steady growth. The wise dragon advises you to devote yourself to small daily virtues. Like a tree, steady growth reaches the heights. ○ Initial six: Pushing upward that meets with confidence. Great good fortune. PUSHING UPWARD that meets with CONFIDENCE. Great GOOD FORTUNE. At the beginning of the ascent, one meets with confidence and trust. This mutual confidence between those below and those above creates the conditions for great good fortune. 297. Confident ascent. The wise dragon advises you that mutual confidence is the foundation of successful ascent. Trust creates the conditions for growth. Nine in the second place means: If one is sincere, it is favorable to make even a small offering. No blame. If one is SINCERE, it is FAVORABLE to make even a SMALL OFFERING. NO BLAME. One approaches with sincerity, even if one's offering is small. Sincerity matters more than the size of the offering. 298. Sincere offering. The wise dragon advises you that sincerity in small offerings is more valuable than grand gestures without heart. Nine in the third place means: One pushes upward into an empty city. One pushes UPWARD into an EMPTY CITY. One advances into a place that has been vacated. There is no opposition. The ascent is unimpeded because the obstacles have been removed. 299. Unimpeded ascent. The wise dragon advises you that sometimes the path upward is clear because obstacles have been removed. Advance confidently. Six in the fourth place means: The king offers him a place on Mount Qi. Good fortune. No blame. The KING offers him a PLACE on MOUNT QI. GOOD FORTUNE. NO BLAME. The king recognizes one's worth and offers a place of honor. This is the reward for persistent effort. The ascent is acknowledged and rewarded. 300. Recognized effort. The wise dragon advises you that persistent effort will be recognized. The reward for steady ascent is acknowledgment from those above. Six in the fifth place means: Perseverance brings good fortune. One pushes upward step by step. PERSEVERANCE brings GOOD FORTUNE. One pushes UPWARD STEP by STEP. One ascends gradually, step by step. Each step is firm and sure. This gradual approach, sustained by perseverance, brings good fortune. 301. Step by step. The wise dragon advises you to ascend step by step. Gradual, firm progress brings good fortune. At the top a six means: Pushing upward in darkness. It is favorable to be unceasingly persevering. PUSHING UPWARD in DARKNESS. It is FAVORABLE to be UNCEASINGLY PERSEVERING. One pushes upward even in darkness — without seeing the goal. This requires unceasing perseverance. One must trust the process and continue even when the path is not visible. 302. Ascent in darkness. The wise dragon advises you to persevere even when you cannot see the goal. Trust the process and keep ascending."],
  [47,"Oppression",["exhaustion", "crisis", "resilience", "discourse", "adversity"],"Oppression. Success. Perseverance. The great man brings about good fortune. Without blame. When one has something to say, it is not believed. OPPRESSION. SUCCESS. PERSEVERANCE. The GREAT MAN brings about GOOD FORTUNE. WITHOUT BLAME. When one has SOMETHING to SAY, it is NOT BELIEVED. Exhaustion restricts but leads to success. Thanks to the continuation of the superior person. Without error, but words said are not believed. OPPRESSION. Let a SACRIFICE be performed. The ORACLE is AUSPICIOUS for the GREAT PERSON. WITHOUT HARM. Words are NOT BELIEVED. Times of adversity are the opposite of times of success, but times of adversity can lead to success if they fall to the right person. When a strong person faces adversity, they remain joyful despite the danger. That joy is the source of their later success.","There is no water in the lake: The image of Exhaustion. Thus the superior person stakes their life to follow their will. When the water has drained away, the lake dries up and is exhausted. That is the fate. This hexagram symbolizes an adverse fate in human life. In such times there is nothing one can do. One can only accept their fate and remain true to themselves. This situation involves the deepest stratum of one's being, for this stratum is itself superior to any external fate. The superior person stakes their life to follow their will — they would rather die than abandon their principles. 303. Fidelity in adversity. The wise dragon advises you to remain true to your principles even in the deepest adversity. Your inner self is superior to any external fate. ○ Initial six: One sits oppressed beneath a bare tree and enters a gloomy valley. For three years one sees nothing. One sits OPPRESSED beneath a BARE TREE and enters a GLOOMY VALLEY. For THREE YEARS one sees NOTHING. One is in the deepest oppression — beneath a bare tree, in a gloomy valley. For three years, nothing changes. One must endure this darkness with patience. 304. The long darkness. The wise dragon advises you to endure the long darkness with patience. Even three years of seeing nothing will eventually end. Nine in the second place means: One is oppressed while at a feast and has red knee covers. One is oppressed by a man in a high position. One is OPPRESSED while at a FEAST and has RED KNEE COVERS. One is oppressed by a MAN in a HIGH POSITION. One is at a feast — surrounded by abundance — but feels oppressed. The oppression comes from someone in a high position who does not recognize one's worth. One must wait for recognition. 305. Oppression amid abundance. The wise dragon advises you that oppression can come even amid abundance. Wait for recognition of your worth. Six in the third place means: One is oppressed by a stone and leans on thorns and thistles. One enters the house and does not see one's wife. Misfortune. One is OPPRESSED by a STONE and leans on THORNS and THISTLES. One enters the HOUSE and does NOT SEE one's WIFE. MISFORTUNE. One is trapped between hard obstacles — a stone before and thorns behind. Even at home, one finds no comfort. This is complete oppression. 306. Complete oppression. The wise dragon advises you that complete oppression leaves no comfort anywhere. Endure with the knowledge that it will pass. Nine in the fourth place means: One comes very quietly, oppressed in a golden wagon. One is humiliated but reaches the end. One comes very QUIETLY, oppressed in a GOLDEN WAGON. One is HUMILIATED but REACHES the END. One rides in a golden wagon — one has status and wealth — but feels oppressed. The golden wagon is itself a prison. One is humiliated but persists to the end. 307. The golden prison. The wise dragon advises you that even status and wealth can be a form of oppression. Persist through humiliation to reach the end. Nine in the fifth place means: One's nose and feet are cut off. Oppression at the hands of the one with the purple knee covers. One acts very gently. It brings joy. One's NOSE and FEET are CUT OFF. OPPRESSION at the hands of the one with the PURPLE KNEE COVERS. One acts very GENTLY. It brings JOY. One is severely oppressed — mutilated, as it were. But one acts gently toward the oppressor. This gentleness eventually brings joy. 308. Gentleness under oppression. The wise dragon advises you that gentleness under oppression eventually brings joy. Responding to harshness with gentleness disarms the oppressor. At the top a six means: One is oppressed by creeping vines. One is in motion and feels oppressed. One says: Movement brings remorse. If one is oppressed, one must first find the right moment. One is oppressed by CREEPING VINES. One is in MOTION and feels oppressed. One SAYS: Movement brings REMORSE. If one is oppressed, one must FIRST find the RIGHT MOMENT. One is entangled by creeping vines — the oppression is subtle and pervasive. Movement only makes it worse. One must find the right moment to act, not act out of frustration. 309. The right moment. The wise dragon advises you that when entangled in subtle oppression, movement without purpose only makes it worse. Wait for the right moment."],
  [48,"The Well",["source", "resources", "community", "constancy", "renewal"],"The well. The town may be changed, but the well cannot be changed. It neither decreases nor increases. They come and go and draw water from the well. If one arrives almost to the water but the rope does not reach, or if the pitcher is broken, it brings misfortune. THE WELL. The TOWN may be CHANGED, but the WELL cannot be CHANGED. It neither DECREASES nor INCREASES. They COME and GO and draw WATER from the WELL. If one arrives ALMOST to the WATER but the ROPE does NOT REACH, or if the PITCHER is BROKEN, it brings MISFORTUNE. In ancient China, capitals were moved from place to place. The style of architecture changed over the centuries, but the form of the well has remained the same from the most ancient times to now. The well is the symbol of the social structure that, arising from the elementary needs of humanity, does not depend on any political form. Political structures change. Nations change. But the life of people and their needs remain eternally the same.","Water over wood: The image of the Well. Thus the sage encourages the people in their work and exhorts them to mutual help. Water over wood — water rises through wood, as water is drawn up from a well by a wooden bucket. The sage, observing this, encourages the people in their work and exhorts them to mutual help. The well is the common resource that sustains all. It must be maintained by the community. The sage reminds people that their work is interconnected and that mutual support is the foundation of social life. 310. The common resource. The wise dragon advises you to maintain the common resources that sustain all. Mutual support is the foundation of community. ○ Initial six: The well is muddy. No animals come to the old well. At the first time, no one comes to it. The WELL is MUDDY. No ANIMALS come to the OLD WELL. At the FIRST TIME, no one comes to it. The well is neglected — it is muddy and no one comes to drink. This represents a social structure that has fallen into disrepair. No one benefits from it. 311. The neglected well. The wise dragon advises you that neglected resources benefit no one. Maintain what sustains the community. Nine in the second place means: One shoots fish in the abyss. The jug is broken and leaks. One SHOOTS FISH in the ABYSS. The JUG is BROKEN and LEAKS. One tries to draw water but the jug is broken — the water leaks out before it reaches the surface. One's efforts are wasted because the instrument is inadequate. 312. The broken instrument. The wise dragon advises you to ensure your instruments are adequate for the task. Broken tools waste effort. Nine in the third place means: The well is cleaned but no one drinks from it. This is the sorrow of my heart. One might draw water. If the king were clear-minded, good fortune might be obtained in common. The WELL is CLEANED but no one DRINKS from it. This is the SORROW of my HEART. One might DRAW WATER. If the KING were CLEAR-MINDED, GOOD FORTUNE might be obtained in COMMON. The well has been cleaned — the resource is available — but no one uses it. This is deeply sorrowful. If the king were clear-minded, everyone could benefit. 313. Available but unused. The wise dragon advises you that resources that are available but unused are a source of sorrow. Ensure that what you offer is actually received. Six in the fourth place means: The well is being lined. No blame. The WELL is being LINED. NO BLAME. The well is being repaired — lined with bricks to prevent the walls from crumbling. This is necessary maintenance that is without blame. 314. Necessary maintenance. The wise dragon advises you that maintaining your resources through proper repair is always without blame. Prevention is better than cure. Nine in the fifth place means: In the well there is a clear, cold spring. One can drink from it. In the WELL there is a CLEAR, COLD SPRING. One can DRINK from it. The well has been restored to its full purity. The water is clear and cold — refreshing and life-giving. One can drink and be renewed. 315. The pure spring. The wise dragon advises you that a well-maintained resource provides pure, refreshing sustenance. Cultivate purity in what you offer to others. At the top a six means: The well is open. One should not cover it. Having come from the well, one finds truth. Good fortune. The WELL is OPEN. One should NOT COVER it. Having COME from the WELL, one finds TRUTH. GOOD FORTUNE. The well is open and accessible to all. One should not cover it or restrict access. The water of truth flows freely, and all who come to the well find nourishment. 316. The open well. The wise dragon advises you to keep your resources open and accessible. Truth that flows freely nourishes all who seek it."],
  [49,"Revolution",["radical change", "transformation", "revolution", "new cycle", "courage"],"Revolution. On one's own day one has faith. Supreme success. Perseverance brings good fortune. Remorse disappears. REVOLUTION. On one's own DAY one has FAITH. Supreme SUCCESS. PERSEVERANCE brings GOOD FORTUNE. REMORSE disappears. The lake within the fire — fire below tries to rise, water above tries to sink. Their interaction produces change, revolution. This hexagram speaks of radical transformation — the moment when an old order must give way to a new one. Revolution is not change for its own sake but the necessary transformation that occurs when the old forms no longer serve life. On one's own day — at the appointed time — one has faith that the revolution is justified. When revolution comes at the right time and for the right reasons, it brings supreme success.","In the lake there is fire: The image of Revolution. Thus the sage regulates the calendar and clarifies the seasons. Fire within the lake — water extinguishes fire, fire evaporates water. Their mutual transformation represents revolution. The sage, observing this, regulates the calendar and clarifies the seasons. The calendar is the human revolution par excellence — the ordering of time itself. By establishing the seasons and the cycles, the sage brings order to change. Revolution is not chaos but the establishment of a new order that better serves the needs of the time. 317. Ordered revolution. The wise dragon advises you that true revolution creates order from change. Like the calendar that orders time, your transformation should bring clarity. ○ Initial nine: Wrapped in the hide of a yellow cow. WRAPPED in the HIDE of a YELLOW COW. At the beginning of revolution, one is bound and restrained — wrapped in yellow cow hide. The time for revolution has not yet come. One must wait and be patient. Yellow represents the middle way; cow hide represents binding. One is bound to the middle way, waiting for the right moment. 318. Patient waiting. The wise dragon advises you not to force revolution before its time. Wait until the moment is ripe. Six in the second place means: When one's own day comes, one undertakes revolution. Starting brings good fortune. No blame. When one's own DAY comes, one UNDERTAKES revolution. STARTING brings GOOD FORTUNE. NO BLAME. The appointed time has arrived. When one's own day comes — the moment when revolution is truly needed — one must act. Starting the revolution at the right time brings good fortune and is without blame. 319. The appointed time. The wise dragon advises you to act decisively when the time for revolution arrives. Right timing makes revolution legitimate. Nine in the third place means: Starting brings misfortune. Perseverance brings danger. When talk of revolution is complete three times, one has faith. Starting brings MISFORTUNE. PERSEVERANCE brings DANGER. When TALK of revolution is COMPLETE THREE TIMES, one has FAITH. One must not start revolution prematurely. If one perseveres in forcing change before the time is right, danger follows. But when the need for revolution has been discussed thoroughly — three times — faith develops and the revolution can proceed. 320. Thorough preparation. The wise dragon advises you to prepare thoroughly before undertaking revolution. Repeated discussion builds the faith needed for change. Nine in the fourth place means: Remorse disappears. One is believed. Changing the form of government brings good fortune. REMORSE disappears. One is BELIEVED. CHANGING the FORM of GOVERNMENT brings GOOD FORTUNE. The revolution has gained credibility. One is believed by the people. Changing the form of government — the external structures — brings good fortune because the time is right and the people are ready. 321. Credible revolution. The wise dragon advises you that revolution must be credible to succeed. When the people believe, change brings good fortune. Nine in the fifth place means: The great person changes like a tiger. Before one questions the oracle, one has faith. The GREAT PERSON CHANGES like a TIGER. Before one QUESTIONS the ORACLE, one has FAITH. The great person transforms like a tiger — with power, beauty, and inevitability. The tiger's stripes are clear and unmistakable. The revolution of the great person is so evident that even before consulting the oracle, one has faith in its rightness. 322. The tiger's transformation. The wise dragon advises you that the revolution of the great person is unmistakable. Like the tiger's stripes, true transformation is clear for all to see. At the top a six means: The superior person changes, the small person strips the face. Starting brings misfortune. To remain persevering brings good fortune. The SUPERIOR PERSON CHANGES, the SMALL PERSON STRIPS the FACE. STARTING brings MISFORTUNE. To REMAIN PERSEVERING brings GOOD FORTUNE. The revolution is complete. The superior person has transformed themselves, while the small person merely changes their face — their outward appearance — without inner change. At this point, starting new revolutions brings misfortune. The time is for consolidation, not for more change. 323. Consolidation after revolution. The wise dragon advises you that after revolution, the time is for consolidation. The superior person transforms within; the small person only changes their mask."],
  [50,"The Cauldron",["transformation", "nourishment", "civilization", "cooking", "vessel"],"The cauldron. Supreme success. Good fortune. THE CAULDRON. Supreme SUCCESS. GOOD FORTUNE. The cauldron is the vessel of transformation — the container in which raw ingredients are transformed into nourishment. Fire over wood — the fire burns beneath the cauldron, transforming what is within. This hexagram represents the highest form of cultural transformation — the alchemy by which the raw material of human experience is refined into wisdom and spiritual nourishment. The cauldron is also the vessel of sacrifice — the container in which offerings are prepared for the divine. Supreme success and good fortune come from the proper use of this transformative power.","Fire over wood: The image of the Cauldron. Thus the sage consolidates their destiny by maintaining the correct position. Fire over wood — the fire burns beneath the cauldron, cooking what is within. The sage, observing this, consolidates their destiny by maintaining the correct position. Like the cauldron that sits steadily on its legs while the fire transforms its contents, the sage maintains their upright position while the fires of experience transform their being. Destiny is consolidated not through force but through the steady application of transformative heat. 324. Steady transformation. The wise dragon advises you to maintain your correct position while the fires of transformation do their work. Destiny is consolidated through steady uprightness. ○ Initial six: A cauldron with upturned legs. It favors the removal of stagnation. One takes a concubine for the sake of having sons and heirs. No blame. A CAULDRON with UP TURNED LEGS. It FAVORS the REMOVAL of STAGNATION. One takes a CONCUBINE for the sake of having SONS and HEIRS. NO BLAME. The cauldron is overturned — its legs point upward. This clears out what is stagnant and prepares the vessel for new contents. Like taking a concubine to ensure heirs, one does what is necessary to ensure continuity. 325. Clearing stagnation. The wise dragon advises you to clear out what is stagnant before filling the vessel with new contents. Preparation is essential for transformation. Nine in the second place means: There is food in the cauldron. One's comrades are envious but cannot harm one. Good fortune. There is FOOD in the CAULDRON. One's COMRADES are ENVIOUS but cannot HARM one. GOOD FORTUNE. The cauldron contains nourishment — real substance. Others may be envious, but they cannot harm what is genuinely valuable. Good fortune prevails because the nourishment is real. 326. Genuine substance. The wise dragon advises you that genuine substance cannot be harmed by envy. When your work has real nourishment, it is protected by its own value. Nine in the third place means: The handles of the cauldron are altered. One is impeded in one's movement. Pheasant fat is not eaten. Once rain falls, remorse disappears. In the end, good fortune comes. The HANDLES of the CAULDRON are ALTERED. One is IMPEDED in one's MOVEMENT. PHEASANT FAT is NOT EATEN. Once RAIN FALLS, REMORSE disappears. In the END, GOOD FORTUNE comes. The cauldron's handles are changed — the means of carrying it are altered. One is impeded. The fine food inside cannot be eaten yet. But when rain falls — when the obstruction clears — remorse disappears and good fortune comes. 327. Temporary impediment. The wise dragon advises you that impediments to transformation are temporary. When the obstruction clears, the nourishment within becomes available. Nine in the fourth place means: The cauldron's legs are broken. The prince's food is spilled. One's face is red with shame. Misfortune. The CAULDRON's LEGS are BROKEN. The PRINCE's FOOD is SPILLED. One's FACE is RED with SHAME. MISFORTUNE. The cauldron is destroyed — its legs broken, its contents spilled. This is a profound failure — the means of transformation have been lost. The shame is deep because the nourishment meant for the prince has been wasted. 328. The broken vessel. The wise dragon advises you to take care with the vessel of transformation. When the means are destroyed, the purpose is lost. Six in the fifth place means: The cauldron has yellow ears and golden carrying rings. It is favorable to persevere. The CAULDRON has YELLOW EARS and GOLDEN CARRYING RINGS. It is FAVORABLE to PERSEVERE. The cauldron is fitted with yellow ears and golden rings — it is properly equipped for its sacred function. This represents the cauldron at its best — well-made, properly positioned, ready to fulfill its purpose. 329. The properly equipped vessel. The wise dragon advises you to ensure your vessel of transformation is properly equipped. Good tools enable good work. Nine at the top means: The cauldron has jade rings. Great good fortune. Nothing that does not act to further. The CAULDRON has JADE RINGS. Great GOOD FORTUNE. Nothing that does NOT act to FURTHER. The cauldron is adorned with jade rings — the highest ornament. Jade represents virtue and perfection. The transformation is complete and the result is perfect. Great good fortune in every way. 330. The perfected vessel. The wise dragon advises you that the highest transformation produces results of jade-like perfection. Virtue is the ultimate ornament."],
  [51,"The Arousing Thunder",["awakening", "shock", "fear", "renewal", "sound"],"The arousing brings success. Thunder comes and there are cries of fright. Then laughs and talk. The thunder startles for a hundred miles. THE AROUSING brings SUCCESS. THUNDER comes and there are CRIES of FRIGHT. Then LAUGHS and TALK. The THUNDER STARTLES for a HUNDRED MILES. Thunder repeated — the arousing doubled. The shock comes twice. First comes fear, then laughter. The thunder startles everyone within a hundred miles, but the one who understands the shock is not overwhelmed by it. The arousing represents the eldest son, the spring, the east — the principle of new beginning. Success comes to those who can receive the shock without losing their composure.","Thunder repeats itself: The image of the Arousing. Thus the sage lives with awe and reconsiders and reforms. Thunder repeats — the shock comes again and again. The sage, observing this, lives with awe — maintaining a constant awareness of the power that moves through all things. And they reconsider and reform — each shock provides an opportunity for self-examination and improvement. The arousing is not merely frightening but transformative. Each thunderclap is an invitation to examine one's life and make corrections. 331. Transformative shock. The wise dragon advises you to receive each shock as an invitation to self-examination. Awe and reform are the proper responses to thunder. ○ Initial nine: Thunder comes — oh, oh! Then follows laughing and talking. The thunder startles for a hundred miles. One is not so startled as to let fall the sacrificial spoon and the anointing wine. THUNDER comes — OH, OH! Then follows LAUGHING and TALKING. The THUNDER STARTLES for a HUNDRED MILES. One is NOT so STARTLED as to let fall the SACRIFICIAL SPOON and the ANOINTING WINE. The shock comes with great force. There is initial fear, then relief and laughter. But the truly composed person does not let the shock disrupt their sacred duties — they hold the sacrificial spoon steady. 332. Composed in shock. The wise dragon advises you to maintain composure during shocks. The one who holds steady through the thunder is the one who truly understands. Six in the second place means: Thunder brings danger. Hundreds of thousands of times one loses one's possessions. One should not pursue the matter. In seven days one will recover it. THUNDER brings DANGER. Hundreds of THOUSANDS of TIMES one LOSES one's POSSESSIONS. One should NOT pursue the MATTER. In SEVEN DAYS one will RECOVER it. The shock causes great loss. But one should not chase after what is lost. In seven days — when the cycle completes — what was lost returns naturally. 333. Natural recovery. The wise dragon advises you not to chase after losses caused by shock. What is meant to return will return in its own time. Six in the third place means: Thunder brings stirring. If one acts in response to the shock, one remains free of blame. THUNDER brings STIRRING. If one ACTS in RESPONSE to the SHOCK, one remains FREE of BLAME. The shock stirs one to action. If one responds appropriately to the arousing energy, one remains without blame. The thunder is not merely frightening but motivating. 334. Motivated action. The wise dragon advises you to respond to the energy of shock with appropriate action. The thunder motivates positive change. Nine in the fourth place means: Thunder falls into the mire. THUNDER falls into the MIRE. The shock falls into mud — the arousing energy is mired and cannot express itself. The transformation is blocked. One must wait for the energy to free itself. 335. Mired energy. The wise dragon advises you that sometimes the arousing energy gets stuck. Patience is needed until it frees itself. Six in the fifth place means: Thunder goes and comes. There is danger. One should attend to one's affairs and not lose what one has. THUNDER GOES and COMES. There is DANGER. One should ATTEND to one's AFFAIRS and NOT LOSE what one HAS. The thunder comes and goes — the shock is repeated. There is danger in the instability. One must attend carefully to one's affairs and protect what one has. 336. Attentive preservation. The wise dragon advises you to be attentive during repeated shocks. Protect what you have while the instability continues. At the top a six means: Thunder brings consternation. One looks around with bewilderment. Going brings misfortune. Though it is not yet one's own affair, one meets with reproach. THUNDER brings CONSTERNATION. One LOOKS AROUND with BEWILDERMENT. GOING brings MISFORTUNE. Though it is NOT YET one's OWN AFFAIR, one meets with REPROACH. The shock brings complete consternation. One looks around bewildered, not knowing which way to turn. Going forward brings misfortune. Even though the affair is not yet one's own, one is reproached for not acting. 337. Bewildered by shock. The wise dragon advises you that some shocks cause complete bewilderment. In such moments, do not force action. Wait for clarity to return."],
  [52,"Keeping Still",["stillness", "meditation", "limits", "pause", "introspection"],"Keeping still. Keeping the back still so that one no longer feels the body. One goes into the courtyard and does not see one's people. Without blame. KEEPING STILL. Keeping the BACK STILL so that one NO LONGER FEELS the BODY. One goes into the COURTYARD and does NOT SEE one's PEOPLE. WITHOUT BLAME. True stillness involves remaining motionless when the time has come not to move and advancing when the time has come to advance. In this way, rest and movement are in agreement with the demands of the time, and thus there is light in life. The hexagram means the end and beginning of all movement. The back is mentioned because it is on the back that all the nerve fibers that make movement possible are located. If the movement of these nerves of the spine can be brought to a state of rest, the ego with its impatience disappears. When a person has achieved calm, they can turn to the outer world.","Mountains joined together: The image of Keeping Still. Thus the superior person does not allow their thoughts to go beyond their situation. Mountains standing close together — the image of doubled stillness. The heart follows its impulses constantly. This cannot be changed, but the movements of the heart — that is, a person's thoughts — must limit themselves to the immediate situation. All thought that goes beyond what is immediate only brings pain to the heart. 338. Limited thought. The wise dragon advises you to limit your thoughts to the immediate situation. Thoughts that go beyond the present bring only pain. ○ Initial six: Keeping one's toes still. No blame. One should remain persevering. Keeping one's TOES STILL. NO BLAME. One should REMAIN PERSEVERING. At the beginning of stillness, one keeps the toes still — one does not even begin to move. This preliminary stillness is correct. One should remain persevering in this immobility. 339. Preliminary stillness. The wise dragon advises you to begin stillness at the most basic level. Not even the toes move. Six in the second place means: Keeping one's calves still. One cannot rescue the one one follows. One's heart is not cheerful. Keeping one's CALVES still. One cannot RESCUE the one one FOLLOWS. One's HEART is NOT CHEERFUL. One keeps the calves still but cannot help the one they follow. The heart is unhappy because one sees someone heading toward danger but cannot move to help. 340. Impotent stillness. The wise dragon advises you that stillness sometimes means being unable to help others. Accept this limitation. Nine in the third place means: Keeping one's loins still. Making the sacrum stiff. Dangerous. The heart suffocates. Keeping one's LOINS still. Making the SACRUM STIFF. DANGEROUS. The HEART SUFFOCATES. Stillness is forced upon the lower body — the loins and sacrum are made rigid. This forced stillness is dangerous because it causes the heart to suffocate. Stillness must be natural, not forced. 341. The danger of forced stillness. The wise dragon advises you that forced stillness is dangerous. True stillness must come from within, not from external constraint. Six in the fourth place means: Keeping one's trunk still. No blame. Keeping one's TRUNK still. NO BLAME. One keeps the trunk — the body — still. This is the central stillness that brings the body to rest. There is no blame because the stillness is appropriate to the position. 342. Central stillness. The wise dragon advises you that stillness of the body brings peace. When the trunk is still, the whole person benefits. Six in the fifth place means: Keeping one's jaw still. One's words have order. Remorse disappears. Keeping one's JAW still. One's WORDS have ORDER. REMORSE disappears. One keeps the jaw still — one does not speak unnecessarily. When one does speak, one's words have order and measure. This disciplined speech brings the disappearance of remorse. 343. Disciplined speech. The wise dragon advises you to keep your jaw still. Speak only when necessary and with order. Disciplined speech eliminates remorse. At the top a nine means: Noblehearted stillness. Good fortune. NOBLEHEARTED stillness. GOOD FORTUNE. At the top of the hexagram, stillness reaches its highest form — noblehearted stillness. One is still not from compulsion or fear but from the nobility of one's character. This is the truest stillness and brings good fortune. 344. Noble stillness. The wise dragon advises you that the highest stillness comes from nobility of character. When stillness is a choice, not a compulsion, it brings the greatest good fortune."],
  [53,"Development",["gradualness", "slow progress", "perseverance", "marriage", "maturity"],"Development. The maiden is given in marriage. Good fortune. Perseverance is favorable. DEVELOPMENT. The MAIDEN is given in MARRIAGE. GOOD FORTUNE. PERSEVERANCE is FAVORABLE. Development is gradual progress — the slow, steady advance that cannot be hurried. Like a tree that grows on a mountain, development follows its own pace. The maiden given in marriage follows the proper ceremonies step by step — each stage of the courtship and marriage must be completed before the next begins. This is the way of all true development: patient, methodical, and correct. Haste brings failure; perseverance brings good fortune.","Above the mountain there is a tree: The image of Development. Thus the superior person dwells in nobility and virtue to improve customs. A tree on the mountain — it grows slowly, steadily, rising above the mountain peak. The superior person, observing this, dwells in nobility and virtue to improve the customs of the people. Like the tree that rises gradually above the mountain, the superior person's influence grows slowly but surely. Improvement of customs cannot be forced — it must develop naturally from the example of noble character. 345. Gradual influence. The wise dragon advises you that true influence grows gradually like a tree on a mountain. Noble character improves the world slowly but surely. ○ Initial six: The wild goose gradually draws near to the shore. The young son is in danger. There is talk. No blame. The WILD GOOSE gradually draws near to the SHORE. The YOUNG SON is in DANGER. There is TALK. NO BLAME. The wild goose — symbol of orderly progression — draws near to the shore. The young son is in danger, and there is talk of the situation. But there is no blame because the development is proceeding correctly, even if slowly. 346. Cautious approach. The wise dragon advises you to approach development with caution. Even when there is danger and talk, correct progress is without blame. Six in the second place means: The wild goose gradually draws near to the cliff. One eats and drinks in peace and joy. Good fortune. The WILD GOOSE gradually draws near to the CLIFF. One EATS and DRINKS in PEACE and JOY. GOOD FORTUNE. The goose approaches the cliff — a higher position. One eats and drinks in peace and joy — one enjoys the fruits of one's gradual advance. This brings good fortune. 347. Peaceful enjoyment. The wise dragon advises you to enjoy the fruits of gradual progress. Peace and joy accompany correct development. Nine in the third place means: The wild goose gradually draws near to the plateau. The man goes forth and does not return. The woman carries the child but does not bring it forth. Misfortune. It is favorable to fight off robbers. The WILD GOOSE gradually draws near to the PLATEAU. The MAN goes forth and does NOT RETURN. The WOMAN carries the CHILD but does NOT bring it FORTH. MISFORTUNE. It is FAVORABLE to FIGHT OFF ROBBERS. The goose reaches the plateau — a high, exposed position. The man goes forth on a journey and does not return. The woman is pregnant but cannot give birth. Development is blocked. One must fight off the forces that obstruct progress. 348. Blocked development. The wise dragon advises you that development can be blocked by external forces. Fight off what obstructs your progress. Six in the fourth place means: The wild goose gradually draws near to the tree. Perhaps it will find a flat branch. No blame. The WILD GOOSE gradually draws near to the TREE. Perhaps it will find a FLAT BRANCH. NO BLAME. The goose approaches the tree — it seeks a resting place. Perhaps it will find a flat branch where it can settle. This is not the ideal position but it is adequate. There is no blame. 349. Adequate rest. The wise dragon advises you that during gradual development, adequate rest is acceptable even if it is not ideal. Nine in the fifth place means: The wild goose gradually draws near to the summit. For three years the woman has no child. In the end, nothing hinders. Good fortune. The WILD GOOSE gradually draws near to the SUMMIT. For THREE YEARS the WOMAN has NO CHILD. In the END, NOTHING HINDERS. GOOD FORTUNE. The goose reaches the summit — the highest point. But the woman has no child for three years — the fruit of the development is delayed. In the end, however, nothing hinders and good fortune comes. 350. Delayed fruit. The wise dragon advises you that the fruit of gradual development may be delayed but will come in the end. Patience brings good fortune. At the top a nine means: The wild goose gradually draws near to the clouds. Its feathers can be used for sacred decoration. Good fortune. The WILD GOOSE gradually draws near to the CLOUDS. Its FEATHERS can be used for SACRED DECORATION. GOOD FORTUNE. The goose reaches the clouds — the highest point of development. Its feathers are used for sacred decoration — the achievement becomes an ornament to something greater than itself. This is the culmination of gradual development. 351. Sacred culmination. The wise dragon advises you that the culmination of gradual development becomes a sacred ornament. Your achievement serves something greater than yourself."],
  [54,"The Marrying Maiden",["subordination", "roles", "relationships", "expectation", "destiny"],"The marrying maiden. Undertaking brings misfortune. Nothing that would be favorable. The MARRYING MAIDEN. UNDERTAKING brings MISFORTUNE. Nothing FAVORABLE. Thunder over the lake — the eldest son above, the youngest daughter below. The maiden is given in marriage but as a concubine, not as the principal wife. She must accept a subordinate position. This hexagram speaks of relationships in which one does not hold the primary position. The marrying maiden must be patient and devoted, accepting her role with grace. Undertaking great things in this position brings misfortune — one must work within the limitations of one's station.","Thunder over the lake: The image of the Marrying Maiden. Thus the superior person knows what endures through what passes. Thunder over the lake — the daughter given in marriage but in a subordinate position. The superior person, observing this, knows what endures through what passes. They understand that all positions are temporary and that true worth endures regardless of station. The marrying maiden may be subordinate now, but her devotion and patience will eventually be recognized. 352. Enduring through change. The wise dragon advises you to know what endures through what passes. True worth is independent of position. ○ Initial nine: The marrying maiden as a concubine. A lame person who can tread. Undertaking brings good fortune. The MARRYING MAIDEN as a CONCUBINE. A LAME PERSON who can TREAD. UNDERTAKING brings GOOD FORTUNE. One is in a subordinate position — like a concubine rather than a wife. But even a lame person who can tread makes progress. Undertaking within one's limitations brings good fortune. 353. Progress within limits. The wise dragon advises you that even from a subordinate position, progress is possible. Work within your limitations. Nine in the second place means: A one-eyed person who can see. The perseverance of a solitary person brings good fortune. A ONE-EYED PERSON who can SEE. The PERSEVERANCE of a SOLITARY PERSON brings GOOD FORTUNE. One has limited vision — like a one-eyed person — but can still see enough to proceed. The solitary person who perseveres in their devotion brings good fortune. 354. Limited but sufficient. The wise dragon advises you that even limited vision is sufficient when combined with perseverance. Six in the third place means: The marrying maiden as a slave. She marries as a concubine. The MARRYING MAIDEN as a SLAVE. She MARRIES as a CONCUBINE. One is in the lowest position — a slave who marries as a concubine. This is the extreme of subordination. But even this position can be accepted with dignity. 355. Dignified subordination. The wise dragon advises you that even the lowest position can be held with dignity. Acceptance is not the same as defeat. Nine in the fourth place means: The marrying maiden draws out the time. A late marriage comes in due course. The MARRYING MAIDEN DRAWS OUT the TIME. A LATE MARRIAGE comes in DUE COURSE. One delays the marriage — draws out the time. But a late marriage comes in due course. Patience is rewarded. What is meant to happen will happen at the right time. 356. Patient waiting. The wise dragon advises you that patience in waiting brings the right outcome at the right time. What is destined will arrive. Six in the fifth place means: The sovereign I gave his daughter in marriage. The sleeves of the princess were not as good as those of the concubine. The moon nearly full. Good fortune. The SOVEREIGN I gave his DAUGHTER in MARRIAGE. The SLEEVES of the PRINCESS were NOT as GOOD as those of the CONCUBINE. The MOON nearly FULL. GOOD FORTUNE. The emperor's daughter marries but her robes are simpler than those of the concubine. This is humility in high position. The moon nearly full — approaching perfection but not quite there. Good fortune. 357. Humble nobility. The wise dragon advises you that true nobility is shown through humility. Approaching perfection without claiming it brings good fortune. At the top a six means: The woman holds the basket but there are no fruits. The man stabs the sheep but no blood flows. Nothing that would further. The WOMAN HOLDS the BASKET but there are no FRUITS. The MAN STABS the SHEEP but no BLOOD flows. Nothing FAVORABLE. The rituals are performed but without substance — an empty basket, a sacrifice without blood. This is the end of the marrying maiden — form without content. Nothing can be accomplished. 358. Empty ritual. The wise dragon advises you that ritual without substance accomplishes nothing. Form must be filled with genuine content."],
  [55,"Abundance",["fullness", "brilliance", "peak", "transience", "ephemeral fullness"],"Abundance brings success. The king attains it. Do not be grieved. Be like the sun at noon. ABUNDANCE. SUCCESS. The KING attains it. Do NOT be GRIEVED. Be like the SUN at NOON. Abundance is the peak — the moment of greatest fullness. The king who attains abundance has reached the height of power and prosperity. But abundance, like the sun at noon, contains within it the seed of its own decline. After noon, the sun begins to set. The wise person does not grieve at this knowledge but shines all the more brightly, like the sun at its zenith that illuminates everything beneath it with full intensity.","Thunder and lightning come together: The image of Abundance. Thus the superior person decides criminal cases and carries out punishments. Thunder and lightning — clarity and movement combined. The superior person, observing this, decides criminal cases with clarity and carries out punishments with decisiveness. Abundance requires justice — the fullness of the time demands that wrongs be righted and order be maintained. Like lightning that illuminates and thunder that acts, the superior person sees clearly and acts decisively. 359. Clear justice in abundance. The wise dragon advises you that times of abundance require clear justice. See clearly and act decisively. ○ Initial nine: When one meets one's match, one can stay ten days. No blame. Going brings recognition. When one meets one's MATCH, one can stay TEN DAYS. NO BLAME. GOING brings RECOGNITION. One meets one's match — an equal. One can stay for ten days — a complete cycle. Going brings recognition. When equals meet, there is harmony and recognition. 360. Meeting one's match. The wise dragon advises you that meeting an equal brings harmony. Stay for the complete cycle and you will be recognized. Six in the second place means: The curtain is so thick that one can see the Dipper at noon. One meets the ruling prince of the darkness. The CURTAIN is so THICK that one can see the DIPPER at NOON. One meets the RULING PRINCE of the DARKNESS. The darkness is so thick that stars are visible at noon. One encounters the prince of darkness — the ruling power of the obscure. This is a time of great confusion. 361. Darkness at noon. The wise dragon advises you that even at the peak of abundance, darkness can appear. Recognize the confusion and do not be deceived. Nine in the third place means: The thick curtain that screens the sun. At noon one sees the little finger. The THICK CURTAIN that SCREENS the SUN. At NOON one sees the LITTLE FINGER. The darkness is so complete that one can barely see one's own hand. The abundance is obscured by a thick curtain. One must act with what little light is available. 362. Acting in deep darkness. The wise dragon advises you that when abundance is obscured, act with whatever light is available. Even small vision is better than none. Nine in the fourth place means: The curtain is of such thickness that one sees the Dipper at noon. One meets the hidden ruler. The CURTAIN is of such THICKNESS that one sees the DIPPER at NOON. One meets the HIDDEN RULER. The darkness is profound, but one encounters the hidden ruler — the power behind the darkness. This meeting, though in obscurity, is significant. 363. The hidden ruler. The wise dragon advises you that in the deepest darkness, one may encounter hidden powers. This meeting is significant even if obscure. Six in the fifth place means: Lines are coming, blessing and fame are near. Good fortune. LINES are COMING, BLESSING and FAME are NEAR. GOOD FORTUNE. Lines of light are coming — the darkness is beginning to lift. Blessing and fame are near. Good fortune approaches. The abundance begins to manifest its benefits. 364. Approaching light. The wise dragon advises you that after deep darkness, light returns. Blessing and fame follow the clearing of obscurity. At the top a six means: The house is made abundant. Screens surround it. One peers through the gate and sees no one. For three years one sees nothing. The HOUSE is made ABUNDANT. SCREENS surround it. One PEERS through the GATE and sees NO ONE. For THREE YEARS one sees NOTHING. The house is abundant but completely isolated — screens surround it, no one is visible. For three years, nothing is seen. Abundance without connection leads to complete isolation. 365. Isolated abundance. The wise dragon advises you that abundance without connection leads to isolation. Wealth behind screens benefits no one."],
  [56,"The Wanderer",["journey", "stranger", "humility", "caution", "adaptation"],"The wanderer. Success in small things. The perseverance of the wanderer brings good fortune. THE WANDERER. SUCCESS in SMALL THINGS. The PERSEVERANCE of the WANDERER brings GOOD FORTUNE. Fire on the mountain top — the fire burns briefly on the summit and moves on. This is the image of the wanderer — one who has no permanent home but passes through places briefly. The wanderer must be cautious and modest. Great things are not possible for one without roots. But in small things, success can be found. The perseverance of the wanderer — the ability to maintain one's integrity while passing through strange lands — brings good fortune.","Fire on the mountain top: The image of the Wanderer. Thus the superior person is clear and intelligent in applying punishments and does not drag out legal processes. Fire on the mountain top — the fire burns brightly but briefly, then moves on. The superior person, observing this, is clear and intelligent in applying punishments. Like the fire that illuminates briefly, legal processes should be swift and clear. The wanderer cannot afford to be tied up in lengthy proceedings. Justice must be prompt. 366. Swift justice. The wise dragon advises you to be swift and clear in all matters. The wanderer cannot afford delays. Prompt justice is the only kind possible. ○ Initial six: If the wanderer busies themselves with trivial things, they bring misfortune upon themselves. If the WANDERER busies themselves with TRIVIAL THINGS, they bring MISFORTUNE upon themselves. At the beginning of the wandering, one busies oneself with trivial things. This brings misfortune because it wastes the limited energy available to the wanderer. 367. Avoid triviality. The wise dragon advises you not to waste energy on trivial things. The wanderer's resources are limited and must be used wisely. Six in the second place means: The wanderer comes to an inn. They have their possessions. They gain the steadfastness of a young servant. The WANDERER comes to an INN. They have their POSSESSIONS. They gain the STEADFASTNESS of a YOUNG SERVANT. The wanderer finds lodging — an inn. They have their possessions, meaning they have not lost everything. They gain a young servant — someone loyal and steadfast to help them. 368. Finding shelter. The wise dragon advises you that even the wanderer can find shelter and loyal help. Maintain your possessions and accept assistance. Six in the third place means: The wanderer's inn burns down. They lose the steadfastness of their young servant. Danger. The WANDERER's INN burns DOWN. They LOSE the STEADFASTNESS of their YOUNG SERVANT. DANGER. The wanderer's shelter is destroyed by fire. They lose their loyal helper. This is danger — the wanderer is left alone and exposed. 369. Lost shelter. The wise dragon advises you that the wanderer's shelter can be lost suddenly. Prepare for the possibility of sudden displacement. Nine in the fourth place means: The wanderer rests in a shelter. They obtain their possessions and an ax. My heart is not glad. The WANDERER rests in a SHELTER. They OBTAIN their POSSESSIONS and an AX. My HEART is NOT GLAD. The wanderer finds a shelter and recovers their possessions, along with an ax — a means of defense. But the heart is not glad because the situation is still precarious. 370. Precarious security. The wise dragon advises you that even when the wanderer finds security, the heart knows it is temporary. Vigilance must continue. Six in the fifth place means: One shoots a pheasant. It falls with the first arrow. In the end, this brings both praise and office. One SHOOTS a PHEASANT. It FALLS with the FIRST ARROW. In the END, this brings both PRAISE and OFFICE. The wanderer demonstrates their skill — shooting a pheasant with the first arrow. This achievement brings praise and eventually an official position. The wanderer is recognized for their abilities. 371. Recognition through skill. The wise dragon advises you that even as a wanderer, demonstrated skill brings recognition and eventually a position. At the top a nine means: The bird's nest burns. The wanderer laughs at first, then must lament. With ease one loses the cow. Misfortune. The BIRD's NEST burns. The WANDERER LAUGHS at FIRST, then must LAMENT. With EASE one LOSES the COW. MISFORTUNE. The nest burns — the last shelter is destroyed. The wanderer first laughs — perhaps thinking it does not matter — but then must lament. The cow, representing docility and wealth, is lost with ease. This is misfortune. 372. The final loss. The wise dragon advises you that careless laughter in the face of loss leads to deeper lamentation. Take every loss seriously."],
  [57,"The Gentle Wind",["gentle penetration", "gentleness", "constancy", "influence", "humility"],"The gentle. Success in small things. It is favorable to have somewhere to go. It is favorable to see the great man. THE GENTLE. SUCCESS in SMALL THINGS. It is FAVORABLE to HAVE somewhere to GO. It is FAVORABLE to SEE the GREAT MAN. Wind following wind — the gentle penetrating doubled. The wind penetrates everywhere, not through force but through persistence. It enters every crack, every opening. This is the way of the gentle — success through persistence rather than force. Great things cannot be accomplished by gentleness alone, but in small things it is highly effective. It is favorable to see the great man because the gentle influence needs guidance from above to be properly directed.","The wind that follows the wind: The image of the Gentle. Thus the superior person repeats their orders and carries out their business. Wind following wind — the gentle penetrates again and again. The superior person, observing this, repeats their orders and carries out their business. Like the wind that must blow repeatedly to move heavy objects, the superior person repeats their instructions until they are fully understood and implemented. 373. Persistent influence. The wise dragon advises you that gentle persistence achieves what force cannot. Repeat your instructions until they take root. ○ Initial six: In advancing and in retreating, it is favorable for the perseverance of a warrior. In ADVANCING and in RETREATING, it is FAVORABLE for the PERSEVERANCE of a WARRIOR. At the beginning of the gentle, one advances and retreats — uncertain. But the perseverance of a warrior — steady determination — is favorable. Even in uncertainty, resolve is the key. 374. Resolute uncertainty. The wise dragon advises you that even when uncertain, maintain warrior-like resolve. Steadfastness guides through indecision. Six in the second place means: Penetration beneath the bed. One employs priests and magicians in abundance. Without blame. Penetration BENEATH the BED. One EMPLOYS PRIESTS and MAGICIANS in ABUNDANCE. WITHOUT BLAME. The gentle penetration reaches beneath the bed — into the hidden places. One employs many helpers — priests and magicians — to address what is hidden. This thoroughness is without blame. 375. Hidden penetration. The wise dragon advises you to penetrate into hidden places. Addressing what is concealed requires thoroughness. Nine in the third place means: Obstinate penetration. Humiliation. OBSTINATE penetration. HUMILIATION. One penetrates too forcefully — with obstinacy rather than gentleness. This contradicts the nature of the hexagram and brings humiliation. Gentleness must remain gentle; force defeats its own purpose. 376. The error of force. The wise dragon advises you that force contradicts gentleness. Obstinate penetration defeats itself and brings humiliation. Six in the fourth place means: Remorse disappears. One catches three kinds of game in the hunt. REMORSE disappears. One catches THREE KINDS of GAME in the HUNT. The gentle penetration is successful — one catches three kinds of game. Remorse disappears because the approach has yielded abundant results. 377. Abundant results. The wise dragon advises you that gentle persistence yields abundant results. When the approach is correct, remorse disappears. Nine in the fifth place means: Perseverance brings good fortune. Remorse disappears. Nothing that does not further. No beginning but an end. Before change, three days. After change, three days. PERSEVERANCE brings GOOD FORTUNE. REMORSE disappears. Nothing that does NOT FURTHER. No BEGINNING but an END. Before CHANGE, THREE DAYS. After CHANGE, THREE DAYS. One perseveres and achieves good fortune. The gentle influence accomplishes its purpose completely. Before and after the change, careful preparation and consolidation are needed — three days each. 378. Complete influence. The wise dragon advises you that gentle influence, when persevered in, accomplishes its purpose completely. Careful preparation and consolidation surround every change. At the top a nine means: Penetration beneath the bed. One loses one's sharp weapons. Perseverance brings misfortune. Penetration BENEATH the BED. One LOSES one's SHARP WEAPONS. PERSEVERANCE brings MISFORTUNE. The penetration goes too deep — beneath the bed. One loses one's weapons — the means of defense. Persevering in this excessive penetration brings misfortune. Gentleness carried to extremes becomes weakness. 379. Excessive gentleness. The wise dragon advises you that gentleness carried to extremes becomes weakness. Know the limit of gentle penetration."],
  [58,"The Joyous Lake",["joy", "openness", "communication", "trust", "harmony"],"The joyous. Success. Perseverance is favorable. THE JOYOUS. SUCCESS. PERSEVERANCE is FAVORABLE. The lake upon the lake — joy doubled, reflected and amplified. The joyous represents the youngest daughter, the west, autumn — the principle of gladness and communication. True joy is not mere pleasure but the deep satisfaction that comes from inner strength expressed outwardly. The lakes rest upon each other, feeding and refreshing one another. Joy shared is joy multiplied. Perseverance is favorable because joy that endures is more valuable than joy that is fleeting.","Lakes resting upon each other: The image of the Joyous. Thus the superior person gathers with friends for instruction and practice. Lakes resting upon each other — water feeds water, joy feeds joy. The superior person, observing this, gathers with friends for instruction and practice. Like lakes that exchange their waters, friends exchange ideas and encouragement. Joy in learning and practice creates a community that nourishes all its members. 380. Joyful community. The wise dragon advises you to gather with friends for joyful learning. Community nourishes all its members. ○ Initial nine: Contented joy. Good fortune. CONTENTED joy. GOOD FORTUNE. At the beginning of the joyous, one is content with simple joy. This contented joy, uncomplicated and genuine, brings good fortune. 381. Simple joy. The wise dragon advises you that simple, genuine joy brings good fortune. Do not complicate happiness. Nine in the second place means: Sincere joy. Good fortune. Remorse disappears. SINCERE joy. GOOD FORTUNE. REMORSE disappears. One's joy is sincere — coming from the heart without pretense. This sincerity brings good fortune and makes remorse disappear. 382. Sincere joy. The wise dragon advises you that joy from the heart, without pretense, eliminates remorse. Sincerity is the foundation of true happiness. Six in the third place means: Coming joy. Misfortune. COMING joy. MISFORTUNE. Joy that comes from outside — from external sources — brings misfortune. One depends on others for happiness rather than generating it from within. This dependency leads to suffering. 383. External joy. The wise dragon advises you that joy dependent on external sources leads to misfortune. True joy must arise from within. Nine in the fourth place means: Joy that is weighed and deliberated is not at peace. After ridding oneself of mistakes, one has joy. Joy that is WEIGHED and DELIBERATED is NOT at PEACE. After RIDDING oneself of MISTAKES, one has JOY. One deliberates about joy — trying to analyze and control it. This prevents peace. But when one rids oneself of mistakes — of what blocks natural joy — joy returns spontaneously. 384. Natural joy. The wise dragon advises you not to overanalyze joy. Remove what blocks it and let it flow naturally. Nine in the fifth place means: One is sincere toward the disintegrating. One is dangerously close to the small person. One is SINCERE toward the DISINTEGRATING. One is DANGEROUSLY CLOSE to the SMALL PERSON. One shows sincerity even toward those who are disintegrating — those who are declining. This puts one dangerously close to the small person. Compassion is admirable but must be balanced with discernment. 385. Discerning compassion. The wise dragon advises you to balance compassion with discernment. Being kind to those who decline can draw you into their decline. At the top a six means: Seductive joy. SEDUCTIVE joy. Joy that seduces — that tempts one away from the right path with the promise of pleasure. This is the lowest form of joy — the joy that corrupts rather than uplifts. One must recognize and reject seductive joy. 386. Seductive joy. The wise dragon advises you to distinguish between joy that uplifts and joy that seduces. True joy elevates; false joy corrupts."],
  [59,"Dispersion",["dissolution", "reunification", "obstacles", "flow", "temple"],"Dispersion. Success. The king approaches his temple. It is favorable to cross the great water. It is favorable to persevere. DISPERSION. SUCCESS. The KING approaches his TEMPLE. It is FAVORABLE to CROSS the GREAT WATER. It is FAVORABLE to PERSEVERE. The wind over water — the wind blows over the water, dispersing it into waves and mist. This represents the dissolution of rigid barriers and selfish separations. The text is similar to Gathering Together (hexagram 45). In that hexagram, the subject gathers what has been separated. In this one, the subject disperses and dissolves the egoism that separates. Religious forces are needed to overcome the selfishness that divides people.","The wind passes over the water: The image of Dispersion. Thus the kings of old made offerings to the Lord and established temples. The wind passes over the water — it disperses and dissolves. The ancient kings, observing this, made offerings to the Lord and established temples. The communal religious experience dissolves the barriers between individuals. When people gather in shared worship, their separate egos dissolve into a common feeling. Music and sacred ceremony create a powerful current of shared emotion that overcomes disunity. 387. Sacred dissolution. The wise dragon advises you that shared sacred experience dissolves the barriers between people. Community worship overcomes separation. ○ Initial six: They help one another with the strength of a horse. Good fortune. They HELP one another with the STRENGTH of a HORSE. GOOD FORTUNE. At the beginning of dispersion, one needs help — the strength of a horse. Others come to assist. This mutual aid in the time of dissolution brings good fortune. 388. Mutual aid. The wise dragon advises you that in times of dispersion, mutual aid is essential. Helping one another brings good fortune. Nine in the second place means: At the dissolution one hurries to the support. Remorse disappears. At the DISSOLUTION one HURRIES to the SUPPORT. REMORSE disappears. When dissolution begins, one hurries to find support — a safe place, a solid foundation. This swift action makes remorse disappear. 389. Swift support. The wise dragon advises you to seek support quickly when dissolution begins. Swift action prevents regret. Six in the third place means: One dissolves one's self. No remorse. One DISSOLVES one's SELF. NO REMORSE. One dissolves the ego — the separate self. This is the highest form of dispersion: the dissolution of selfishness itself. There is no remorse because what is dissolved is the source of all separation. 390. Dissolving the self. The wise dragon advises you that dissolving the selfish self is the highest form of dispersion. Letting go of ego brings no regret. Six in the fourth place means: One dissolves one's group. Supreme good fortune. Through dispersion one accumulates heights. What ordinary people would not think of. One DISSOLVES one's GROUP. Supreme GOOD FORTUNE. Through DISPERSION one ACCUMULATES HEIGHTS. What ORDINARY PEOPLE would NOT think of. One dissolves the limited group — the clique, the faction. This supreme good fortune allows one to accumulate heights that ordinary thinking cannot imagine. Breaking narrow loyalties opens universal possibilities. 391. Beyond the group. The wise dragon advises you that dissolving narrow loyalties opens universal possibilities. What seems impossible becomes achievable. Nine in the fifth place means: One disperses sweat. One disperses commandments. Dissolution of the accumulated. One disperses SWEAT. One disperses COMMANDMENTS. Dissolution of the ACCUMULATED. One disperses sweat — the physical effort of overcoming difficulties. One disperses commandments — the ruler's orders reach everywhere, dissolving barriers. What was accumulated — hoarded, held tight — is released. 392. Releasing the accumulated. The wise dragon advises you to release what has been hoarded. Sweat, commandments, and accumulated wealth all benefit from dispersion. At the top a nine means: One disperses one's blood. One departs, moves away, goes out. No blame. One disperses one's BLOOD. One DEPARTS, MOVES AWAY, GOES OUT. NO BLAME. One disperses one's blood — the most intimate substance. One departs from what has caused harm. This departure is not cowardice but self-preservation. There is no blame in removing oneself from what threatens one's life. 393. Life-preserving departure. The wise dragon advises you that departing from what threatens your life is not cowardice but wisdom. There is no blame in self-preservation."],
  [60,"Limitation",["limits", "moderation", "structure", "order", "economy"],"Limitation brings success. Bitter perseverance cannot be maintained. LIMITATION brings SUCCESS. BITTER PERSEVERANCE cannot be MAINTAINED. Water above the lake — the lake has a limited capacity. When water rises above it, the lake must either overflow or establish limits. This represents the principle of limitation — the necessary boundaries that make life possible. Without limits, everything dissolves into chaos. But bitter limitation — limitation that is too severe — cannot be maintained. The right limit is the one that is natural and appropriate, not the one that is imposed by force.","Water above the lake: The image of Limitation. Thus the superior person creates numbers and measures and examines the character of virtue. Water above the lake — the water is contained within bounds. The superior person, observing this, creates numbers and measures — the systems of counting and measuring that bring order to the world. And they examine the character of virtue — establishing the moral limits that guide behavior. Limitation is not merely restrictive but creative — it gives form and structure to what would otherwise be formless. 394. Creative limitation. The wise dragon advises you that limitation is creative, not merely restrictive. Numbers, measures, and moral boundaries give form to life. ○ Initial nine: One does not go out of the door and the courtyard. No blame. One does NOT GO OUT of the DOOR and the COURTYARD. NO BLAME. At the beginning of limitation, one stays within — not going out the door into the courtyard. This cautious limitation is without blame. One does not overextend. 395. Cautious limitation. The wise dragon advises you that cautious limitation at the beginning is wise. Do not overextend yourself. Nine in the second place means: One does not go out of the gate and the courtyard. Misfortune. One does NOT GO OUT of the GATE and the COURTYARD. MISFORTUNE. One fails to go out when the time requires action. This excessive limitation brings misfortune. There is a time to stay within limits and a time to go beyond them. 396. Excessive limitation. The wise dragon advises you that excessive limitation is as harmful as no limitation. Know when to step beyond your boundaries. Six in the third place means: One who knows no limitation will have cause to lament. No blame. One who KNOWS NO LIMITATION will have CAUSE to LAMENT. NO BLAME. One who has no limits — who spends, speaks, and acts without restraint — will eventually lament the consequences. But there is no blame in the person themselves — only in their failure to learn. 397. The cost of no limits. The wise dragon advises you that living without limits leads to inevitable lamentation. Restraint prevents regret. Six in the fourth place means: Contented limitation. Success. CONTENTED LIMITATION. SUCCESS. One accepts limitation with contentment. One does not chafe against boundaries but finds peace within them. This contented acceptance brings success. 398. Contented limits. The wise dragon advises you to accept limitation with contentment. Finding peace within boundaries brings success. Nine in the fifth place means: Sweet limitation brings good fortune. Going brings esteem. SWEET LIMITATION brings GOOD FORTUNE. GOING brings ESTEEM. The limitation is sweet — natural, appropriate, and willingly accepted. This is the ideal form of limitation — one that feels not like restriction but like the natural shape of things. Going brings esteem because the limitation is well placed. 399. Sweet limitation. The wise dragon advises you that the best limitations are sweet — natural and willingly accepted. When limits feel right, they bring good fortune. At the top a six means: Bitter limitation brings misfortune. Remorse disappears. BITTER LIMITATION brings MISFORTUNE. REMORSE disappears. The limitation is bitter — too severe, too restrictive. This brings misfortune because it cannot be maintained. But if one recognizes the error, remorse disappears. 400. The error of severity. The wise dragon advises you that bitter limitation cannot be sustained. Recognize when limits are too severe and adjust them."],
  [61,"Inner Truth",["sincerity", "trust", "inner truth", "influence", "openness"],"Inner truth. Pigs and fish bring good fortune. It is favorable to cross the great water. INNER TRUTH. PIGS and FISH bring GOOD FORTUNE. It is FAVORABLE to CROSS the GREAT WATER. Wind over the lake — the wind blows over the lake, touching its surface and creating resonance. This represents inner truth — the power of sincerity that reaches even the most hidden and insignificant things. Pigs and fish — the most common and obscure creatures — are moved by genuine inner truth. When one's heart is truly sincere, one's influence extends to all beings, even those hardest to reach.","Wind over the lake: The image of Inner Truth. Thus the sage deliberates on criminal cases in order to delay executions. Wind over the lake — the wind touches the water and creates resonance. The sage, observing this, deliberates on criminal cases in order to delay executions. Inner truth requires careful deliberation before passing judgment. The sage seeks to find extenuating circumstances, to delay the moment of irreversible judgment. This is the compassion that comes from genuine understanding of the human heart. 401. Compassionate judgment. The wise dragon advises you to deliberate carefully before judging others. Seek understanding before passing sentence. ○ Initial nine: Being prepared brings good fortune. If one has secret designs, one is restless. Being PREPARED brings GOOD FORTUNE. If one has SECRET DESIGNS, one is RESTLESS. At the beginning of inner truth, one is prepared and open. This brings good fortune. But if one harbors secret designs, one becomes restless — inner truth and hidden motives cannot coexist. 402. Openness vs. secrecy. The wise dragon advises you that inner truth requires openness. Secret designs create restlessness and destroy sincerity. Nine in the second place means: A crane calling in the shade. Its young answer it. I have a good goblet. I will share it with you. A CRANE CALLING in the SHADE. Its YOUNG ANSWER it. I have a GOOD GOBLET. I will SHARE it with you. The crane calls from the shade and its young answer — resonance through inner truth. Even at a distance, sincerity creates connection. The good goblet shared represents the communion that inner truth makes possible. 403. Resonance through truth. The wise dragon advises you that inner truth creates resonance across any distance. Sincerity connects hearts naturally. Six in the third place means: One finds a comrade. Now one beats the drum, now one stops. Now one sobs, now one sings. One FINDS a COMRADE. Now one BEATS the DRUM, now one STOPS. Now one SOBS, now one SINGS. One finds a comrade but the relationship is unstable — alternating between drumming and stopping, sobbing and singing. Inner truth has not yet stabilized the connection. 404. Unstable connection. The wise dragon advises you that connections based on inner truth may be unstable at first. Patience is needed for the relationship to mature. Six in the fourth place means: The moon nearly at the full. The horse partner disappears. No blame. The MOON nearly at the FULL. The HORSE PARTNER disappears. NO BLAME. The moon is nearly full — approaching maximum illumination. The horse partner disappears — the companion of the journey goes away. But there is no blame because inner truth provides what external companionship cannot. 405. Inner sufficiency. The wise dragon advises you that inner truth provides sufficiency even when companions depart. The nearly full moon illuminates from within. Nine in the fifth place means: Possessing truth, one links together. No blame. Possessing TRUTH, one LINKS TOGETHER. NO BLAME. One possesses inner truth and uses it to link people together. This is the social function of sincerity — it creates bonds that hold the community together. There is no blame because the linking is genuine. 406. Truth that links. The wise dragon advises you that inner truth has the power to link people together. Genuine sincerity creates lasting bonds. At the top a nine means: Cockcrow penetrates to heaven. Perseverance brings misfortune. COCKCROW penetrates to HEAVEN. PERSEVERANCE brings MISFORTUNE. The cockcrow reaches heaven — the sound of inner truth rises to the highest point. But if one perseveres in this excessive expression, misfortune follows. Even truth must know its limits. 407. The limit of expression. The wise dragon advises you that even inner truth must not be expressed to excess. Know when to be silent."],
  [62,"Preponderance of the Small",["modesty", "small actions", "care", "adaptation", "measure"],"Preponderance of the small. Success. Perseverance is favorable. Small things may be done; great things should not be done. The small bird brings the message: It is not good to strive upward. It is good to remain below. Great good fortune. SMALL EXCESS. SUCCESS. PERSEVERANCE is FAVORABLE. SMALL THINGS may be done; GREAT THINGS should NOT be done. The SMALL BIRD brings the MESSAGE: It is NOT GOOD to STRIVE UPWARD. It is GOOD to REMAIN BELOW. Great GOOD FORTUNE. An exceptional modesty and consciousness of one's acts will surely be rewarded with success. But if a person is not to be wasted, it is important that they not assume a vainly submissive form but always behave with dignity. We must understand the demands of the time to find what compensates for the deficiencies and damages of the moment.","Thunder above the mountain: The image of Preponderance of the Small. Thus the superior person in conduct goes beyond the ordinary in reverence, in mourning goes beyond the ordinary in grief, in expenditure goes beyond the ordinary in thrift. Thunder above the mountain — the thunder is small compared to the mountain. The superior person, observing this, goes beyond the ordinary in small matters: exceeding in reverence, in grief, in thrift. These are not great deeds but small excesses in the right direction. The preponderance of the small is the preponderance of care, of attention to detail, of exceeding expectations in modest ways. 408. Exceeding in small things. The wise dragon advises you to exceed expectations in small matters. Extra reverence, extra care, extra thrift — these small excesses are the way. ○ Initial six: The bird meets with misfortune through flying. The bird meets with MISFORTUNE through FLYING. At the beginning, the bird tries to fly upward. This brings misfortune because the time is not for ascending but for staying below. The small bird should not try to fly like the great eagle. 409. Knowing one's limits. The wise dragon advises you to know your limits. The small bird that tries to fly too high meets misfortune. Six in the second place means: One passes one's ancestor and meets one's ancestor. One passes one's ruler and meets one's ruler. One does not act thus. One PASSES one's ANCESTOR and MEETS one's ANCESTOR. One PASSES one's RULER and MEETS one's RULER. One does NOT act THUS. One goes beyond what is expected — passing the ancestor to meet the ancestor, passing the ruler to meet the ruler. This is exceeding in the right way — going beyond form to reach essence. But one must not act on this — it must be experienced, not performed. 410. Beyond form. The wise dragon advises you that exceeding in the right way means going beyond form to reach essence. But this cannot be performed — only lived. Nine in the third place means: If one is not extremely careful, someone may come up from behind and strike one. Misfortune. If one is NOT EXTREMELY CAREFUL, someone may COME UP from BEHIND and STRIKE one. MISFORTUNE. One must be extremely careful. In the time of preponderance of the small, carelessness invites attack from unexpected quarters. 411. Extreme care. The wise dragon advises you to be extremely careful in times of small excess. Carelessness invites unexpected attack. Nine in the fourth place means: No blame. One meets them. Going brings danger. One must be warned. Do not act. Be constantly persevering. NO BLAME. One MEETS them. GOING brings DANGER. One must be WARNED. Do NOT ACT. Be CONSTANTLY PERSEVERING. One meets the situation without blame. But going forward brings danger. One must be warned: do not act, but remain constantly persevering. 412. Warned stillness. The wise dragon advises you to remain still when warned. Constant perseverance is more effective than premature action. Six in the fifth place means: Dense clouds, no rain from our western territory. DENSE CLOUDS, no RAIN from our WESTERN TERRITORY. Dense clouds gather but no rain falls. The tension builds but does not release. One must wait for the rain to come in its own time. 413. Unreleased tension. The wise dragon advises you that tension that does not release must be endured with patience. The rain will come in its own time. At the top a six means: One passes them by. One is not meeting them. The flying bird leaves them. Misfortune. This means bad luck and injury. One PASSES them BY. One is NOT MEETING them. The FLYING BIRD LEAVES them. MISFORTUNE. This means BAD LUCK and INJURY. One passes by the opportunity and does not meet it. The bird flies away. This is the misfortune of missing the moment — of not being present when the small opportunity presented itself. 414. The missed moment. The wise dragon advises you not to miss small opportunities. Passing by the moment brings misfortune and injury."],
  [63,"After Completion",["completion", "success", "prudence", "maintenance", "care"],"After completion. Success in small things. Perseverance is favorable. At first good fortune; in the end disorder. AFTER COMPLETION. SUCCESS in SMALL THINGS. PERSEVERANCE is FAVORABLE. At FIRST GOOD FORTUNE; in the END DISORDER. Water over fire — water in the pot above fire below. The elements are in relation and generate energy — steam, cooking, transformation. Everything is in its proper place. The transition from the old to the new has already occurred. Everything is in order. But this very perfection contains the seed of disorder. When everything is complete, the only direction left is decline. Therefore, success is found in small things and perseverance is essential.","Water over fire: The image of the state After Completion. Thus the superior person thinks about misfortune and arms against it in advance. Water over fire — the elements are in perfect relation. But this perfection is unstable. If the water overflows, the fire is extinguished. If the fire burns too hot, the water evaporates. The superior person, observing this, thinks about misfortune and arms against it in advance. At the moment of completion, one must already prepare for the decline that will follow. Vigilance at the peak prevents the fall. 415. Vigilant completion. The wise dragon advises you that at the moment of completion, vigilance is most essential. Prepare for decline while at the peak. ○ Initial nine: One brakes the wheels. One gets one's tail in the water. Without blame. One BRAKES the WHEELS. One gets one's TAIL in the WATER. WITHOUT BLAME. At the beginning after completion, one brakes the wheels — slows down immediately. One gets one's tail wet — like the fox that almost crossed but wets its tail. This caution is without blame. 416. Immediate caution. The wise dragon advises you to brake immediately after completion. Caution at the peak prevents the fall. Six in the second place means: The woman loses the curtain of her carriage. Do not run after it. In seven days you will get it. The WOMAN LOSES the CURTAIN of her CARRIAGE. Do NOT RUN after it. In SEVEN DAYS you will GET it. One loses something — the woman loses her carriage curtain. But one should not chase after it. In seven days it returns on its own. What is lost in the transition will be restored naturally. 417. Natural restoration. The wise dragon advises you not to chase after losses after completion. What is meant to return will return naturally. Nine in the third place means: The Illustrious Ancestor attacks the Devil's Country. After three years he conquers it. One should not use small people. The ILLUSTRIOUS ANCESTOR attacks the DEVIL's COUNTRY. After THREE YEARS he CONQUERS it. One should NOT USE small people. After completion, there is still work to do — the Illustrious Ancestor must conquer the Devil's Country. This takes three years of persistent effort. But one should not use small people for this task. 418. Post-completion work. The wise dragon advises you that after completion, work remains. Persistent effort is needed, but choose your helpers wisely. Six in the fourth place means: The finest clothes become rags. Be careful all day long. The FINEST CLOTHES become RAGS. Be CAREFUL ALL DAY LONG. The finest clothes become rags — what was perfect decays. One must be careful all day long, constantly attending to the maintenance of what has been achieved. 419. Constant maintenance. The wise dragon advises you that even the finest achievements decay without constant maintenance. Vigilance must be unceasing. Nine in the fifth place means: The neighbor in the east who slaughters an ox does not attain as much real happiness as the neighbor in the west with their small offering. The NEIGHBOR in the EAST who SLAUGHTERS an OX does NOT attain as much real HAPPINESS as the NEIGHBOR in the WEST with their SMALL OFFERING. The eastern neighbor makes a great sacrifice — an ox — but the western neighbor with a small offering achieves more real happiness. Sincerity matters more than scale. 420. Sincere smallness. The wise dragon advises you that a small offering given with sincerity surpasses a grand sacrifice given without heart. At the top a six means: One gets one's head in the water. Danger. One gets one's HEAD in the WATER. DANGER. One gets one's head wet — the fox that was almost across now submerges its head. This is danger — the completion has been lost at the very last moment. One must exercise the greatest care. 421. The final submersion. The wise dragon advises you that even at the very end, carelessness can destroy everything. The greatest danger comes at the moment of apparent completion."],
  [64,"Before Completion",["transition", "potential", "caution", "incomplete", "threshold"],"Before completion. Success. But if the little fox, having almost completed the crossing, wets its tail, nothing is favorable. BEFORE COMPLETION. SUCCESS. But if the LITTLE FOX, having almost COMPLETED the CROSSING, wets its TAIL, nothing FAVORABLE. Fire over water — fire above, water below. Their effects move in opposite directions and do not connect. The conditions are difficult. The task is great and full of responsibility. It is nothing less than leading the world out of confusion and back to order. But it is a task that promises success, for there is a goal that can unite the forces now oriented in different directions.","Fire over water: The image of the state Before Completion. Thus the superior person is careful in distinguishing the nature of things so that each finds its place. Fire above, water below — their natures pull in opposite directions. The superior person, observing this, is careful in distinguishing the nature of things so that each finds its proper place. Before completion, everything is not yet in order. The task of the superior person is to carefully distinguish what belongs where and to guide each element to its proper position. This is the work of bringing order from chaos. 422. Distinguishing natures. The wise dragon advises you to carefully distinguish the nature of each thing. Before completion, everything must find its proper place. ○ Initial six: One gets one's tail wet. Humiliation. One gets one's TAIL wet. HUMILIATION. At the beginning, before the crossing has even properly started, one gets one's tail wet. This is humiliating — a premature failure. The little fox was too hasty. 423. Premature failure. The wise dragon advises you not to be too hasty at the beginning. Premature action leads to humiliating failure. Nine in the second place means: One brakes the wheels. Perseverance brings good fortune. One BRAKES the WHEELS. PERSEVERANCE brings GOOD FORTUNE. One brakes the wheels — deliberately slows down. This perseverance in caution brings good fortune. Before completion, restraint is more valuable than speed. 424. Deliberate restraint. The wise dragon advises you to brake deliberately before completion. Caution is more valuable than speed. Six in the third place means: Before completion, attack brings misfortune. It is favorable to cross the great water. Before COMPLETION, ATTACK brings MISFORTUNE. It is FAVORABLE to CROSS the GREAT WATER. Attacking before the time is complete brings misfortune. But crossing the great water — undertaking the great passage — is favorable if done with the right approach. 425. Timing the attack. The wise dragon advises you that attacking before completion is misfortune. But the great passage, approached correctly, is favorable. Nine in the fourth place means: Perseverance brings good fortune. Remorse disappears. The shock is great, like charging against the Devil's Country. After three years, a great realm is rewarded. PERSEVERANCE brings GOOD FORTUNE. REMORSE disappears. The SHOCK is GREAT, like CHARGING against the Devil's Country. After THREE YEARS, a GREAT REALM is REWARDED. One perseveres through a great shock — like charging against a powerful enemy. After three years of struggle, a great realm is won. The long effort is rewarded. 426. Rewarded perseverance. The wise dragon advises you that long perseverance through great shocks eventually brings great reward. Six in the fifth place means: Perseverance brings good fortune. No remorse. The light of the superior person is true. Good fortune. PERSEVERANCE brings GOOD FORTUNE. NO REMORSE. The LIGHT of the SUPERIOR PERSON is TRUE. GOOD FORTUNE. One perseveres and achieves good fortune without remorse. The light of the superior person is true — genuine and reliable. This authentic light brings good fortune to all. 427. True light. The wise dragon advises you that the true light of the superior person brings good fortune to all. Authenticity eliminates remorse. At the top a nine means: One is trusted. No blame. If one wets one's head, one loses it. One is TRUSTED. NO BLAME. If one WETS one's HEAD, one LOSES it. One is trusted — the completion is within reach. There is no blame. But if one wets one's head — if one is careless at the very last moment — one loses everything. The crossing is almost complete. Do not lose it now. 428. The final moment. The wise dragon advises you that the final moment requires the greatest care. Trust has been earned, but carelessness at the threshold can lose everything."]
];
